json_ExchangePointScheduleBean.title: ExchangePointScheduleBean
json_ExchangePointScheduleBean.description:
Used to set times for making a pickup or delivery exchange inactive while keeping the transport in an enabled state.
For example, you could set a schedule to turn off the exchange for a few hours once a week to perform maintenance on a transport server.</br>
By default exchanges are active continuously. Schedules are added by day of the week and time of day.
For instance, if you select Monday 0:00 - 23:59, the exchange is on all day every Monday.
If you select Monday 8:30 - 11:30, the exchange is on from 8:30 to 11:30 a.m. and off all other times on Mondays.</br>
Times are expressed in 24-hour format: hh:mm or h:mm. Times are the time zone for your server.</br>
If you schedule down times for a pickup used by a community to receive messages from partners, you may want to inform partners when the transport is inactive.</br>
If you want an exchange to be active most of the time but turned off only some of the time, you may need many schedules specifying the daily times you want
the transport to be on or off. For example, to schedule a transport to turn off between 1 and 2 p.m. each Saturday, eight schedules are needed as follows:
six daily schedules calling for the transport to run continuously Sunday through Friday and two Saturday schedules, the first specifying the transport
is on from midnight to 1 p.m. and the second specifying the transport is on from 2 p.m. to midnight.</br>
Messages in queue when a transport turns off are suspended until the transport turns back on. For example, if a message is picked up from an application
while the transport for sending to a partner is turned off, Message Tracker reports the status for the message as "scheduled production."
When the transport turns on again, processing of the message continues. Similarly, retries and resends for messages are suspended while the transport is off,
but they resume at the point where they were suspended when the transport turns back on.</br>
To use schedules, make sure message backups are enabled for the affected transports.
Unless backups are enabled, messages in process when a transport turns off cannot be queued to resume processing when the transport turns on again.</br>
If you trade via the AS2 message protocol and request asynchronous receipts, your community cannot receive receipts from partners
when the sending transport is turned off. To avoid this, request synchronous receipts or schedule a transport to be off when no messages are in process.

addendaDocument.description: The document type of the addenda for the selected format and version.

addendaType.description:
Indicates the addenda format type to be specified, if NACHA files that include addenda (embedded documents)

useAddendaVersion.description: Specify if the addenda version is used for matching/selection. If this option is set to true, the field must match the defined (or empty) indicated value.

callerIdentification.description: Holds the caller's protocol identity (P13) and password requirements. <p/>

password.description: Get the user's password  to connect to the server.

hasCredentials.description: Returns if this FTP user has credentials. The user may not have credentials if credentials should be read from an external source.

passwordPolicyName.description: Get the password policy to assign to the user.

ftpSubDirectories.description: The FTP subdirectories associated with the user. A specific combination of user and directory can be associated with only one exchange.

subscribedPartners.description: The trading partners that belong to community

integrationDeliveries.description:
The transports set up to route messages to a back-end system. A community can have multiple integration
delivery exchanges.

tradingPickupExchanges.description:
The message protocols and transports partners use to send messages to the community and how the
community retrieves the sent messages. A community with multiple trading pickups gives partners
multiple avenues for sending messages.

defaultSigningCertificate.description: The default certificate for signing documents used by the community

defaultEncryptionCertificate.description: The default certificate for encrypting documents used by the community

defaultSslCertificate.description: The default certificate for use in authenticating SSL connections used by the community

pgpCertificates.description: Used to retrieve the URI to all the public PGP Certificates.

defaultPGPCertificate.description: Returns the URI to the default PGP certificate.

defaultUser.description: The default FTP account used by the FTP server.

deleteAfterDownload.description:
For delivery only
<p/>
Select this if you want the embedded server to delete files after they have been downloaded from it

deliveryFilenameMode.description:
This property is used when the trading engine delivers messages.

Ftp Delivery Filename Options:
  • Preserve original

    Select this option if you want original file names to be preserved when the trading engine delivers messages.
  • Auto generate

    If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine appends a number to the new file. For FTP and SFTP the appended number is hexadecimal, with the format: filename_c4.
  • Custom generate

    When this flag is used, the additional property userDefinedDeliveryFilename must be set.

duplicateFileNameMode.description:
We recommend using this option to prevent the trading engine from attempting to retrieve partially written files.There may be some specialized servers, typically running on mainframes, that support only part of the FTP protocol (RFC 959). In such cases you may have to take steps of your own to make sure collisions do not occur. Ftp Duplicate File Name Options:
  • Overwrite

    If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine overwrites the existing file.
  • Auto generate

    Automatically generate unique filenames
  • Append

    If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine appends a number to the new file. For FTP and SFTP the appended number is hexadecimal, with the format: filename_c4.
  • Custom generate

    When this flag is used, the additional property userDefinedDuplicateFilename must be set.

localPort.description:
The local port used by the embedded FTP server to listen for incoming connections.
The default value is 4021 for trading server and 5021 for application server.

modifyFtpServerDirectory.description: Enable subdirectory management on the client side.

userDefinedDuplicateFilename.description: Use items such as $filename$, $extension$, $timestamp$, $sequence$ and $filesequence$ one time.

emailAddress.description:
The email address of this SMTP user. Once created, it cannot be changed. The email address allows wildcards:
  • ? - matches any character
  • * - matches any characters occurring zero or more times
Examples: user@host.com; *@host.com; ??user@*.com.

enabled.description: The status of this user.

localPort.description: The port on which the embedded server listens for connection requests.

maxLingerTimeSeconds.description:
The amount of time in seconds the connection is kept open after it is closed.
A negative number (-1) indicates that the connection should not be kept open after it is closed

maxThreads.description: The maximum number of threads the trading engine can dedicate to the server.

minThreads.description: The least number of threads the trading engine must dedicate to the server.

restartableMinKiloBytes.description:
The minimum size of a file that triggers the system to continue the file transfer at the point where it was
interrupted before the connection was lost. The minimum size is in kilobytes. The system only resumes
transfers of files that meet this minimum. The system starts over the transfer of smaller files whose
processing is interrupted.

tempFileHoursToLive.description:
The number of hours the system retains a file whose transfer has been interrupted while waiting for the
connection to be restored, if restart attempts are made.
This temporary file enables the system to resume the transfer at the point where it was interrupted.

cipherSuites.description:
The specific cipher suites supported by the server. If empty, all cipher suites are supported by
default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain cipher suites.
The default order in the list is the preferred order of use.
<p/>
A cipher suite is a collection of security algorithms used in making connections via Secure Sockets Layer or
Transport Layer Security. For example, an SSL or TLS protocol requires signing messages using a message digest
algorithm. But the choice of algorithm is determined by the particular cipher suite being used for the
connection. Typically, you can select an MD5 or SHA digest algorithm.

ssl.description: Specify whether Secure Sockets Layer protocol is in use during connections. If this option is set to true, the server presents a certificate for verification. To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Specify whether the cipher suites supported by the server are stated, in order for you select the level of security that suits your needs and enables communicating with others who might have different security requirements.

For example, when an SSL connection is established, the client and server exchange information about the cipher suites they have in common. Then they communicate using the common cipher suite that offers the highest level of security. If they do not have a cipher suite in common, secure communication is not possible. If this option is set to false, all cipher suites are supported by default.

enableClientAuthenticatedSsl.description: Specify whether the partners certificate should be used for authentication when the partner connects to the server, when using SSL option is enabled. If this option is set to true, partners are required to present a certificate for identity verification trusted by the server before the delivery exchanges using this server allow the connection and you must add an authentication certificate for the partner. If this option is set to false, non-authenticated HTTPS is used.

certificate.description: Path to get the certificate for this server. <p/>

ackTimeout.description: If useAcceptAck is set to true, enter a timeout limit to how B2Bi will wait for the accept acknowledgement.

componentSeparator.description: Message component separator. Default value is ^.

countryCode.description: The country code for the specified HL7v2 agreement. The format is [ISO code]. For a list of codes see the Website for ISO (International Organization for Standardization): http://www.iso.org/iso/home.html.

escapeCharacter.description: Message escape character separator. Default value is \.

fieldSeparator.description: Message field separator. Default value is |.

messageControlIdGenerator.description: Generator identifier set for message control counter. Default value is $MsgId:9$.

repetitionCharacter.description: Message repetition character separator. Default value is ~.

security.description: MSH-0008 field is an optional field used to implement security features. If this exchange agreement requires specific security, enter the MSH-00008 code in this field.

sequenceNumberGenerator.description: Sequence number generator. Default value is $SeqId:9$.

subComponentSeparator.description: Message sub component separator. Default value is &.

useAcceptAck.description:
Select this option if you want the receiving application to send an acknowledgement code to indicate
the receipt of the message.

useNonDefaultSeparators.description:
If the exchanges defined in this agreement use messages with non-default separators, specify the required separator characters in the following fields:
  • Field separator
  • Component separator
  • Repetition character
  • Escape character
  • Sub-component separator

applyNegativeFiltering.description:
Specify whether the filter pattern is inclusive or exclusive.

If set to false it is inclusive, only files matching the pattern are consumed. If set to true it is exclusive, files matching the pattern are ignored, but all other files are consumed.
Note: This field is used only in integration

cipherSuites.description: List with cipher suites.

deleteAfterDownload.description:
Select this if you want the server to delete files after they have been downloaded from it. This option should be enabled in most cases. If an external server automatically deletes files that have been downloaded, deselect this option.
Note: This field is used only in integration

duplicateFileNameMode.description:
We recommend using this option to prevent the trading engine from attempting to retrieve partially written files.There may be some specialized servers, typically running on mainframes, that support only part of the FTP protocol (RFC 959). In such cases you may have to take steps of your own to make sure collisions do not occur. Ftp Duplicate File Name Options:
  • Overwrite

    If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine overwrites the existing file.
  • Auto generate

    Automatically generate unique filenames
  • Append

    If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine appends a number to the new file. For FTP and SFTP the appended number is hexadecimal, with the format: filename_c4.

enableFiltering.description:
Enabling file filtering allows the trading engine to discriminate which files to consume based on file names
Note: This field is used only in integration

fileCollisionMode.description:
It is recommended to use this option to prevent the trading engine from attempting to retrieve partially written files. There may be some specialized servers, typically running on mainframes, that support only part of the FTP protocol (RFC 959). In such cases you may have to clear this check box and take steps of your own to make sure collisions do not occur. If connecting to a partner's Interchange embedded FTP server, use None. This property will be ignored if the filename handling is in append mode.

Options available:

  • NoneUse this option if the partner's server is an Interchange embedded server.
  • Use temp files with inbox

    Type the full path of an inbox directory (for example, c:\data\inbox). Files are uploaded to this directory. When fully written, files are moved to the pickup directory for retrieval. Do not put the inbox under the pickup directory unless you use a period at the beginning of the inbox name. The trading engine and other applications ignore directories and files that begin with periods. For example, do not use the following directory structure: c:\data\pickup\inbox But you can use the following because a period is the first character of the inbox directory name: c:\data\pickup\.inbox

    When this flag is used, the additional property inboxPath should be set.
  • Use temp file extension

    If you prefer not to use an inbox, select this option. While a file is being written to the pickup directory, a temporary extension is added so the system knows not to retrieve it because the file is only partially written. Once fully written, the temporary extension goes away and the file can be retrieved.

    When this flag is used, the additional property tempFileExtension should be set.

filterPattern.description:
Insert the format of the file names you want the transport to consume or ignore. Use conventional wildcard characters for file names or extensions or both. The following describes the supported characters and symbols:

*      One or more characters.

?      Any single character.

[ ]      Matches any single character within the brackets. For example, r[aou]t matches rat, rot and rut.

,      Commas can be used as and/or operators within brackets (for example, r[a, o,u]t).

-      Use hyphens within brackets to specify ranges of letters or numbers. For example, [0-9] is for any number between 0 and 9, and [A-Za-z] is for any upper- or lower-case letter.

.      Use the character dot to separate the file name and extension. For example, *.txt.

|      Use the pipe character to separate multiple file-name formats. For example, *.edi|*.txt|[a,b,c]?.xml.


Note: This field is used only in integration

host.description: The name of the SSH/SFTP server.

hostBasedAuthentication.description:
Whether or not server requires the SFTP client to use host based authentication By using this mechanism passwords no longer have to be transferred to the untrusted systems

Note: per-user SSH public keys can achieve similar effects; but maintaining per-user keys could be an unwanted administrative overhead

inboxPath.description:
Type the full path of an inbox directory (for example, c:\data\inbox). Files are uploaded to this directory. When fully written, files are moved to the pickup directory for retrieval. Do not put the inbox under the pickup directory unless you use a period at the beginning of the inbox name. The trading engine and other applications ignore directories and files that begin with periods. For example, do not use the following directory structure:
 c:\data\pickup\inbox
But you can use the following because a period is the first character of the inbox directory name:
 c:\data\pickup\.inbox

keyUserName.description: This user name applies to both public/private key pair and host-based authentication.

maxBlockSize.description:
The maximum size of the packets that can be downloaded from an external SFTP server by the SFTP client within the trading engine. The client downloads messages in a series of data packets. By default the maximum size is 32768 data packet units. The default value is compatible with most SFTP servers. But when handling messages of a certain size (2-3 megabytes or larger), some servers cannot process many packets of the default size and downloading hangs. If this occurs, reduce the packet size maximum.
Note: This field is used only in integration

metadataHierarchy.description:
Set message attributes that correspond to the names of subdirectories.
Each item in the selected attributes list represents another subdirectory level.
For example, add "From routing ID" and "To routing ID" to the selected attributes
list in that order. A message with attributes "From routing ID" set to "ABC"
and "To routing ID" set to "DEF" would be delivered to the subdirectory ABC/DEF.

overrideCipherSuites.description: If true a list of cipher suites should be provided.

passwordAuthentication.description: Whether or not server requires the SFTP client to authenticate using a password

pickupDirectory.description:
Path of the directory on your server where messages are
picked up. When the trading engine polls the server for files, it only looks in the pickup
directory, not an inbox directory. If connecting to a partner's B2Bi embedded FTP server,
use mailbox if picking up. Leave the field blank if delivering.

port.description:
The port on which the server listens for incoming connections.
The default is 22 (embedded SFTP default is for trading 4022/ for application 5022).

publicKeyAuthentication.description: Whether or not server requires the SFTP client to use public key authentication

readTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits to read data from the delivery exchange before terminating the connection.
The default is 30 seconds.

tempFileExtension.description:
If you prefer to not use an inbox, select this option. When a file is being written to the
pickup directory, a temporary extension is added so that the system knows not
to retrieve it because the file is only partially written. Once fully written, the
temporary extension goes away and the file can be retrieved.

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: The user name and its password to connect to the server.

jmsCredentials.description:
User name and password for the JMS provider. The user name and password can be the same as your JNDI user name
and password. This depends on your JMS provider and how it is configured.

jmsQueue.description:
The name of the queue.

Example: XMLQueue@router1.

jmsQueueConnFactory.description: The connection factory as defined within the JMS provider. This value can be either in the form factoryname@routername or the JNDI public symbol for the QueueConnectionFactory. This depends on your JMS provider and how it is configured. Examples: plainsocket@router1 or QueueConnectionFactory22.

jndiCredentials.description:
User name and password for the JNDI provider. The user name and password could be blank and are typically provided
in the JNDI URL. This depends on the JNDI provider and how it is configured.

jndiFactory.description:
The name of the JNDI service provider class.

Example: com.swiftmq.jndi.InitialContextFactoryImpl.

jndiUrl.description: The network URL used to obtain access to the JNDI service provider for your JMS service. Example: smqp://localhost:4001/timeout=10000.

maxMessagesPerConnection.description:
This value specifies the maximum number of messages to be consumed over a single connection before the connection
is closed and reopened on another processing node. As such, this setting effectively controls load balancing.

queueUtilClass.description: The name of the Java class for implementing the connection to the message queue. A Java class for Oracle AQ is available. The class name is: com.cyclonecommerce.tradingengine.transport.jms.OracleAQQueueUtil. If you want a Java class for a provider other than Oracle AQ, you need the help of a professional services consultant.

queueUtilParameters.description:
There are four parameters required for the Java class for Oracle AQ. These parameters must be in the following order:
  1. Host - the name of the computer running Oracle AQ
  2. Database name - the name of the database that contains the message queue
  3. Port - the port Oracle AQ uses to listen for messages
  4. Driver type - the type of JDBC driver for connecting to the provider. For Oracle AQ, the valid values are thin and oci8.

receiveTimeoutSeconds.description:
If your JMS provider is slow to respond to the request received from the trading engine, increase the response interval.
The default value of 0 is acceptable in the case of most JMS providers. However, if unacceptable for your
JMS provider, use trial-and-error to determine a workable interval between 1 and 32767 seconds.

useJndi.description:
Specify whether the JMS provider requires a Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) implementation.
For example, Oracle Advanced Queuing facility (Oracle AQ) does not use a JNDI provider.

useTransactedQueue.description: Set this option to true if the provider is Oracle AQ. Otherwise, set it to false.

readTimeoutSeconds.description: Time in seconds the trading engine waits to read data from the delivery exchange before terminating the connection.

connectTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits for a connection to the delivery exchange before the attempt times out.
Although the default value is 30 seconds, this may be longer than the interval allowed by your operating system.
For example, Windows XP by default allows a maximum timeout of 20 seconds. The actual connect timeout interval
is the lesser of the operating system timeout and the value set in the trading engine.

responseTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits for the delivery exchange to respond to a request before terminating the
connection.

cipherSuites.description:
The specific cipher suites supported by the server. If empty, all cipher suites are supported by
default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain cipher suites.
The default order in the list is the preferred order of use.
<p/>
A cipher suite is a collection of security algorithms used in making connections via Secure Sockets Layer or
Transport Layer Security. For example, an SSL or TLS protocol requires the signing of messages using a message digest
algorithm. The choice of algorithm is determined by the particular cipher suite being used for the
connection. Typically, you can select an MD5 or SHA digest algorithm.

ssl.description: Specify whether Secure Sockets Layer protocol is in use during connections. If this option is set to true, the server presents a certificate for verification. To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Specify whether the cipher suites supported by the server are stated, in order for you select the level of security that suits your needs and enables communicating with others who might have different security requirements.

For example, when an SSL connection is established, the client and server exchange information about the cipher suites they have in common. Then they communicate using the common cipher suite that offers the highest level of security. If they do not have a cipher suite in common, secure communication is not possible. If this option is set to false, all cipher suites are supported by default.

defaultEncryptionCertificateId.description: The default certificate id for encrypting documents used by the community

defaultPGPCertificateId.description: Returns the default PGP certificate of this partner.

defaultSigningCertificateId.description: The default certificate id for signing documents used by the community

defaultSshKeyId.description: Default ssh key used by this community

defaultSslCertificateId.description: The default certificate id for use in authenticating SSL connections used by the community

processingMode.description:
Processing mode to use for X12 message handling:

  • ISA_AND_GS (default)

    Select this option to enable the handling of complete X12 messages (including ISA headers).

  • GS_ONLY (X12 only)

    Select this option to enable the handling of X12 messages without ISA headers.

interchangeSenderIdQualifier.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The qualifier for designating the system or method of information code structure used to designate the sender ID element being qualified (ISA05). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

interchangeReceiverIdQualifier.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The qualifier for designating the system or method of information code structure to designate the receiver ID element being qualified (ISA07). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

interchangeSenderId.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The information code published by the sender for other parties to use as the receiver ID to route data to them (ISA06). When you are sending, the sender uses this as its sending ID. Other parties sending to you use this as a receiving ID route data to them. This is an interchange envelope parameter.

interchangeReceiverId.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The information code published by the receiver of the data (ISA08). This is an interchange envelope parameter. This is an interchange envelope parameter.

applicationSenderId.description: A code identifying the sender (GS02) of the message. The trading partners agree upon the codes to use. This is a functional group parameter.

applicationReceiverId.description: A code identifying the receiver (GS03) of the message. The trading partners agree upon the codes to use. This is a functional group parameter.

x12TestIndicator.description:
A code (T, I or P) indicating whether data in the interchange envelope is for testing or production
(ISA15). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

groupAgreements.description: List with all functional groups for current agreement

host.description: The name of the FTP server. <p/>

port.description: The port on which the server listens for incoming connections. The default is 21. <p/>

pickupDirectory.description:
The path of the directory on your server where messages are picked up. When the trading engine polls the
server for files, it only looks in the pickup directory, not in an inbox directory. <p/>

connectTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits for a connection to the delivery exchange before the attempt times out.
Although the default value is 30 seconds, this may be longer than the interval allowed by your operating
system (OS) . The actual connect timeout interval is the lesser of the OS timeout and the value set in the trading
engine.  <p/>

readTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits to read data from the delivery exchange before terminating the connection.
The default is 30 seconds.  <p/>

passive.description:
If set to true, files are transmitted using passive mode. In this mode, during the connection, the server
specifies the port it will listen to for the data connection. If set to false, files are transmitted using
active mode.  <p/>

transferType.description:
Select the format of the files that are transmitted over this delivery:

  • ASCII_AUTO_LF

    ASCII - automatic line ending

  • ASCII_CR_LF

    ASCII - user CR/LF

  • ASCII_CR_ONLY

    ASCII - use CR only

  • BINARY

    Binary (default). In most cases, use binary mode. Always trade packaged files (for example, AS2, AS3, Secure file) in binary mode.

If the receiver requires a particular line-ender, select an ASCII option to have the trading engine translate the line-ender based on what is required by the back-end system. The FTP specification requires the sender to always use CRLF as the line-ender when transmitting files in ASCII mode. It is up to the receiver to translate the line-ender to something else if desired.

commandSetConfigPath.description:
The FTP command set file controls the commands sent to the FTP server for operations such as send, receive, delete.
The default command set file is ftpcommandset.xml. This field lets you specify a different command set file.  Changing
this is only for advanced FTP users with specialized needs. The  field value is the name of an entry in
filereg.xml in [install directory]\conf that points to another file in the conf directory. <p/>

attemptRestarts.description:
Indicates whether the system resumes transferring large files at the interruption point, when a connection is lost
before a transfer is completed. If selected, the system resumes the processing of files that are at least as
large as specified in the restartable minimum bytes field. This checkpoint-restart feature is worthwhile only for
large documents. If this option is not used, the system starts a file transfer over when processing is interrupted. <p/>

restartableMinKiloBytes.description:
If attempt restarts is selected, the minimum size of a file that triggers the system to continue the file transfer
at the point interrupted before the connection was lost. The minimum size is in megabytes. The system only resumes
transfers of files that meet this minimum. The system starts over the transfer of smaller files whose processing is
interrupted. <p/>

tempFileHoursToLive.description:
If attempt restarts is selected, how long the system retains a file whose transfer has been interrupted while
waiting for the connection to be restored. This temporary file enables the system to resume the transfer at the
point interrupted. <p/>

userCommands.description:
Enter user commands such as SITE to be sent to the server after login. <p/>
Commands must be entered in the exact case and format expected by the server. Consult RFC 959 for a list of standard
FTP commands.  You can use FTP commands that do not make use of the FTP data connection. Commands that make use
of the FTP data connection are not supported. <p/>
If any command fails, the remaining commands are not executed, and production to the FTP server fails. To avoid
possible failures, preface any command with an "at" sign (@) to indicate that errors from that command should be
ignored, for example, "@MKD test". Preface any command with an asterisk to cause the entire line to be treated as
a comment, for example, "*Create test directory".  <p/>

fileCollisionMode.description:
Defines the use of temporary files to avoid read/write collisions. It is recommended to use USE_TEMP_FILES_WITH_INBOX or USE_TEMP_FILE_EXTENSION to prevent the trading engine from attempting to retrieve partially written files.

  • USE_USE_NONE

    Temporary files will not be used in order to avoid read/write collisions.

  • USE_TEMP_FILES_WITH_INBOX

    Use separate directory for temporary files. When receiving files from a partner, we recommend that your partner write files to the inbox directory first and then move them to the pickup directory when they are ready to be retrieved. This process is automatic if your partner also uses Axway products B2Bi, Interchange or Activator. If the partner uses other software to upload files to your server, the software should be configured to initially upload the files to the inbox directory and move them to the pickup directory when they are ready to be retrieved. The trading engine writes to the inbox and then moves the message to the pickup directory.

  • USE_TEMP_FILE_EXTENSION

    Use special extension in pickup directory for temporary files. If you prefer not to use an inbox, select this option. While a file is being written to the pickup directory, a temporary extension is added so the system knows not to retrieve it because the file is only partially written. Once fully written, the temporary extension goes away and the file can be retrieved.

inboxPath.description:
Type the full path of an inbox directory (for example, c:\data\inbox). Files are uploaded to this directory.
When fully written, files are moved to the pickup directory for retrieval. <p/>

tempFileExtension.description:
Used when File Collision Mode is set to USE_TEMP_FILE_EXTENSION. Specify a temporary extension to be added to the
file while it is being written to the pickup directory. Once fully written, the temporary extension goes away and
the file can be retrieved. <p/>

metadataHierarchy.description:
You can use metadata hierarchy to avoid file name collisions by selecting message attributes that correspond to
the names of subdirectories. Each item added represents another subdirectory level. For example, add
"From routing ID" and "To routing ID" to the selected attributes list in that order. Then, place a message in a
subdirectory named "ABC/DEF". The message will be assigned a "From routing ID" attribute set to "ABC" and a "To
routing ID" set to "DEF".  <p/>

cipherSuites.description: List of cipher suites to be used. <p/>

ssl.description: Select this option if you must connect to this server using SSL.<p/>

implicitSsl.description:
Use implicit SSL. Select this if you want to use implicit SSL rather than explicit SSL, which is the default mode. FTP supports two methods to accomplish security through a sequence of commands passed between two computers. The sequence is initiated with explicit (active) or implicit (passive) security.

  • Explicit security. To establish the SSL link, explicit security requires the FTP client to issue a specific command to the FTP server after establishing a connection. The default FTP server port is used.
  • Implicit security. Implicit security begins with an SSL connection as soon as the FTP client connects to an FTP server. The FTP server defines a specific port for the client to be used for secure connections.

enableHostnameVerification.description: Enable if you use host-based authentication with a Linux SFTP server. <p/>

overrideCipherSuites.description: Optionally, set to true in order to override the default cipher suites.  <p/>

deleteAfterDownload.description:
Select this if you want the server to delete files after they have been downloaded from it. This option should be
enabled in most cases. If an external server automatically deletes files that have been downloaded, deselect this
option.  <p/>

applyNegativeFiltering.description:
Specify whether the filter pattern is inclusive or exclusive. <p/>
If set to false it is inclusive, only files matching the pattern are consumed. If set to true it is exclusive,
files matching the pattern are ignored, but all other files are consumed.  <p/>

enableFiltering.description:
Enabling file filtering allows the trading engine to discriminate which
files to consume based on file names.  <p/>

filterPattern.description:
Insert the format of the file names you want the transport
to consume or ignore. Use conventional wildcard characters for file names or
extensions or both. The following describes the supported characters and symbols:
<p/> <hr/>
*      One or more characters.<p/><hr/>
?      Any single character.<p/><hr/>
[ ]      Matches any single character within the brackets. For example, r[aou]t
matches rat, rot and rut.<p/><hr/>
,      Commas can be used as and/or operators within brackets (for example, r[a,
o,u]t). <p/><hr/>
-      Use hyphens within brackets to specify ranges of letters or numbers. For
example, [0-9] is for any number between 0 and 9, and [A-Za-z] is for any
upper- or lower-case letter. <p/><hr/>
.      Use the character dot to separate the file name and extension. For example,
*.txt.<p/><hr/>
|      Use the pipe character to separate multiple file-name formats. For example,
*.edi|*.txt|[a,b,c]?.xml.<p/>

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: The username and the password required to connect to the server.  <p/>

sequenced.description:
Set this option to true if you want all messages that are consumed by this pickup to be delivered in their
original consumption order. <p/>

sequenceTimeoutSeconds.description: Value of sequence timeout in seconds. <p/>

ftpProcessingMode.description: Set the mode how the files are poll from the FTP server.

maxMessagesPerConnection.description:
This value specifies the maximum number of messages to be consumed over a single connection before the connection
is closed and reopened on another processing node. As such, this setting effectively controls load balancing. The
default setting of 1 achieves optimal load balancing at the cost of greater overhead per message. Depending on your
message volume and the load on each node, this value could be increased to avoid the overhead associated with
reconnecting to the transport server, at the cost  of a less well-balanced cluster.

json_InvalidRequestException.title: InvalidRequestException
json_InvalidRequestException.description: Exception that maps to HTTP 400 return code

cipherSuites.description:
The specific cipher suites supported by the server. If empty, all cipher suites are supported by
default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain cipher suites.
The default order in the list is the preferred order of use.
<p/>
A cipher suite is a collection of security algorithms used in making connections via Secure Sockets Layer or
Transport Layer Security. For example, an SSL or TLS protocol requires signing messages using a message digest
algorithm. But the choice of algorithm is determined by the particular cipher suite being used for the
connection. Typically, you can select an MD5 or SHA digest algorithm.

connectTimeoutSeconds.description: Time in seconds the trading engine waits for a connection to the delivery exchange before the attempt times out.

enableHostnameVerification.description: If TLS is enabled for connecting to the server, you can optionally select this additional security feature.

endBlockCharacter.description:
The decimal byte value to use for the end block character. Start and stop block characters enclose the message
data that is sent or received in through MLLP messages. At runtime B2Bi converts this decimal value to hexadecimal.
Default = 28 (hexadecimal 1C). The default value is the customary MLLP value. You must use the same values for the
client and server sides of the MLLP exchange.

expectAcknowledgement.description: Select this option to keep the connection with the MLLP server open while waiting for acknowledgement.

host.description: The address of the MLLP server.

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Select the level of security that suits your need and enables communicating with others who might have different security requirements. For example, when an SSL connection is established, the client and server exchange information about cipher suites they have in common. Then they communicate using the common cipher suite that offers the highest level of security. If they do not have a cipher suite in common, secure communication is not possible.

If this option is set to false, all cipher suites are supported by default.

port.description: The server port for MLLP connections.

readTimeoutSeconds.description: Time in seconds the trading engine waits to read data from the delivery exchange before terminating the connection.

ssl.description: Set this to true if TLS is required for the client connection to the MLLP server.

startBlockCharacter.description:
The decimal byte value to use for the start block character. Start and stop block characters enclose the message
data that is sent or received in through MLLP messages. At runtime B2Bi converts this decimal value to hexadecimal.
Default = 11 (hexadecimal B). The default value is the customary MLLP value. You must use the same values for the
client and server sides of the MLLP exchange.

json_WebTraderPasswordChangeFailure.title: WebTraderPasswordChangeFailure
json_WebTraderPasswordChangeFailure.description: Use this class to show information about the password policies

useTestFlag.description: If true, testFlag will be used for detection / matching.

testFlag.description: Set this field to true if the agreement is for testing and not for production.

useSenderIdentification.description: Enable sender identification for detection/matching. </br> This is a read-only field.

useReceiverIdentification.description: Enable receiver identification for detection/matching. </br> This is a read-only field.

documentAgreements.description: List with all document agreements for current agreement.

recipientTransmisionReference.description: Receiver Reference (Out_ReceiverReference). Transmission reference ID of the receiver.

useApplicationReference.description: Enable application reference for detection / matching.

usePriorityCode.description: Enable transmission priority code for detection / matching.

useReceiverTransmissionCode.description: Enable receiver identification code for detection / matching.

useReceiverTransmissionName.description: Enable receiver identification name for detection / matching.

useSenderTransmissionCode.description: Enable sender identification code for detection / matching.

useSenderTransmissionName.description: Enable sender identification name for detection / matching.

useSyntaxRuleId.description: Enable syntax rule identification for detection / matching.

useSyntaxRuleVersion.description: Enable syntax rule version for detection / matching.

acknowledgementMode.description:
The option for sending acknowledgements. The following options are available for the acknowledgement mode:
  • NONE - Select this option to implement MLLP connections without acknowledgements.
  • MLLP - Select this option to enable transport-level acknowledgements for connections to this MLLP server.
  • SYNC_FROM_BACKEND Select this option if you want connections to this MLLP server kept open until an application acknowledgement is generated in the back end.

cipherSuites.description:
The specific cipher suites supported by the server. If empty, all cipher suites are supported by
default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain cipher suites.
The default order in the list is the preferred order of use.
<p/>
A cipher suite is a collection of security algorithms used in making connections via Secure Sockets Layer or
Transport Layer Security. For example, an SSL or TLS protocol requires signing messages using a message digest
algorithm. But the choice of algorithm is determined by the particular cipher suite being used for the
connection. Typically, you can select an MD5 or SHA digest algorithm.

enableClientAuthenticatedSsl.description: Specify whether the partners certificate should be used for authentication when the partner connects to the server using SSL. If this option is set to true, partners are required to present a certificate for identity verification trusted by the server before the delivery exchanges using this server allow the connection. You must add an authentication certificate for the partner. If this option is set to false, non-authenticated HTTPS is used.

endBlockCharacter.description:
The decimal byte value used to identify the end block character.
Start and stop block characters enclose the message data that is sent or received in through MLLP messages.
At runtime, B2Bi converts this decimal value to hexadecimal.
The default value is 28 (hexadecimal 1C).
The default value is the customary MLLP value.
You must use the same values for the client and server sides of the MLLP exchange.

localPort.description: The TCP port on which the embedded server listens for connection requests.

maxThreads.description: The most threads the trading engine can dedicate to the server.

minThreads.description: The least number of threads the trading engine must dedicate to the server.

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Select the level of security that suits your need and enables communicating with others who might have different security requirements. For example, when an SSL connection is established, the client and server exchange information about cipher suites they have in common. Then they communicate using the common cipher suite that offers the highest level of security. If they do not have a chipper suite in common, secure communication is not possible.

If this option is set to false, all cipher suites are supported by default.

ssl.description: Specify whether Secure Sockets Layer protocol is in use during connections. If this option is set to true, the server presents a certificate for verification. To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

startBlockCharacter.description:
The decimal byte value used to identify the start block character.
Start and stop block characters enclose the message data that is sent or received in through MLLP messages.
At runtime, B2Bi converts this decimal value to hexadecimal. The default value is 11 (hexadecimal B).
The default value is the customary MLLP value.
You must use the same values for the client and server sides of the MLLP exchange.

batchRejectionRule.description: The action to take when the batch is rejected.

expireDate.description: The date the public key expires.

keyAlgorithm.description: An algorithm identifier that specifies the public key crypto system this key belongs to and any associated key parameters, such as key length <p/>

keyId.description: The keyId is string identifier for the Public Key.

keyLength.description: Key length indicates encryption strength, the larger the number the stronger the key. <p/>

applicationAcknowledgement.description:
Option for returning acknowledgments to the application that sent the inbound message.
Possible options:
  • AR As requested
  • AL Always
  • NE Never
  • ER Error/Reject only
  • SU Successful completion only

documentServiceId.description:
The service used for acknowledgement processing. If there are not any services to select, configure the
service and pass it to this field.

ackEnvelopingMode.description:
Select this option if you want to use either a specific outbound agreement to determine the acknowledgement processing or the interchange IDs and application IDs of the incoming Hl7v2 document as values (reversed) for the acknowledgement back to the sender.
Possible options:
  • DEFAULT Select this option if you want B2Bi to use the message control ID of the incoming document.
  • OUTBOUND_AGREEMENT Select this option if you want to use a specific outbound agreement to determine the acknowledgement processing.

messageControlIdGenerator.description: Generator for message control counter. Default value is $MsgId:9$

outboundAgreementForAckEnvelopeId.description:
If you selected Generate acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements, and if you selected to
Use an Outbound Agreement for acknowledgement enveloping" above, select an outbound agreement that
provides the enveloping. If there are not any outbound agreements to select, add one and pass it to
this field.

overrideAckTransportReceiver.description:
Select this option if you want to identify a specific party as the receiving party of the
acknowledgement. Then use the Partner, Routing ID and Delivery fields to identify the partner and
associated delivery exchange.

ackTransportReceiver.description:
If you selected Generate acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements, and if you selected to
Use alternate delivery partner, select a specific party as the receiving party of the acknowledgement.

ackTransportReceiverRoutingId.description:

Use alternate delivery partner, select a specific Routing Id from the specific party selected as the
receiving party of the acknowledgement.

ackDeliveryExchangeId.description:
If you selected an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements, and you have multiple delivery
exchanges that are valid for this agreement, you can select a specific delivery exchange to handle the
delivery of the acknowledgements.

rejectionRule.description:
The condition for rejecting interchanges, selected from a drop-down list. Interchanges are rejected depending on where errors are found. For example, if there is an error in one transaction set, the whole interchange is rejected.
Possible options:
  • NONE (default)
  • ENTIRE_BATCH If any documents are stopped, reject entire batch
  • SAME_TYPE If any documents are stopped, reject documents of the same type
  • CUSTOM_TYPE If any documents are stopped, reject documents of the following types - If you select this option you must enter the document types in the Custom rules field.

customRejectionRule.description: If CUSTOM_TYPE rejection rule is selected, specify the document types to be rejected.

sequenceCheck.description:
The interchange control number for inbound messages is verified to be in sequence. So, for example, if
the user sets the next expected interchange control number to 123456, the system validates that the
next inbound document has an interchange control number of 123456. If the validation succeeds the field
is updated to 123457. If the validation fails, the out of sequence action is applied.

outOfSeqAction.description:
Action to take in case sequenceCheck field is true.
Possible options:
  • WARN_AND_PROCESS Allows an inbound document to be processed successfully, with a logged warning.
  • FAIL_AND_PARK Processing is halted and an error is logged.
  • IGNORE No action.

dupAction.description:
Sequence numbers are checked for duplicates by comparing to documents already received. If a duplicate is detected for an inbound document, the selected duplicate action is respected.
Possible options:
  • WARN_AND_PROCESS Allows an inbound document to be processed successfully, with a logged warning.
  • FAIL_AND_PARK Processing is halted and an error is logged.
  • IGNORE No action.

deliveryMethod.description:
The delivery method for this service. You can use one of the following values:
  • DELIVER_TO_PARTNER
    Select this option if the message is to be sent to a trading partner. This option is the default setting for the following document formats: MEC XML, XML, In-house and IDoc.
  • RETURN_TO_SENDER
    Select this option if you are creating a service to support Web Services or MLLP trading, and the service requires a return exchange to the originating party.
  • DELIVER_TO_APPLICATION
    Select this option if the delivery endpoint of the document exchange is a back-end application. This option is the default setting for the following document formats: EDIFACT, X12, VDA and TRADACOMS. If you select this option, you must also provide the target application for the document delivery.
  • CONTINUE_TO_NEXT_STEP
    Select this option if the message is to be sent to the next content-based processing after the processing steps specified in the service have been executed.
    Note: This option is for metadata services only.

exchangePointId.description: The ID of the Application Delivery used when DELIVER_TO_APPLICATION delivery method is selected.

id.description: The unique ID of this service output.

name.description: The name of the document service output.

outputType.description: The format of the document output from the initial component of this service.

host.description: The fully qualified domain name or IP address of the OFTP server.

port.description: The TCP port on which the server listens for connection requests. This field does not apply to OFTP V1 X.25.

SSID.description:
The start session identification (SSID) of the local or remote party. Trading partners exchange SSIDs to identify
each other in the protocol handshake and session setup.

backendGenerateReceipt.description: Specify whether the trading engine should pause before generating and sending EERPs (signed end-to-end responses) and NERPs (signed negative end responses). If this option is set to true, the trading engine waits for a back-end system to submit messages containing the correct metadata for generating EERPs and NERPs. If this option is set to false, the trading engine synchronously generates and sends EERPs and NERPs without waiting for the back-end system to respond.

creditCounter.description:
The number of consecutive data exchange buffers sent by the speaker before it must wait for a credit (CDT)
command from the listener. The credit value is only applied to data flow in the data transfer phase.
The speaker's available credit is initialized to SSIDCRED when it receives a start file positive answer (SFPA)
command from the listener. It is zeroed by the end file (EFID) command. After negotiation, the smallest size must
be selected in the answer of the responder or a protocol error aborts the session.

dataExchangeBuffer.description:
The length in octets of the largest acceptable data exchange buffer. The length includes the command octet,
but not the stream transmission header. After negotiation, the smallest size is selected. The value in this
field maps to the SSIDSDEB field in the SSID OFTP protocol command.

networkSettings.description:
The network settings for the embedded server referred by this exchange point. The following types are supported:
  1. TCP. Transmission Control Protocol is the basic communications protocol of the Internet.
  2. X.25. An ITU-T standard protocol suite for packet-switched wide area network communications.
  3. X.25 over ISDN (B-channel). Integrated Services Digital Network broadband channel supports data transfers over telephone networks

protocolVersion.description: The protocol version being used (1.3 or 1.4 for OFTP V1 and 2.0 for OFTP V2).

readTimeoutSeconds.description: The maximum number of seconds the server waits when reading data from a partner.

sessionPassword.description:
OFTP session password. If password verification is enabled before establishing a connection, this field is
mandatory. The password can be no longer than eight alphanumeric characters and is case sensitive.

useSessionPassword.description:
Specify whether a password verification is required before establishing the connection.
<p/>
If this is an exchange for receiving messages from a partner, your community presents this
password to the partner. The password is compared to the one the partner has stored for your
community.
<p/>
If this is an exchange for sending messages to a partner, the partner must present this password
to your community. The password is compared to the one your community has stored for the
partner.
<p/>
In either case, the passwords must match to establish the connection.

usePreferredNodes.description:
If there are one or more nodes for the trading engine, you can select one or more as the preferred nodes for consuming messages. If the preferred nodes are running, these are used to process messages. If the preferred nodes are stopped, work is distributed among the remaining running available nodes. Selecting preferred nodes lets you manage work distribution among nodes.

This option is available for integration pickup and trading delivery exchanges that poll for messages.

In general, this setting should not be used. Usually it is best to let the trading engine automatically determine which node should be responsible for initiating the polling of which exchange point. This setting is useful if you have a cluster that spans geographical locations and each location has its own local transport servers. In this situation, you would use this setting to ensure the exchange points associated with the transport servers are assigned to nodes in the vicinity of the transport servers.

pollingIntervalSeconds.description: Returns the interval in seconds the trading engine waits before polling for messages to retrieve.

maxMessagesPerPollingInterval.description: Returns the highest number of messages the system can retrieve each time it polls.

preferredNodes.description: Get the preferred nodes used to process messages. See usePreferredNodes.

functionalGroupId.description: (GS 479) Identifies a group of application related transaction sets.

identifierCode.description:
(GS480) Code indicating the version, release, sub-release, and industry identifier of the EDI standard being used,
including the GS and GE segments. If code in DE455 in GS segment is X, then in DE 480 positions 1-3 are the version number;
positions 4-6 are the release and subrelease, level of the version; and positions 7-12 are the industry
or trade association identifiers (optionally assigned by user); if code in DE455 in GS segment is T, then other formats are allowed.

receiverMessagingId.description: (GS 124) Identifies the party receiving transmission. This code is agreed to by trading partners.

responsibleAgencyCode.description: (GS 455) Identifies the issuer of the standard. This code is used in conjunction with GS 480 below.

senderMessagingId.description: (GS 142) Identifies the party sending the transmission. This code is agreed to by trading partners.

useFunctionalGroupId.description: Select this option if you want B2Bi to use a group of application related transaction sets at runtime.

useIdentifierCode.description: Select this option if you want that B2Bi to parse the version, release, sub-release, and industry identifier at runtime.

useReceiverMessagingId.description: Select this option if you want that B2Bi to parse the interchange receiver id value at runtime.

useResponsibleAgencyCode.description: Select this option if you want that B2Bi to parse the issuer of the standard at runtime.

useSenderMessagingId.description: Select this option if you want that B2Bi to parse the interchange sender id value at runtime.

cipherSuites.description:
The specific cipher suites supported by the server. If empty, all cipher suites are supported by
default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain cipher suites.
The default order in the list is the preferred order of use.
<p/>
A cipher suite is a collection of security algorithms used in making connections via Secure Sockets Layer or
Transport Layer Security. For example, an SSL or TLS protocol requires signing messages using a message digest
algorithm. But the choice of algorithm is determined by the particular cipher suite being used for the
connection. Typically, you can select an MD5 or SHA digest algorithm.

enableClientAuthenticatedTls.description: Specify whether the partner's certificate should be used for authentication when the partner connects to the server, when using TLS option is enabled. If this option is set to true, partners are required to present a certificate for identity verification.

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Specify whether the cipher suites supported by the server are stated, in order for you select the level of security that suits your needs and enables communicating with others who might have different security requirements.

For example, when an SSL connection is established, the client and server exchange information about the cipher suites they have in common. Then they communicate using the common cipher suite that offers the highest level of security. If they do not have a cipher suite in common, secure communication is not possible. If this option is set to false, all cipher suites are supported by default.

If you selected an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements, and you have multiple delivery exchanges
that are valid for this agreement, you can select a specific delivery exchange to handle the delivery of the
acknowledgements.

ackEnvelopingType.description:
Specify the acknowledgement enveloping type. The accepted values are:

  • DEFAULT

    • Select this option if you want B2Bi to use interchange IDs and application IDs of the incoming X12 document as values (reversed) for the acknowledgment back to the sender.

  • OUTBOUND_AGREEMENT

    • Select this option if you want to use a specific outbound agreement to determine the acknowledgment processing.

ackGroupCntrlNumberGenerator.description: Assigned number originated and maintained by the sender (GS 06).

ackGroupTimeFormat.description:
Select one of the following time formats:
  • HHMM
  • HHMMSS
  • HHMMSSD
  • HHSSMMDD

ackInterchangeCntrlNumberGenerator.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The data interchange information code control number. This is the starting value of unique identifiers for outbound messages. By default, the identifier increases by 1 for each additional message (ISA13). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

ackTransSetCntrlNumberGenerator.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

A control number assigned by the sender and stored in the transaction set header. The number must be unique in the functional group (ST02).

ackTransportReceiverId.description: If you selected an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements, and overrideAckTransportReceiver is set to true, select a specific party as the receiving party of the acknowledgement.

ackTransportReceiverRoutingId.description: If you selected an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements, and overrideAckTransportReceiver is set to true, select a specific Routing ID from the specific party selected as the receiving party of the acknowledgement.

bypassEdiProcessing.description:
If true, all inbound processing options will be ignored. By default, this option is set to false.

This option improves the performance of B2Bi when handling large interchanges. If you select this option, the trading engine handles incoming interchanges without unpacking the envelopes. The trading engine reads only the interchange header and transaction set header segment (ST). The entire interchange is sent to the map as a single message. Regular EDI logic is not applied. For this reason, no acknowledgements can be automatically generated and sent.

checkControlNumbs.description:
The interchange control number for inbound messages is verified to be in sequence. So, for example, if the user
sets the next expected interchange control number to 123456, the system validates that the next inbound document
has an interchange control number of 123456. If the validation succeeds the field is updated to 123457. If the
validation fails, the out of sequence action is applied.

checkGroupControlNumbs.description:
The group control numbers for inbound messages is verified to be in sequence. So, for example, if the user
sets the next expected group control number to 123456, the system validates that the next inbound document
has an group control number of 123456. If the validation succeeds the field is updated to 123457. If the
validation fails, the out of sequence action is applied.

compositeElementSeperator.description:
Enabled for X12 Group level processing mode.

Enter the character to use as the composite element separator (ISA16). The field uses a colon as the default value. Alternately, you can use a hex code.

dupAction.description:
The action to take for non-sequential interchange and group control numbers. Options are:
  • WARN_AND_PROCESS

    • Allows an inbound interchange to be processed successfully, but a warning is posted.

  • FAIL_AND_PARK

    • Processing is halted and an error is posted.

dupCheckControlNumbs.description:
Interchange control numbers are checked for duplicates, by comparing to interchanges already received. If a
duplicate is detected for an inbound interchange, the duplicate action is respected.

dupCheckGroupControlNumbs.description:
Group control numbers are checked for duplicates, by comparing to groups already received. If a duplicate is
detected for an inbound group, the duplicate action is respected.
