serverIdentification.description:
Holds the partner server's protocol identity (PI4) and password requirements.  <p/>
For Application Delivery you must then enter a specific identifier for PI4 if finalDestinationEnabled flag is set to false. This value must
correspond to the value used by the application to identify the server. <p/>

finalDestinationEnabled.description:
Use the final destination ID from the message - Set to true on an Application Delivery to have the trading engine
read pesit.finalDestinationId.out (which corresponds to PI62), and use it as PI4. When set to false on an Application
Delivery, the Remote Identification should have restrictedToId set to true and an identifier set. <p/>
This value should be false for Partner Delivery.

bufferSize.description:
Max data unit size in bytes (PI25): The largest chunk of data, in bytes, to be transferred at one time. For
high-speed networks, use the default 32700 bytes. This value is related to the client setting for record length.
<p/>
The value of this field must be the same or larger than the value of the record length field.

kbPerSyncPoint.description:
Intervals between sync points (Kbytes): Each time an amount of data equal to this value has been sent, the
client is expected to ask the server to confirm whether data totaling this value has been received. This represents
a check point in the progress of a file transfer. If a connection is lost before a file transfer has been
completed, the transfer resumes (upon restart of the transport) at the point of the last successful check point. <p/>
The default value is 1024 kilobytes (1 megabyte).  <p/>
This setting corresponds to the pacing setting in Axway Transfer CFT. <p/>

maxOutstandingSyncPoints.description:
Sync acknowledgement window: The number of check-point cycles that the client waits for the server to respond
to a request to confirm file-transfer progress. For example, if the value of Kb per sync point (pacing) is 1024
(1 megabyte) and the value of this field is 1, the client stops sending data after 1024 kilobytes unless the
server responds, although the transfer remains active.  <p/>
If this value is 2, the client keeps sending until 2 megabytes (1024 x 2) of data  are sent, and so on. <p/>
If the client's value for this field is 0 (zero), the client does not ask the server to confirm at intervals the
amount of data received.  <p/>
If the server's value for this field is 0, the server does not send confirmations at intervals of data received.
The default value is 3. In most situation this is the correct value. <p/>
This setting corresponds to the chkw setting in Axway Transfer CFT.

enableAcks.description:
Expect acknowledgments - this should be true if you expect the remote application or partner to send a receipt to
acknowledge receiving each message sent.  <p/>

supportNegativeAcknowledgement.description: If expect acknowledgements is enabled, set this to true to support negative acknowledgements. <p/>

fileName.description:
File name (PI12) - Name of the file, forced to uppercase at runtime. Often, the real name of the file is delivered in
in File label (customFilename).

customFilename.description: File label (PI37) - Logical name of the file. It is used when overwriteFileLabel is set to true. <p/>

serviceParam.description: Free text (PI99) - Any text string. Often it is used to transfer metadata. <p/>

fileType.description: The file type (PI11) - Some monitors use this. The default value is 0.  <p/>

dataEncoding.description:
Data encoding (PI16)

  • TEXT

    Used for ASCII files

  • BINARY

    Used for all other file types

recordFormat.description:
Record format (PI31). Select one of the following:

  • FIXED

    For fixed length records

  • VARIABLE

    For variable length records

recordLength.description: Record length (PI32) - Record length for fixed records, or maximum record length for variable records.  <p/>

priority.description:
Priority (PI17) - Select an option:

  • HIGH

    Highest priority

  • MEDIUM

    Default

  • LOW

    Lowest priority

compressionType.description:
Compression (PI21) - Controls the compression of the file during the transfer (compression on the fly). Select a compression method:

  • NONE

    No compression. (default)

  • HORIZONTAL

    Compresses the consecutive identical characters in the records.

  • Vertical

    Records are compared to one another and the consecutive identical columns are compressed.

  • BOTH

    Combination of the above two compression methods.

connectionTimeoutSecs.description: PeSIT Tc timeout. The time the caller waits for a connection acknowledgment from the server. <p/>

transferTimeoutSecs.description: PeSIT Td timeout. The time the caller keeps the connection open, waiting for another message to send.  <p/>

networkTimeoutSecs.description:
PeSIT Tr timeout. The time the caller waits for an expected and effective network disconnection, before forcing
it. <p/>

protocolTimeoutSecs.description:
PeSIT Tp timeout. The time the caller waits for the response of the remote, in the middle of a protocol action
(such as a transfer). <p/>

allocationSizePercentage.description:
Destination file size delta for transformed files (+/- in %) - If you configure an "on the fly" transformation,
you can use this setting to adjust the file size info sent with the PeSIT CREATE order. That is because the
"on the fly" transformation changes the file size while sending. If no transformation is configured, this value
is ignored.  <p/>

json_IsdnClientNetworkSettingsBean.title: IsdnClientNetworkSettingsBean

remoteNumber.description:
For ISDN, the partners ISDN number. If prefixes are required to access an external
line or an international number, include those in the number.

localNumber.description:
The ISDN number identifying the caller (the instance of the trading engine).
Depending on the telecom operators configuration, you must set this to your number
or let the telecom equipment fill it in for you.

remoteNUA.description:
The X.121 address of the partner if the call is to be routed over X.25.
If the call is established directly to the partners ISDN number,
this number may be optional depending on its access control configuration.

localNUA.description:
The X.25 address identifying the caller (the instance of the trading engine).
Complete this field if the call is routed over an X.25 network that requires
it or if the remote partner uses X.25 access control based on the originating address.

x25PacketSize.description:
The size of the X.25 packets to be sent over the network.
If the value is blank the networks default value is used.

x25WindowSize.description:
The number of X.25 packets that can be sent without acknowledgment.
If the value is blank the networks default value is used.

callUserData.description:
This value is passed to the X.25 connection request.
Depending on the configuration on the partners side,
this may be used to select the software responsible for answering the call.

json_IsdnClientNetworkSettingsBean.description: Integrated Services Digital Network broadband channel supports data transfers over telephone networks

sequenceNumberGenerator.description: Generator for previous document number. The default value is "$TransNumber:5$".

detectBGMContent.description: Select this option if you want to use this document agreement only on a specific BGM content type.

bgmDocNameCode.description: The BGM name code for which this document agreement is used. If detectBGMContent is true, this identification field will be used for matching/selection.

cipherSuites.description: List with cipher suites.

host.description: The name of the SSH/SFTP server.

port.description:
The port on which the server listens for incoming connections.
The default port for the SFTP server is 22 (embedded SFTP default for trading is 4022; for application 5022).

passwordAuthentication.description: Whether or not server requires the SFTP client to authenticate using a password

publicKeyAuthentication.description:
Whether or not server requires the SFTP client to use public key authentication.

If this exchange is for a community, add the private key to the community. If this exchange is for a partner, add the public key to any community that will be trading with the partner.

hostBasedAuthentication.description:
Whether or not server requires the SFTP client to use host-based authentication. By using this mechanism passwords no longer have to be transferred to the untrusted systems.

Note: per-user SSH public keys can achieve similar effects; but maintaining per-user keys could be an unwanted administrative overhead

keyUserName.description: This user name applies to both public/private key pair and host-based authentication.

pickupDirectory.description:
The path of the directory on your server where messages are picked up.
When the trading engine polls the server for files, it only looks in the pickup directory, not an inbox directory.

fileCollisionMode.description:
Use this option to prevent the trading engine from attempting to retrieve partially written files. There may be some specialized servers, typically running on mainframes, that support only part of the FTP protocol (RFC 959). In such cases you may have to clear this check box and take steps of your own to make sure collisions do not occur. If connecting to a partner's B2Bi or Interchange embedded FTP server, use None. This property will be ignored if the filename handling is in append mode.

Options available:

  • None Use this option if the partner's server is B2Bi or Interchange embedded server.
  • Use temp files with inbox

    Type the full path of an inbox directory (for example, c:\data\inbox). Files are uploaded to this directory. When fully written, files are moved to the pickup directory for retrieval. Do not put the inbox under the pickup directory unless you use a period at the beginning of the inbox name. The trading engine and other applications ignore directories and files that begin with periods. For example, do not use the following directory structure: c:\data\pickup\inbox. But you can use the following because a period is the first character of the inbox directory name: c:\data\pickup\.inbox

    When this flag is used, the additional property inboxPath should be set.
  • Use temp file extension

    If you prefer not to use an inbox, select this option. While a file is being written to the pickup directory, a temporary extension is added so the system knows not to retrieve it because the file is only partially written. Once fully written, the temporary extension goes away and the file can be retrieved.

    When this flag is used, the additional property tempFileExtension should be set.

inboxPath.description:
Type the full path of an inbox directory (for example, c:\data\inbox). Files are uploaded to this directory. When fully written, files are moved to the pickup directory for retrieval. Do not put the inbox under the pickup directory unless you use a period at the beginning of the inbox name. The trading engine and other applications ignore directories and files that begin with periods. For example, do not use the following directory structure:
 c:\data\pickup\inbox
But you can use the following because a period is the first character of the inbox directory name:
 c:\data\pickup\.inbox

tempFileExtension.description:
If you prefer to not use an inbox, select this option. When a file is being written to the
pickup directory, a temporary extension is added so that the system knows not
to retrieve it because the file is only partially written. Once fully written, the
temporary extension goes away and the file can be retrieved.

readTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits to read data from the delivery exchange before terminating the connection.
The default is 30 seconds.

deleteAfterDownload.description:
Select this if you want the server to delete files after they have been downloaded from it. This option should be
enabled in most cases. If an external server automatically deletes files that have been downloaded, deselect this
option.

maxBlockSize.description:
The maximum size of the packets that can be downloaded from an external SFTP server by the SFTP client within the trading engine.
The client downloads messages in a series of data packets. By default the maximum size is 32768  data packet units.
The default value is compatible with most SFTP servers. However, when handling messages of a certain size (2-3 megabytes or larger),
some servers cannot process many packets of the default size and downloading hangs. If this occurs, reduce the packet size maximum.

enableFiltering.description:
Enabling file filtering allows the trading engine to discriminate which
files to consume based on file names

filterPattern.description:
Insert the format of the file names you want the transport
to consume or ignore. Use conventional wildcard characters for file names,
extensions, or both. The following describes the supported characters and symbols:
<p/> <hr/>
*      One or more characters.<p/><hr/>
?      Any single character.<p/><hr/>
[ ]      Matches any single character within the brackets. For example, r[aou]t
matches rat, rot and rut.<p/><hr/>
,      Commas can be used as and/or operators within brackets (for example, r[a,
o,u]t). <p/><hr/>
-      Use hyphens within brackets to specify ranges of letters or numbers. For
example, [0-9] is for any number between 0 and 9, and [A-Za-z] is for any
upper- or lower-case letter. <p/><hr/>
.      Use the character dot to separate the file name and extension. For example,
*.txt.<p/><hr/>
|      Use the pipe character to separate multiple file-name formats. For example,
*.edi|*.txt|[a,b,c]?.xml.<p/>

sequenced.description:
Specify whether all messages that are consumed by this pickup should be delivered in their original
consumption order.
<p/>
In B2Bi message-handling, sequential delivery is the ability to deliver messages in the order they
were originally consumed on a specific pickup. This is sometimes referred to as first-in-first-out
(FIFO) behavior.
<p/>
Sequential message delivery is implemented only for trading engine pickups, not for integration
engine pickups

sequenceTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds that the trading engine waits for missing messages of a sequence before taking the appropriate action.
This feature avoids the blocking of processing when a sequenced message is not available. Default value is of
60 seconds.

encodedHostPublicKey.description: SSH/SFTP server's public key. If keyword is used, the key is automatically retrieved.

overrideCipherSuites.description: If true, a list of cipher suites should be provided.

metadataHierarchy.description:
Set message attributes that correspond to the names of subdirectories.
Each item in the selected attributes list represents another subdirectory level.
For example, add "From routing ID" and "To routing ID" to the selected attributes
list in that order. A message with attributes "From routing ID" set to "ABC"
and "To routing ID" set to "DEF" would be delivered to the subdirectory ABC/DEF.

maxMessagesPerConnection.description:
This value specifies the maximum number of messages to be consumed over a single connection before the connection is closed and reopened on another processing node. As such, this setting effectively controls load balancing. The default setting of 1 achieves optimal load balancing at the cost of greater overhead per message. Depending on your message volume and the load on each node, this value could be increased to avoid the overhead associated with reconnecting to the transport server, at the cost of a less well-balanced cluster.

This setting only applies to transports where a list of file names is not available. These include POP, JMS and (for Interchange stand-alone) the Synchrony Integrator exchange point, which is based on JMS. Exchange points such as these are limited to one connection at a time to prevent concurrency problems.

This field is not applicable in a single node environment.

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: The user name and its password to connect to the server.

privateKeyCredentials.description:
The user name, password and the private key used to connect to server.
This applies to both public/private key pair and host-based authentication

host.description:
The name of the POP server that the trading engine polls for messages sent by your partner. This must be a fully
qualified domain name or IP address.

port.description: The POP server port. By default this is 110.

connectTimeoutSeconds.description:
Connect timeout (seconds) - Time in seconds the trading engine waits for a connection to the delivery exchange
before the attempt times out. By default this is set to 30 seconds.

readTimeoutSeconds.description: Read timeout (seconds) - The maximum number of seconds the server waits when reading data from a partner.

authenticationType.description: Authentication type; must be set to 'USER_PASS' or 'APOP'.

senderIdentificationType.description:
Specify how the sender will be identified; must be set to 'PD_EMAIL_ADDRESSES' or
'PARTNER_EMAIL_ACCOUNTS'.

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: The user name and password required to connect to the server.

maxMessagesPerConnection.description:
Maximum number of messages to be consumed over a single connection before the connection
is closed and reopened on another processing node.

sequenced.description:
Select this option if you want all messages that are consumed by this pickup to be delivered in their original
consumption order.

sequenceTimeoutSeconds.description: Time limit to wait for missing messages of a sequence before taking the appropriate action.

cipherSuites.description: List with cipher suites.

ssl.description: Client use ssl to connect to this server ?.

enableHostnameVerification.description:
SSL authentication.  If we're acting as the client, true means we should verify that the
hostname for the certificate given to us by the server matches the host we connected to.
If we're acting as the server, true means we require the client to present its
certificate ("client authentication").

overrideCipherSuites.description: If true, a list of cipher suites should be provided.

partnerCode.description:
The partner code. For an outbound message, enter the sender ID. For an inbound message, enter the
receiver ID.

alwaysConsumeFromSubdirs.description: Specify what to do when partners upload messages to subdirectories of the SFTP directories. If this option is set to true, the users are allowed to write files to any subdirectory under the root path. Otherwise, the users are allowed to write files to a subdirectory under the root path only when a message attribute is set up for each subdirectory level.

defaultUser.description: Default account for the SFTP server.

localPort.description:
The local port used by the embedded SFTP server to listen for incoming connections. The default values are 4022
for a trading server and 5022 for an application server.

modifySftpServerDirectory.description: Specify whether subdirectory management is enabled on the client side. When this option is set to true, SFTP clients are allowed to add or remove subdirectories.

sequenceTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds that B2Bi waits for missing messages of a sequence before taking the appropriate action.
This feature avoids the blocking of processing when a sequenced message is not available. Default value is of
60 seconds.

sequenced.description:
Specify whether all messages that are consumed by this pickup should be delivered in their original
consumption order.
<p/>
In B2Bi message-handling, sequential delivery is the ability to deliver messages in the order they
were originally consumed on a specific pickup. This is sometimes referred to as first-in-first-out
(FIFO) behavior.
<p/>
Sequential message delivery is implemented only for trading engine pickups, not for integration
engine pickups

requiresSecureAuthentication.description:
For OFTP V2 only, this is an extra layer of security to enable senders and receivers to validate each other as genuine. There are two requirements to enable secure OFTP authentication:

  • Both the sender and receiver must enable secure OFTP authentication. If one party turns it on and the other party does not, a protocol error is generated and the session between the parties is disconnected.
  • Both the sender and receiver must be using certificates. These are the normal certificates used by a community and its partners to securely exchange messages. These are not TLS certificates, which are additional certificates needed if TLS is configured for a delivery exchange.
This is how the authentication works: The initiator of the connection uses the partners public key to encrypt and send a short, random message to the partner. The partner decrypts the message with its private key and sends the message back. The initiator compares the response to the original message. If the messages match, the initiator has authenticated the partner. The partner repeats the process to validate the initiator.

useDifferentAuthCertificate.description:
Set this to true in order to select a partner certificate to use for secure authentication other than the default
certificate. <p/>

secureAuthCertificateId.description:
The ID of the partner certificate used for secure authentication. This ID is shown only when another certificate
than the default one is used. <p/>

enabled.description: Returns if this FTP user is enabled.

ftpSubDirectories.description: The FTP subdirectories associated with the user. A specific combination of user and directory can be associated with only one exchange.

hasCredentials.description: Returns if this FTP user has credentials. The user may not have credentials if credentials should be read from an external source.

password.description: Get the user's password  to connect to the server.

passwordPolicyName.description: Get the password policy to assign to the user.

host.description: The address of the MLLP server.

port.description: The server port for MLLP connections.

connectTimeoutSeconds.description: Time in seconds the trading engine waits for a connection to the delivery exchange before the attempt times out.

readTimeoutSeconds.description: Time in seconds the trading engine waits to read data from the delivery exchange before terminating the connection.

startBlockCharacter.description:
The decimal byte value to use for the start block character. Start and stop block characters enclose the message
data that is sent or received in through MLLP messages. At runtime B2Bi converts this decimal value to hexadecimal.
Default = 11 (hexadecimal B). The default value is the customary MLLP value. You must use the same values for the
client and server sides of the MLLP exchange.

endBlockCharacter.description:
The decimal byte value to use for the end block character. Start and stop block characters enclose the message
data that is sent or received in through MLLP messages. At runtime B2Bi converts this decimal value to hexadecimal.
Default = 28 (hexadecimal 1C). The default value is the customary MLLP value. You must use the same values for the
client and server sides of the MLLP exchange.

expectAcknowledgement.description: Select this option to keep the connection with the MLLP server open while waiting for acknowledgement.

ssl.description: Set this to true if TLS is required for the client connection to the MLLP server.

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Select the level of security that suits your need and enables communicating with others who might have different security requirements. For example, when an SSL connection is established, the client and server exchange information about cipher suites they have in common. Then they communicate using the common cipher suite that offers the highest level of security. If they do not have a cipher suite in common, secure communication is not possible.

If this option is set to false, all cipher suites are supported by default.

cipherSuites.description:
The specific cipher suites supported by the server. If empty, all cipher suites are supported by
default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain cipher suites.
The default order in the list is the preferred order of use.
<p/>
A cipher suite is a collection of security algorithms used in making connections via Secure Sockets Layer or
Transport Layer Security. For example, an SSL or TLS protocol requires signing messages using a message digest
algorithm. But the choice of algorithm is determined by the particular cipher suite being used for the
connection. Typically, you can select an MD5 or SHA digest algorithm.

enableHostnameVerification.description: If TLS is enabled for connecting to the server, you can optionally select this additional security feature.

id.description: The unique ID of this service output component.

stepId.description: The current processing step to be configured.

type.description:
The type of the current processing step. This field can have one of the following four values:
  • Document
  • Post enveloping
  • Post transfer success
  • Post transfer failed

clientModeEnabled.description:
The MQSeries connection type. Two options are available:
  • true - select this option to use a channel connection on the local machine or via the network, to connect to a queue manager.
  • false select this option to use an API connection, via shared memory, to a local queue manager.

multiInstanceEnabled.description: Select this option if the server has an MQSeries multi-instance queue manager.

mqQueueName.description: The name of the MQSeries queue.

convertUsingCCSID.description: Set to true if you want to enable data conversion.

mqCharset.description: The character set for converting data.

segmentationSize.description: The message segmentation size in bytes.

useSsl.description: Use SSL to connect to the MQSeries server.

sslCipherSuite.description: The SSL cipher suite to use for SSL encryption.

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: User name and password to connect to the server.

keyId.description: The keyId is string identifier for the Public Key.

level.description:
A signer indicates a level of trust ranging from low to high.
For example, a self-signed certificate is by default signed
by the community that generated the certificate within B2Bi.
The community gives the certificate a positive level, which
is a high level of trust.

userName.description: The username refers to Community name and email

localPort.description:
The local port used by the embedded SFTP server to listen for incoming connections. The default values are 4022
for a trading server and 5022 for an application server.

subDirectories.description:
Subdirectories associated to the SFTP exchange point. A specific combination of user
and directory can be associated with only one exchange.

alwaysConsumeFromSubdirs.description: Specify what to do when partners upload messages to subdirectories of the SFTP directories. If this option is set to true, the users are allowed to write files to any subdirectory under the root path. Otherwise, the users are allowed to write files to a subdirectory under the root path only when a message attribute is set up for each subdirectory level.

modifySftpServerDirectory.description: Specify whether subdirectory management is enabled on the client side. When this option is set to true, SFTP clients are allowed to add or remove subdirectories.

sequenced.description:
Specify whether all messages that are consumed by this pickup should be delivered in their original
consumption order.
<p/>
In B2Bi message-handling, sequential delivery is the ability to deliver messages in the order they
were originally consumed on a specific pickup. This is sometimes referred to as first-in-first-out
(FIFO) behavior.
<p/>
Sequential message delivery is implemented only for trading engine pickups, not for integration
engine pickups

sequenceTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds that B2Bi waits for missing messages of a sequence before taking the appropriate action.
This feature avoids the blocking of processing when a sequenced message is not available. Default value is of
60 seconds.

defaultUser.description: Default account for the SFTP server.

metadataName.description:
The name of the message attribute used for attaching metadata to the messages the trading engine picks up
from applications or receives from partners.
<p/>
Attributes are name-value pairs whose values are extracted from messages through parsing or have
fixed values. The trading engine can parse only XML messages, but attributes with fixed values can
apply to EDI, XML or binary documents.
For example, you can have the system parse certain XML messages for values of an attribute named
POAmount. Or, you can instruct the system to apply an attribute named SupplyChain with a fixed
value of Retail to certain messages.

compareOperator.description:
Operator which specifies the relationship between the attribute name (metadataName) and the provided value (metadataValue). You can define attributes to be active only when certain conditions occur. This lets you customize attributes to a high degree of specificity. You can choose one of the following operators:
  • EQUALS - the operator tests whether an attribute exists and has a specific value
  • NOT_EQUALS - the operator tests whether an attribute exists, but does not match a specific value
Conditions cause payloads to be delivered to the appropriate application delivery. If a payload does not satisfy the delivery criteria for any application delivery, then the first available application delivery is used. An application delivery with no criteria is used only if it is the first one available.

metadataValue.description:
The value of the message attribute used for attaching metadata to the messages the trading engine picks up
from applications or receives from partners.

partnerCode.description:
The partner code. For an outbound message, enter the sender ID. For an inbound message, enter the
receiver ID.

resourceName.description: The name of the resource that provides the functionality for this component.

resourceAbsFilePath.description: The absolute file path for the resource that provides the functionality for this component.

resourceType.description: The type of the resource that provides the functionality for this component.

useInterchangeSenderIdQualifier.description: Select this option if you want that B2Bi to parse the interchange sender id qualifier value at runtime.

useInterchangeReceiverIdQualifier.description: Select this option if you want that B2Bi to parse the interchange receiver id qualifier value at runtime.

useInterchangeSenderId.description: Select this option if you want that B2Bi to parse the interchange sender id value at runtime.

useInterchangeReceiverId.description: Select this option if you want that B2Bi to parse the interchange receiver id value at runtime.

bypassEdiProcessing.description:
If true, all inbound processing options will be ignored. By default, this option is set to false.

This option improves the performance of B2Bi when handling large interchanges. If you select this option, the trading engine handles incoming interchanges without unpacking the envelopes. The trading engine reads only the interchange header and transaction set header segment (ST). The entire interchange is sent to the map as a single message. Regular EDI logic is not applied. For this reason, no acknowledgements can be automatically generated and sent.

generateAckRule.description:
The condition for sending acknowledgments. Options are:
  • NO
  • YES_NON_DETAILED
  • YES_DETAILED

serviceId.description:
The service used for acknowledgement processing. If there are not any services to select, configure the service
and pass it to this field.

ackEnvelopingType.description:
Specify the acknowledgement enveloping type. The accepted values are:

  • DEFAULT

    • Select this option if you want B2Bi to use interchange IDs and application IDs of the incoming X12 document as values (reversed) for the acknowledgment back to the sender.

  • OUTBOUND_AGREEMENT

    • Select this option if you want to use a specific outbound agreement to determine the acknowledgment processing.

outboundAgreementForAckEnvelopeId.description: If you selected an acknowledgment rule that generates acknowledgements, and ackEnvelopingType is set to OUTBOUND_AGREEMENT, select an outbound agreement that provides the enveloping. If there are not any outbound agreements to select, a warning message will be returned.

ackDeliveryExchangeId.description:
If you selected an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements, and you have multiple delivery exchanges
that are valid for this agreement, you can select a specific delivery exchange to handle the delivery of the
acknowledgements.

overrideAckTransportReceiver.description: Select this option if you want to identify a specific party as the receiving party of the acknowledgement. Then use ackTransportReceiverId, ackTransportReceiverRoutingId and ackDeliveryExchangeId to identify the partner and the associated delivery exchange.

ackTransportReceiverId.description: If you selected an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements, and overrideAckTransportReceiver is set to true, select a specific party as the receiving party of the acknowledgement.

ackTransportReceiverRoutingId.description: If you selected an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements, and overrideAckTransportReceiver is set to true, select a specific Routing ID from the specific party selected as the receiving party of the acknowledgement.

ackInterchangeCntrlNumberGenerator.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The data interchange information code control number. This is the starting value of unique identifiers for outbound messages. By default, the identifier increases by 1 for each additional message (ISA13). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

ackGroupCntrlNumberGenerator.description: Assigned number originated and maintained by the sender (GS 06).

ackTransSetCntrlNumberGenerator.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

A control number assigned by the sender and stored in the transaction set header. The number must be unique in the functional group (ST02).

ackGroupTimeFormat.description:
Select one of the following time formats:
  • HHMM
  • HHMMSS
  • HHMMSSD
  • HHSSMMDD

rejectionRule.description:
The condition for rejecting interchange. Interchanges are rejected depending on
where errors are found. For example, if there is an error in one transaction set, the whole interchange is
rejected.

customRejectionRule.description: If "If any documents are stopped, reject documents of the following types" rejection rule is selected, specify the document types to be rejected.

checkControlNumbs.description:
The interchange control number for inbound messages is verified to be in sequence. So, for example, if the user
sets the next expected interchange control number to 123456, the system validates that the next inbound document
has an interchange control number of 123456. If the validation succeeds the field is updated to 123457. If the
validation fails, the out of sequence action is applied.

checkGroupControlNumbs.description:
The group control numbers for inbound messages is verified to be in sequence. So, for example, if the user
sets the next expected group control number to 123456, the system validates that the next inbound document
has an group control number of 123456. If the validation succeeds the field is updated to 123457. If the
validation fails, the out of sequence action is applied.

outOfSeqAction.description:
The action to take for non-sequential interchange and group control numbers. Options are:
  • WARN_AND_PROCESS

    • Allows an inbound interchange to be processed successfully, but a warning is posted.

  • FAIL_AND_PARK

    • Processing is halted and an error is posted.

dupCheckControlNumbs.description:
Interchange control numbers are checked for duplicates, by comparing to interchanges already received. If a
duplicate is detected for an inbound interchange, the duplicate action is respected.

dupCheckGroupControlNumbs.description:
Group control numbers are checked for duplicates, by comparing to groups already received. If a duplicate is
detected for an inbound group, the duplicate action is respected.

dupAction.description:
The action to take for non-sequential interchange and group control numbers. Options are:
  • WARN_AND_PROCESS

    • Allows an inbound interchange to be processed successfully, but a warning is posted.

  • FAIL_AND_PARK

    • Processing is halted and an error is posted.

compositeElementSeperator.description:
Enabled for X12 Group level processing mode.

Enter the character to use as the composite element separator (ISA16). The field uses a colon as the default value. Alternately, you can use a hex code.

useX12TestIndicator.description: Select this option if you want that B2Bi to parse the X12 test indicator value at runtime.

documentAgreements.description: List with all document agreements for current agreement

nachaIdentifier.description: Position 04-13 (Immediate Destination) or 14-23 (Immediate Origin) of the NACHA file header record.

nachaName.description: Position 41-63 (Immediate Destination Name) or 64-86 (Immediate Origin Name) of the NACHA file header record.

remoteOftpExchangePoint.description: The URL of the server being polled for messages.

remoteOftpExchangePointToPollId.description:
The id of a partner's OFTP exchange point whom community polls for inbound messages.
The version (V1 or V2) must match and at most one community can poll a partner's server

routingIdentifier.description:
The Routing Id belonging to a partner or a community. For Application Delivery, use PesitReceiverID instead.
Note: If missing, allow any valid routing Id to be used.

password.description:
Password to be used. This should be the password expected from the partner on a remote identification and the password the partner expects for the local identification.
Note: This field is used only on trading part.

overridePasswordSettings.description: Set to true to specify a password. <p/>

authenticationType.description: Authentication type; must be set to 'USER_PASS' or 'APOP'.

cipherSuites.description: List with cipher suites.

connectTimeoutSeconds.description:
Connect timeout (seconds) - Time in seconds the trading engine waits for a connection to the delivery exchange
before the attempt times out. By default this is set to 30 seconds.

enableHostnameVerification.description:
SSL authentication.  If we're acting as the client, true means we should verify that the
hostname for the certificate given to us by the server matches the host we connected to.
If we're acting as the server, true means we require the client to present its
certificate ("client authentication").

host.description:
The name of the POP server that the trading engine polls for messages sent by your partner. This must be a fully
qualified domain name or IP address.

maxMessagesPerConnection.description:
Maximum number of messages to be consumed over a single connection before the connection
is closed and reopened on another processing node.

overrideCipherSuites.description: If true, a list of cipher suites should be provided.

port.description: The POP server port. By default this is 110.

readTimeoutSeconds.description: Read timeout (seconds) - The maximum number of seconds the server waits when reading data from a partner.

senderIdentificationType.description:
Specify how the sender will be identified; must be set to 'PD_EMAIL_ADDRESSES' or
'PARTNER_EMAIL_ACCOUNTS'.

sequenceTimeoutSeconds.description: Time limit to wait for missing messages of a sequence before taking the appropriate action.

sequenced.description:
Select this option if you want all messages that are consumed by this pickup to be delivered in their original
consumption order.

ssl.description: Client use ssl to connect to this server ?.

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: The user name and password required to connect to the server.

bindAddresses.description: The DMZ hosts for the machines in the cluster.

forwardingEnabled.description: Specify whether connections to this server should be proxied through DMZ nodes. If this option is set to true, the external firewall or load balancer sends inbound connections to Secure Relay DMZ nodes rather than directly to embedded servers in the protected network.

forwardingPorts.description:
Ports for DMZ forwarding. In the simplest case, there is one DMZ port with the same value as the corresponding
embedded server port in the protected network. If you add a machine to your cluster, another DMZ port
is automatically added in sequence. This happens because every machine in the cluster that can host the embedded
server must be assigned a unique corresponding port in the DMZ.
<p/>
For example, if the server port is 4080 and there are two cluster machines, two ports would be exposed on every
DMZ node, e.g. 4080 and 4081. If you add machines to the cluster, you should update your firewall or load
balancer configuration accordingly.

id.description: The unique ID of the transport server.

ipAddressCheckEnabled.description:
Specify whether the trading engine should check partners' IP addresses against a whitelist of authorized IP
addresses. Connections from unknown IP addresses are not allowed.

ipAddressPartnerMatchEnabled.description:
When IP address checking is enabled, specify whether the router agent should check if the partner is registered to the IP address. If this option is set to false, the agent only checks the user's credentials.

This control is not available to all types of servers.

name.description: The name of the transport server, used to distinguish it from other embedded servers.

readTimeoutSeconds.description: The maximum number of seconds the server waits when reading data from a partner. Default value is 30 seconds.

securityTerminationEnabled.description:
Specify whether various security functions should be performed in the DMZ. If connections are via SSL, the secure
connection is terminated at the router agent in the DMZ. For delivery exchanges that require a user name and
password to connect (for example, FTP, SFTP or WebDAV), the router agent authenticates the user.

Note: it is read only

Note: it is read only

usedForProcessing.description:

Note: it is read only

message processing. For an outbound message, this is the sender's ID. For an inbound message,
this is the receiver's ID.

or OFTP V2 delivery exchanges for other partners. The user interface only allows selecting delivery

and directory can be associated with only one exchange.

partnerPort.description: The port of the sender (SNDPOR) or the receiver (RCVPOR)

partnerType.description: The partner type of the sender (SNDPRT) or the receiver (RCVPRT)

The network settings for this server. The following types are supported:
  1. TCP. Transmission Control Protocol is the basic communications protocol of the Internet.
  2. X.25. An ITU-T standard protocol suite for packet-switched wide area network communications.
  3. X.25 over ISDN (B-channel). Integrated Services Digital Network broadband channel supports data transfers over telephone networks

identifier.description:
The name of the generator for which the value will be considered. Possible values are:

  • _0020 - Interchange control reference generator. Valid for Edifact Outbound Agreement.
  • _0062 - Message reference number generator. Valid for Edifact Outbound Agreement.
  • UNG0048 - Reference Number Generator. Valid for Edifact Outbound Functional Group Agreement.
  • SNRF - Sender transmission reference generator. Valid for Tradacoms Outbound Agreement.
  • FIELD05 - Transmission number old. Valid for VDA Inbound Agreement.
  • FIELD06 - Transmission number new generator. Valid for VDA Outbound Agreement.
  • LATEST_TRANSMISSION_NUMBER - Latest transmission number new. Valid for VDA Outbound Agreement.
  • NEXT_GROUP_CONTROL - Next expected group control. Valid for Edifact Inbound Agreement, X12 Inbound Agreement.
  • NEXT_INTERCHANGE_CONTROL - Next expected interchange control. Valid for Edifact Inbound Agreement, X12 Inbound Agreement.
  • MSH00010 - Message control ID. Valid for HL7v2 Inbound Agreement, HL7v2 Outbound Agreement.
  • MSH00013 - Sequence number generator. Valid for HL7v2 Outbound Agreement.
  • NEXT_INTERCHANGE_SEQUENCE_NUMBER - Next expected sequence number. Valid for HL7v2 Inbound Agreement.
  • ISA13 - Interchange control number generator. Valid for X12 Inbound Agreement, X12 Outbound Agreement.
  • GS06 - Group control number generator. Valid for X12 Inbound Agreement, X12 Outbound Functional Group Agreement.

preferredNodes.description: Get the preferred nodes used to process messages. See usePreferredNodes.

usePreferredNodes.description:
If there are one or more nodes for the trading engine, you can select one or more as the preferred nodes for consuming messages. If the preferred nodes are running, these are used to process messages. If the preferred nodes are stopped, work is distributed among the remaining running available nodes. Selecting preferred nodes lets you manage work distribution among nodes.

This option is available for integration pickup and trading delivery exchanges that poll for messages.

In general, this setting should not be used. Usually it is best to let the trading engine automatically determine which node should be responsible for initiating the polling of which exchange point. This setting is useful if you have a cluster that spans geographical locations and each location has its own local transport servers. In this situation, you would use this setting to ensure the exchange points associated with the transport servers are assigned to nodes in the vicinity of the transport servers.

definitionName.description:

For consistency with existing names, use an initial capital letter, and no period at the end.

settings.description: Defines setting string to be passed to the implementation class when a pluggable transport is created

cipherSuites.description: List with cipher suites.

implicitSsl.description:
Select this option if you want to use implicit SSL rather than explicit SSL, which is the default mode. FTP supports two methods to accomplish security through a sequence of commands passed between two computers. The sequence is initiated with explicit (active) or implicit (passive) security.
  • Explicit security. To establish the SSL link, explicit security requires the FTP client to issue a specific command to the FTP server after establishing a connection. The default FTP server port is used.
  • Implicit security. Implicit security begins with an SSL connection as soon as the FTP client connects to an FTP server. The FTP server defines a specific port for the client to be used for secure connections.
FTP over SSL Implicit has been deprecated and should no longer be used.

passivePorts.description: Ports for inbound passive data connections from FTP clients. You can enter multiple ports. Separate individual port numbers by a comma. Alternatively, you can specify a range of ports. The following example uses both comma-separated port numbers and a range of ports: 50000,50001,50010-50020

Contact your network administrator if you need help with this field.

remoteUrl.description:
URL that should be exported and placed in the community's partner profile. This is the URL that is
exposed on the public side of a reverse proxy or firewall. This method is really only useful for
embedded server exchanges on the trading side like HTTP and FTP.
<p/>
In the case of HTTP an actual value is stored in the db because the load balancer could have a
different external vs. internal path for every exchange point. In the case of FTP there is no need to
store a per-exchange point external URL, so it overrides this method and dynamically returns a URL
built from other sources.
<p/>
Worst case, this method will return url if remoteUrl is null.

serverSettings.description: Embedded server settings of the embedded exchange point.

directory.description:
The full path for a unique directory where the trading engine picks up messages. If the directory does not exist,
the trading engine creates it for you.
<p/>
You must specify a unique directory name. You may want to give the directory a name that indicates that the transport
is being used for integration or receiving messages from partners.

filterConditions.description:
Insert the formats of the files you want the transport
to consume or ignore. Use conventional wildcard characters for file names or
extensions or both. The following describes the supported characters and symbols:
<p/> <hr/>
*      One or more characters.<p/><hr/>
?      Any single character.<p/><hr/>
[ ]      Matches any single character within the brackets. For example, r[aou]t
matches rat, rot and rut.<p/><hr/>
,      Commas can be used as and/or operators within brackets (for example, r[a,
o,u]t). <p/><hr/>
-      Use hyphens within brackets to specify ranges of letters or numbers. For
example, [0-9] is for any number between 0 and 9, and [A-Za-z] is for any
upper- or lower-case letter. <p/><hr/>
.      Use the character dot to separate the file name and extension. For example,
*.txt.<p/><hr/>
|      Use the pipe character to separate multiple file name formats. For example,
*.edi|*.txt|[a,b,c]?.xml.<p/>

filterOption.description:
Enabling file filtering allows the trading engine to discriminate which
files to consume based on file names  <p/>

metadataHierarchy.description:
You can use metadata hierarchy to avoid file name collisions by selecting message attributes that
correspond to the names of subdirectories. <p/>
Each item added represents another subdirectory level. For example, add "From routing ID" and "To
routing ID" to the selected attributes list in that order. Then, place a message in a subdirectory
named "ABC/DEF". The message will be assigned a "From routing ID" attribute set to "ABC" and a
"To routing ID" set to "DEF".

negativeFilterOption.description:
Specify whether the filter pattern is inclusive or exclusive. <p/>
If set to false it is inclusive: only files matching the pattern are consumed. If set to true it is exclusive:
files matching the pattern are ignored, but all other files are consumed.

xml_ns0_addressingRuleBean.title: addressingRuleBean

addressingAction.description:
Determine how a pickup will compute the sender/receiver's address

Values for addressing rule action
  • USE_METADATA_OR_PROTOCOL_ADDRESS Address must be determined by either message attribute configuration or by protocol address only.
  • USE_FIXED_PARTY Specify the address. Always use a fixed address.
    Specifies that the trading engine should always use a fixed address for the sender or receiver. The "from" or "to" party must be set up as a community or partner.
    Note When this value is chosen, fixedPartyId should also be set
  • USE_PROTOCOL_ADDRESS Use the protocol address but if protocol address is missing, parse the document for the address.
    If you select this option, you must configure the address parsing rule. See Address parsing rule options below.
  • ALWAYS_PARSE Always parse for the address. Regardless whether the message protocol provides the address, always parse the document for the address..
    Select this option to specify that the trading engine should always parse the message for the sender or receiver address. For messages from partners, however, the trading engine still checks the protocol header for the sender and receiver. A message with an unknown sender or receiver in the header is rejected. The always parse option for inbound messages is for finding the identity of true senders or true receivers.For messages picked up from applications, the always parse option tells the trading engine to find the sender or receiver in the message body. Messages from integration do not have protocol headers.If you select this option, you must configure the address parsing rule. See Address parsing rule options below.

Address parsing rule options
  • If the document is EDI, parse for the address - If an EDI document is picked up, use the "to" and "from" addresses specified within it. Properly formatted EDI documents contain this information.
  • If the document is XML, use XPaths to locate the address - If an XML document is picked up, use the "to" and "from" addresses specified by the XPaths within it. XML Path Language or XPath is a language for addressing parts of an XML document.

edifactUseInternal.description:
Perform enhanced EDI parsing to match partner messaging IDs - This setting applies to X12, EDIFACT, and TRADACOMS. If your user license supports Axway B2Bi, this option is selected by default.If selected, the trading engine performs additional parsing of the header information to create routing IDs with a colon separator between values.
For example, information from an EDIFACT file would be parsed in the following format:
ID:interchange ID:internal ID:sub-internal ID
When this parsing option is elected, communities and partners must have matching routing IDs in the same format.
For example, if the "from" address in a parsed message is ID:interchange ID:value3:value4, the partner must have the same routing ID.
When this option is not selected, "to" and "from" addresses in messages are parsed only for the trading engineID and ID values.
For example, 1:partner is parsed as the sender and rendered as partner1 in the user interface.
Note that TRADACOMS only has two, optional values that can be parsed. They must match one of the following patterns:
A:
:B
A:B

parseEdi.description: If the document is EDI, parse for the address - If an EDI document is picked up, use the "to" and "from" addresses specified within it. Properly formatted EDI documents contain this information.

parseXml.description: If the document is XML, use XPaths to locate the address - If an XML document is picked up, use the "to" and "from" addresses specified by the XPaths within it. XML Path Language or XPath is a language for addressing parts of an XML document.

xpaths.description:
This field is for specifying the XPaths of the message sender or receiver.
Note Using the XPath requires knowledge of XML.

xml_ns0_addressingRuleBean.description: Use this class to specify sender and receiver rules for consumed files

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Specify whether the cipher suites supported by the server are stated, in order for you select the level of security that suits your needs and enables communicating with others who might have different security requirements.

For example, when an SSL connection is established, the client and server exchange information about the cipher suites they have in common. Then they communicate using the common cipher suite that offers the highest level of security. If they do not have a cipher suite in common, secure communication is not possible. If this option is set to false, all cipher suites are supported by default.

cipherSuites.description:
The specific cipher suites supported by the server. If empty, all cipher suites are supported by
default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain cipher suites.
The default order in the list is the preferred order of use.
<p/>
A cipher suite is a collection of security algorithms used in making connections via Secure Sockets Layer or
Transport Layer Security. For example, an SSL or TLS protocol requires signing messages using a message digest
algorithm. But the choice of algorithm is determined by the particular cipher suite being used for the
connection. Typically, you can select an MD5 or SHA digest algorithm.

enableClientAuthenticatedTls.description: Specify whether the partner's certificate should be used for authentication when the partner connects to the server, when using TLS option is enabled. If this option is set to true, partners are required to present a certificate for identity verification.

authCodeQualifier.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

A code identifying the type of information in the authorization information (ISA01). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

authCode.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

A value representing additional identification or authorization of the interchange sender or the data in the interchange (ISA02). This is an interchange envelope parameter. The type of information is set by the Authorization code qualifier (ISA01).

securityCodeQualifier.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

A code identifying the type of information in the security information (ISA03). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

securityCode.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

Security information about the interchange sender or the data in the interchange (ISA04). This is an interchange envelope parameter. The type of information is set by the Security code qualifier (ISA03).

repetitionSeperator.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The repetition separator character for the repeating element (ISA11). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

interchangeControlVersion.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The information code version number. This covers all current interchange control segments (ISA12). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

interchangeControlNumberGenerator.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The data interchange information code control number. This is the starting value of unique identifiers for outbound messages. By default, the identifier increases by 1 for each additional message (ISA13). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

requestTa1Acks.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

Select this option to request an interchange acknowledgment (TA1) (ISA14). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

compositeElementSeperator.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

Enter the character to use as the composite element separator (ISA16). The field uses a colon as the default value. Alternately, you can use a hex code.

elementSeperator.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

Enter the character to use as the element separator. The field uses an asterisk as the default value. Alternately, you can use a hex code.

segmentSeperator.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

Enter the character to use as the segment separator. The field uses the hex code \H0A as the default value.

acceptGroups.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

Select this option if you want to accept group segments.

groupTimeout.description: When acceptGroups is true, specify the time limit in hours and minutes before groups time out. The 24-hour format is HH:MM.

groupTimeoutAction.description:
When acceptGroups is true, specify the action to perform if group messages are missing. The accepted values are:
  • SEND_AND_WARN
  • SEND
  • STOP

maxNumbDocs.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

The largest number of documents the envelope can contain.

envelopeTimeout.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

The envelope timeout in hours and minutes. The 24-hour format is HH:MM, where HH is from 00 to 23 and MM is from 00 to 59.

groupAckWaitTime.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

The time in hours and minutes to wait for receiving acknowledgments. If not received within this time, the transmission is regarded as faulty. The 24-hour format is HH:MM, where HH is from 00 to 23 and MM is from 00 to 59.

transSetControlNumbGenerator.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

A control number assigned by the sender and stored in the transaction set header. The number must be unique in the functional group (ST02).

request997Acks.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

Select this option if the an acknowledgement to the outbound message is required.

json_WebTraderUnAuthorizedException.title: WebTraderUnAuthorizedException
json_WebTraderUnAuthorizedException.description: Exception that maps to HTTP 401 return code

backlogSeconds.description: The number of connections that the server puts 'on hold' while it is busy. Once this number is reached, connections are refused. Required.

localPort.description: The port that the embedded server uses to listen for connection requests. Required.

remoteHost.description: The host used by a partner to connect to this embedded server. The trading engine supplies a value based on the name of the host computer. Required.

remotePort.description: The port used by a remote partner to connect to this embedded server. Required.

host.description:
The SMTP server for sending messages to the specified partner. You must provide a fully qualified domain name or IP
address for the server. If you leave this field blank, the system inserts its external SMTP server.

port.description: The port used for sending messages to the specified partner. The default values is 25.

emailAddress.description: The email address for sending messages to a partner.

connectTimeoutSeconds.description: Time in seconds the trading engine waits for a connection to the delivery exchange before the attempt times out. The default value is 30 seconds. Required.

readTimeoutSeconds.description: Time in seconds the trading engine waits to read data from the delivery exchange before terminating the connection. Required.

useGlobalSmtp.description:
Specify whether the system's external SMTP server is used to send messages to the partner.
Otherwise, you can specify a different external SMTP server to send messages to the partner.

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: User name and password to connect to the server. Usually, SMTP servers do not require user names and passwords for sending messages.

cipherSuites.description: List with cipher suites.

ssl.description: client use ssl to connect to this server ?

enableHostnameVerification.description:
SSL authentication.  If we're acting as the client, true means we should verify that the
hostname for the certificate given to us by the server matches the host we connected to.
If we're acting as the server, true means we require the client to present its
certificate ("client authentication").

overrideCipherSuites.description: If true, a list of cipher suites should be provided.

cipherSuites.description:
The specific cipher suites supported by the server. If empty, all cipher suites are supported by
default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain cipher suites.
The default order in the list is the preferred order of use.
<p/>
A cipher suite is a collection of security algorithms used in making connections via Secure Sockets Layer or
Transport Layer Security. For example, an SSL or TLS protocol requires the signing of messages using a message digest
algorithm. The choice of algorithm is determined by the particular cipher suite being used for the
connection. Typically, you can select an MD5 or SHA digest algorithm.

connectTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits for a connection to the delivery exchange before the attempt times out.
<p/>
Although the default value is 30 seconds, this may be longer than the interval allowed by your operating
system. For example, Windows XP by default allows a maximum timeout of 20 seconds. The actual connect timeout
interval is the lesser of the operating system timeout and the value set in the trading engine.

enable102Processing.description:
Specify whether 102-processing is enabled. If this option is set to true, it is ensured that the connection between the client and server does not become idle and fail while message processing is in progress.

For example, this makes sure the connection remains active when the client is sending a multi-gigabyte message. Most often this setting is useful when the client requests a synchronous receipt, but is also recommended in some cases for an asynchronous receipt. Before selecting this option, make sure the server supports 102 responses.

enableChunking.description:
Specify whether chunking messages is enabled. A chunked message is a large message broken into smaller
pieces for sending to a partner over the Internet or to back-end integration.
<p/>
Although primarily used for handling large messages, chunking can also be enabled for small messages.
You should perform tests to determine whether a partner's server can handle chunked messages.

enableRestarts.description:
Specify whether checkpoint-restart is enabled. A checkpoint is information saved to disk that is a
recovery point in the event of a transport failure.
<p/>
The restart program uses the last saved checkpoint and
starts again, ensuring no loss of data. To reduce unnecessary overhead when processing small files,
checkpoint files are only created for messages that are at least 100 KB in size.

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Specify whether the cipher suites supported by the server are stated, to enable communication with partners who might have different security requirements.

For example, when an SSL connection is established, the client and server exchange information about the cipher suites they have in common. Then they communicate using the common cipher suite that offers the highest level of security. If they do not have a cipher suite in common, secure communication is not possible. If this option is set to false, all cipher suites are supported by default.

proxy.description:
Specify whether you must pass through a proxy to reach the delivery exchange server. For partner exchanges,
the proxy is located between the trading engine and the partner's HTTP server.

readTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits to read data from the delivery exchange before terminating
the connection.

responseTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits for the delivery exchange to respond to a request
before terminating the connection.

ssl.description: Specify whether Secure Sockets Layer protocol is in use during connections. If this option is set to true, the server presents a certificate for verification. To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: User name and password to connect to the server.

id.description: Gets the Message identifier

receiverPartyID.description: Gets the Message receiver party Id

receiverRoutingID.description: Gets the Message receiver routing Id

senderPartyID.description: Gets the Message sender party Id

senderRoutingID.description: Gets the Message sender routing Id

jmsQueueConnFactory.description: The connection factory as defined within the JMS provider. This value can be either in the form factoryname@routername or the JNDI public symbol for the QueueConnectionFactory. This depends on your JMS provider and how it is configured. Examples: plainsocket@router1 or QueueConnectionFactory22.

jmsQueue.description:
The name of the queue.

Example: XMLQueue@router1.

jmsCredentials.description:
User name and password for the JMS provider. The user name and password can be the same as your JNDI user name
and password. This depends on your JMS provider and how it is configured.

useJndi.description:
Specify whether the JMS provider requires a Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI) implementation.
For example, Oracle Advanced Queuing facility (Oracle AQ) does not use a JNDI provider.

jndiUrl.description: The network URL used to obtain access to the JNDI service provider for your JMS service. Example: smqp://localhost:4001/timeout=10000.

jndiFactory.description:
The name of the JNDI service provider class.

Example: com.swiftmq.jndi.InitialContextFactoryImpl.

jndiCredentials.description:
User name and password for the JNDI provider. The user name and password could be blank and are typically provided
in the JNDI URL. This depends on the JNDI provider and how it is configured.

queueUtilClass.description: The name of the Java class for implementing the connection to the message queue. A Java class for Oracle AQ is available. The class name is: com.cyclonecommerce.tradingengine.transport.jms.OracleAQQueueUtil. If you want a Java class for a provider other than Oracle AQ, you need the help of a professional services consultant.

queueUtilParameters.description:
There are four parameters required for the Java class for Oracle AQ. These parameters must be in the following order:
  1. Host - the name of the computer running Oracle AQ
  2. Database name - the name of the database that contains the message queue
  3. Port - the port Oracle AQ uses to listen for messages
  4. Driver type - the type of JDBC driver for connecting to the provider. For Oracle AQ, the valid values are thin and oci8.

receiveTimeoutSeconds.description:
If your JMS provider is slow to respond to the request received from the trading engine, increase the response interval.
The default value of 0 is acceptable in the case of most JMS providers. However, if unacceptable for your
JMS provider, use trial-and-error to determine a workable interval between 1 and 32767 seconds.

serverReconnectIntervalSeconds.description: The interval in seconds to wait between reconnect attempts.

usePreferredNodes.description:
If there are one or more nodes for the trading engine, you can select one or more as the preferred nodes for consuming messages. If the preferred nodes are running, these are used to process messages. If the preferred nodes are stopped, work is distributed among the remaining running available nodes. Selecting preferred nodes lets you manage work distribution among nodes.

This option is available for integration pickup and trading delivery exchanges that poll for messages.

In general, this setting should not be used. Usually it is best to let the trading engine automatically determine which node should be responsible for initiating the polling of which exchange point. This setting is useful if you have a cluster that spans geographical locations and each location has its own local transport servers. In this situation, you would use this setting to ensure the exchange points associated with the transport servers are assigned to nodes in the vicinity of the transport servers.

preferredNodes.description: Get the preferred nodes used to process messages. See usePreferredNodes.

delivery.description: Returns a link to the delivery exchange point which will be given to trading partners for sending messages.

applicationDeliveryId.description: The ID of the Application Delivery used by this Delivery Setting.  <p/>

deliveryCriteria.description:
Use this to define the conditions that cause payloads to be delivered to the appropriate application delivery.
If a payload does not satisfy the delivery criteria for any application delivery, then the first available
application delivery is used. An application delivery with no criteria is used only if it is the first one
available. <p/>

enabled.description: Specifies whether or not this Delivery Setting is enabled. <p/>

id.description: The ID of this Delivery Setting. <p/>

enabled.description: The status of this user.

id.description: The unique String ID for this user.

password.description: The password of this Web Services user.

policy.description: The password policy assigned to this user.

user.description: The username of this Web Services user. Once the user is created, the username cannot be changed.

defaultUser.description: The default ftp account used by the FTP embedded server.

localPort.description:
The local port used by the embedded FTP server to listen for incoming connections.
The default value is 4021 for the trading server and 5021 for the application server.

modifyFtpServerDirectory.description: Enable subdirectory management on the client side.

sequenceTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds that B2Bi waits for missing messages of a sequence before taking the appropriate action.
This feature avoids the blocking of processing when a sequenced message is not available. Default value is of
60 seconds.

sequenced.description:
Specify whether all messages that are consumed by this pickup should be delivered in their original
consumption order.
<p/>
In B2Bi message-handling, sequential delivery is the ability to deliver messages in the order they
were originally consumed on a specific pickup. This is sometimes referred to as first-in-first-out
(FIFO) behavior.
<p/>
Sequential message delivery is implemented only for trading engine pickups, not for integration
engine pickups

localPort.description: The port on which the embedded server listens for connection requests.

remoteHost.description: The fully qualified domain name or IP address your partners use to pick up messages from this exchange. <p/>

remotePort.description: The port number that a community's partners must use to connect to this embedded server.<p/>

maxConnections.description:
The number of total open connections the trading engine server can make to a partner. If you are operating in a
cluster environment, this is the total number across the entire cluster, no matter how many JVM nodes are
running. <p/>

maxAuthentications.description: The number of failed authentication attempts the server allows before disconnecting the user. <p/>

clientSessionTimeoutSeconds.description: The number of seconds the server waits before disconnecting an inactive logged-on user.<p/>

authenticationMode.description:
The authentication type this server requires. Select one of the following:

  • PASSWORD_AUTHENTICATION

    This server requires the SFTP client to authenticate using a password. Select this in order to require your partner to submit a password to connect to your embedded SFTP server.

  • PUBLIC_KEY_AUTHENTICATION

    This server requires the SFTP client to authenticate using a public/private key pair. Select this in order to require your partner to use a private key to encrypt an authentication message and pass it to the server to decrypt with the matching public key.

  • BOTH_PUBLIC_KEY_PASSWORD_AUTHENTICATION

    This server requires the SFTP client to authenticate using both a password and a public/private key pair.

  • EITHER_PUBLIC_KEY_PASSWORD_AUTHENTICATION

    This server allows the SFTP client to authenticate using either a password or a public/private key pair.

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Set this to true if you want to select the specific ciphers supported for the server. If set to false, all ciphers
are supported by default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain ciphers.<p/>

cipherSuites.description: Specific SSH ciphers supported by this server. <p/>

rsaKeyType.description: The type of the RSA key found on this server. <p/>

rsaKey.description: Path to the RSA SSH key.

dsaKey.description: Path to the DSA SSH key.

dsaKeyType.description: The type of the DSA key found on this server. <p/>

dsaKeyLength.description: The length of the DSA key. <p/>

rsaKeyLength.description: The length of the RSA key. <p/>

allowUploadOnDelExchange.description:
Select this option to allow documents to be uploaded to application deliveries or partner deliveries. By default,
document uploads are not allowed for deliveries. This setting does not impact pickups. <p/>

xml_ns0_addressingRulesBean.title: addressingRulesBean

fromAddress.description: Used to configure how the system determines who is sending the message.

toAddress.description: Used to configure how the system determines to whom the message is being sent

xml_ns0_addressingRulesBean.description: Used to configure how the system determines who is sending/receiving the message.

controlNumberGenerator.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The data interchange information code control number. This is the starting value of unique identifiers for outbound messages. By default, the identifier increases by 1 for each additional message (ISA13). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

functionalGroupId.description: (GS 479) Identifies a group of application related transaction sets.

identifierCode.description:
(GS480) Code indicating the version, release, sub-release, and industry identifier of the EDI standard
being used, including the GS and GE segments. If code in DE455 in GS segment is X, then in DE 480
positions 1-3 are the version number; positions 4-6 are the release and subrelease, level of the
version; and positions 7-12 are the industry or trade association identifiers (optionally assigned by
user); if code in DE455 in GS segment is T, then other formats are allowed.

receiverMessagingId.description: (GS 124) Identifies the party receiving transmission. This code is agreed to by trading partners.

responsibleAgencyCode.description: (GS 455) Identifies the issuer of the standard. This code is used in conjunction with GS 480 below.

senderMessagingId.description: (GS 142) Identifies the party sending the transmission. This code is agreed to by trading partners.

timeFormat.description:
Select one of the following time formats:
  • HHMM
  • HHMMSS
  • HHMMSSD
  • HHSSMMDD

receiverIdentification.description: The "Partner Code" identification defined in the receiver's Messaging ID. </br> This is a read-only field.

receiverVdaRole.description: The VDA role of the receiving partner. </br> This is a read-only field.

senderIdentification.description: The "Partner Code" identification defined in the sender's Messaging ID. </br> This is a read-only field.

senderVdaRole.description: The VDA role of the sending partner.

clientModeEnabled.description:
The MQSeries connection type. Two options are available:
  • true - select this option to use a channel connection on the local machine or via the network, to connect to a queue manager.
  • false select this option to use an API connection, via shared memory, to a local queue manager.

convertUsingCCSID.description: Set to true if you want to enable data conversion.

mqCharset.description: The character set for converting data.

mqQueueName.description: The name of the MQSeries queue.

multiInstanceEnabled.description: Select this option if the server has an MQSeries multi-instance queue manager.

segmentationSize.description: The message segmentation size in bytes.

sslCipherSuite.description: The SSL cipher suite to use for SSL encryption.

useSsl.description: Use SSL to connect to the MQSeries server.

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: User name and password to connect to the server.

acceptGroups.description: Specify whether group segments are accepted.

envelopeTimeout.description: The envelope timeout in hours and minutes. The 24-hour format is HH:MM.

groupTimeout.description: The time limit in hours and minutes before groups time out (when group segments are accepted). The 24-hour format is HH:MM.

groupTimeoutAction.description:
