The action to perform if group messages are missing (when group segments are accepted). The available options are:
  • SEND_AND_WARN
  • SEND
  • STOP

maxNumbDocs.description: The largest number of entries the envelope can contain.

senderIdentification.description: The sender partner's messaging ID. </br> This is a read-only field.

receiverIdentification.description: The receiver partner's messaging ID. </br> This is a read-only field.

ftpUserName.description: Get the name of the FTP user.

subDirectory.description:
User's subdirectory where the messages will be written.
The user subdirectories for each exchange are different.

allowUploadOnDelExchange.description:
Select this option to allow documents to be uploaded to application deliveries or partner deliveries. By default,
document uploads are not allowed for deliveries. This setting does not impact pickups. <p/>

authenticationMode.description:
The authentication type this server requires. Select one of the following:

  • PASSWORD_AUTHENTICATION

    This server requires the SFTP client to authenticate using a password. Select this in order to require your partner to submit a password to connect to your embedded SFTP server.

  • PUBLIC_KEY_AUTHENTICATION

    This server requires the SFTP client to authenticate using a public/private key pair. Select this in order to require your partner to use a private key to encrypt an authentication message and pass it to the server to decrypt with the matching public key.

  • BOTH_PUBLIC_KEY_PASSWORD_AUTHENTICATION

    This server requires the SFTP client to authenticate using both a password and a public/private key pair.

  • EITHER_PUBLIC_KEY_PASSWORD_AUTHENTICATION

    This server allows the SFTP client to authenticate using either a password or a public/private key pair.

cipherSuites.description: Specific SSH ciphers supported by this server. <p/>

clientSessionTimeoutSeconds.description: The number of seconds the server waits before disconnecting an inactive logged-on user.<p/>

dsaKeyLength.description: The length of the DSA key. <p/>

dsaKeyType.description: The type of the DSA key found on this server. <p/>

localPort.description: The port on which the embedded server listens for connection requests.

maxAuthentications.description: The number of failed authentication attempts the server allows before disconnecting the user. <p/>

maxConnections.description:
The number of total open connections the trading engine server can make to a partner. If you are operating in a
cluster environment, this is the total number across the entire cluster, no matter how many JVM nodes are
running. <p/>

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Set this to true if you want to select the specific ciphers supported for the server. If set to false, all ciphers
are supported by default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain ciphers.<p/>

remoteHost.description: The fully qualified domain name or IP address your partners use to pick up messages from this exchange. <p/>

remotePort.description: The port number that a community's partners must use to connect to this embedded server.<p/>

rsaKeyLength.description: The length of the RSA key. <p/>

rsaKeyType.description: The type of the RSA key found on this server. <p/>

documentFormat.description: The documentStandard or format that applies to the document that is to be exchanged between partners.

documentVersion.description: The documentVersion of the document that is to be exchanged between partners.

documentType.description: The type of document that is to be exchanged between partners.

postDetectionComponent.description:
The component which provides post detection processing to the messages handled by this service.
This processing is executed after detection and before any other processing (such as splitting or  mapping) is done.

agreementId.description: The ID of the outbound agreement to be used for enveloping.

deliveryExchangeId.description: Delivery belonging to the alternate delivery partner to be used. This must be a complete and enabled partner delivery.

overrideTransportReceiver.description: Set this to true in order to use an alternate delivery partner.

receiverId.description: The ID of the receiver partner for the outbound agreement or null for [ANY].

senderId.description: The ID of the sender partner or null for [ANY].

transportReceiverId.description: The partner to be used as alternate delivery partner.

transportReceiverRoutingId.description: Routing ID belonging to the alternate delivery partner to be used.

useSyntaxVersion.description: Specify whether the syntaxVersion field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useSyntaxIdentifier.description: Specify whether the syntaxIdentifier field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

usePartnerIdSender.description: Specify whether the partnerIdSender field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

usePartnerIdReceiver.description: Specify whether the partnerIdReceiver field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useIdCodeQualifierSender.description: Specify whether the idCodeQualifierSender field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useIdCodeQualifierReceiver.description: Specify whether the idCodeQualifierReceiver field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

usePartnerIdInternalIdSender.description: Specify whether the partnerIdInternalIdSender field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

usePartnerIdInternalIdReceiver.description: Specify whether the partnerIdInternalIdReceiver field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

usePartnerIdInternalSubIdSender.description: Specify whether the partnerIdInternalSubIdSender field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

usePartnerIdInternalSubIdReceiver.description: Specify whether the partnerIdInternalSubIdReceiver field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useApplicationReference.description: Specify whether the applicationReference field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useCommunicationAgreementId.description: Specify whether the communicationAgreementId field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useTestIndicator.description: Specify whether the testIndicator field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

bypassEdiProcessing.description: Specify whether all other inbound processing options are unavailable. If this option is set to true, the performance of B2Bi is improved when handling large interchanges. The trading engine handles incoming interchanges without unpacking the envelopes. The trading engine reads only the interchange header and transaction set header segment (ST). The entire interchange is sent to the map as a single message. Regular EDI logic is not applied. For this reason, no acknowledgements can be automatically generated and sent. It is not required to have a map in the service attached to this agreement. This enables the trading engine to pass an entire interchange to the next application without modification. If the service that is attached to the agreement contains a map, the documents contained in the interchange must all be of the same type and same version.

generateAckRule.description:
The condition for sending acknowledgments. The available options are:
  • NEVER (default) - no acknowledgement is generated
  • ON_REQUEST - acknowledgments must be requested when an integration is set up.
  • ALWAYS - acknowledgments are always sent.
  • IF_ERRORS - acknowledgements are sent only when errors are detected

generateAckType.description:
The type of the EDIFACT acknowledgement. This information is needed when an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements is selected. The following options are available:
  • CONTROL_EANCOM_D93A
  • CONTROL_EANCOM_D96A
  • CONTROL_UN_EDIEL_2
  • CONTROL_UN_2
  • CONTROL_UN_2_1
  • CONTROL_UN_2_2
  • CONTROL_UN_3
  • CONTROL_UN_4
  • CONTROL_EDIG_S_3_2
  • CONTROL_EDIG_S_4

documentServiceId.description:
The ID of the Service used for generating acknowledgements. This information is needed when an
acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements is selected.

outboundAgreementForAckEnvelopeId.description:
The ID of the outbound agreement used for enveloping the acknowledgement. This information is needed when an
acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements is selected.

overrideAckTransportReceiver.description: Specify whether you want to identify a specific party as the receiving party of the acknowledgement. If this option is set to false, the receiver that is specified in the selected outbound agreement is used as the receiving delivery partner of the acknowledgement. This information is needed when an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements is selected.

ackDeliveryExchangeId.description:
The ID of the delivery exchange used for handling the delivery of the acknowledgements. This information is
needed when an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements is selected.

ackTransportReceiverId.description: The ID of the partner selected as the receiving party of the acknowledgement. This information is needed when an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements is selected and the overrideAckTransportReceiver field is set to true.

ackTransportReceiverRoutingId.description: The ID of the Routing Id of the partner selected as the receiving party of the acknowledgement. This information is needed when an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements is selected and the overrideAckTransportReceiver field is set to true.

rejectionRule.description:
The condition for rejecting interchanges. Interchanges are rejected depending on where errors are found. For example, if there is an error in one transaction set, the whole interchange is rejected. The available options are:
  • NONE
  • ENTIRE_INTERCHANGE
  • SAME_TYPE
  • CUSTOM_TYPE

seqCheckControlNumbs.description: Specify whether the interchange control number for inbound messages is verified to be in sequence. For example, if the user sets the next expected interchange control number to 123456, the system validates the next inbound document has an interchange control number of 123456. If the validation succeeds, the field is updated to 123457. If the validation fails, the outOfSequence action is respected.

outOfSeqAction.description:
The action to take for non-sequential numbers, when the seqCheckControlNumbs field is set to true. The following options are available:
  • WARN_AND_PROCESS - allows an inbound interchange to be processed successfully, with a logged warning
  • FAIL_AND_PARK - processing is halted and an error is logged

dupCheckControlNumbs.description: Specify whether the interchange control numbers are checked for duplicates by comparing to interchanges already received. If a duplicate is detected for an inbound interchange, the dupAction is respected.

dupAction.description:
The action to take for duplicate numbers, when the dupCheckControlNumbs field is set to true. The following options are available:
  • WARN_AND_PROCESS - allows an inbound interchange to be processed successfully, with a logged warning
  • FAIL_AND_PARK - processing is halted and an error is logged

seqCheckGroupControlNumbs.description: Specify whether the interchange group control number for inbound messages is verified to be in sequence. For example, if the user sets the next expected interchange group control number to 123456, the system validates the next inbound document has an interchange control number of 123456. If the validation succeeds, the field is updated to 123457. If the validation fails, the outOfSeqAction is respected.

dupCheckGroupControlNumbs.description: Specify whether the interchange group control numbers are checked for duplicates by comparing to interchanges already received. If a duplicate is detected for an inbound interchange group , the dupAction is respected.

documentAgreements.description: List with all document agreements for current agreement

@id.description: The ID of the metadata profile output bean. Read-only field.

name.description: The name of the metadata profile output.

useOutboundAgreement.description: Set this to true to deliver using defined outbound agreement(s).

outboundAgreements.description: The outbound agreement configuration to use for output delivery.

id.description: The unique ID String for routing ID

routingId.description:
The value of the Routing ID. A routing ID can be in any format or length (up to 255 characters),
including standard EDI or custom formats that include special characters or spaces.

type.description:
The type of this Routing ID.
  • For ebXML traders only, enter an ebXML party ID type only if the routing ID you enter is not a URI.
  • For cXML traders only, enter the matching cXML credential domain type

@id.description: The ID of this metadata profile condition.

metadata.description: The metadata rule that applies to the metadata profile.

condition.description: The condition defined for the metadata rule.

value.description: The value defined for the metadata rule.

cipherSuites.description: List with cipher suites.

deleteAfterDownload.description:
Select this if you want the server to delete files after they have been downloaded from it. This option should be
enabled in most cases. If an external server automatically deletes files that have been downloaded, deselect this
option.

enableFiltering.description:
Enabling file filtering allows the trading engine to discriminate which
files to consume based on file names

encodedHostPublicKey.description: SSH/SFTP server's public key. If keyword is used, the key is automatically retrieved.

fileCollisionMode.description:
Use this option to prevent the trading engine from attempting to retrieve partially written files. There may be some specialized servers, typically running on mainframes, that support only part of the FTP protocol (RFC 959). In such cases you may have to clear this check box and take steps of your own to make sure collisions do not occur. If connecting to a partner's B2Bi or Interchange embedded FTP server, use None. This property will be ignored if the filename handling is in append mode.

Options available:

  • None Use this option if the partner's server is B2Bi or Interchange embedded server.
  • Use temp files with inbox

    Type the full path of an inbox directory (for example, c:\data\inbox). Files are uploaded to this directory. When fully written, files are moved to the pickup directory for retrieval. Do not put the inbox under the pickup directory unless you use a period at the beginning of the inbox name. The trading engine and other applications ignore directories and files that begin with periods. For example, do not use the following directory structure: c:\data\pickup\inbox. But you can use the following because a period is the first character of the inbox directory name: c:\data\pickup\.inbox

    When this flag is used, the additional property inboxPath should be set.
  • Use temp file extension

    If you prefer not to use an inbox, select this option. While a file is being written to the pickup directory, a temporary extension is added so the system knows not to retrieve it because the file is only partially written. Once fully written, the temporary extension goes away and the file can be retrieved.

    When this flag is used, the additional property tempFileExtension should be set.

filterPattern.description:
Insert the format of the file names you want the transport
to consume or ignore. Use conventional wildcard characters for file names,
extensions, or both. The following describes the supported characters and symbols:
<p/> <hr/>
*      One or more characters.<p/><hr/>
?      Any single character.<p/><hr/>
[ ]      Matches any single character within the brackets. For example, r[aou]t
matches rat, rot and rut.<p/><hr/>
,      Commas can be used as and/or operators within brackets (for example, r[a,
o,u]t). <p/><hr/>
-      Use hyphens within brackets to specify ranges of letters or numbers. For
example, [0-9] is for any number between 0 and 9, and [A-Za-z] is for any
upper- or lower-case letter. <p/><hr/>
.      Use the character dot to separate the file name and extension. For example,
*.txt.<p/><hr/>
|      Use the pipe character to separate multiple file-name formats. For example,
*.edi|*.txt|[a,b,c]?.xml.<p/>

host.description: The name of the SSH/SFTP server.

hostBasedAuthentication.description:
Whether or not server requires the SFTP client to use host-based authentication. By using this mechanism passwords no longer have to be transferred to the untrusted systems.

Note: per-user SSH public keys can achieve similar effects; but maintaining per-user keys could be an unwanted administrative overhead

inboxPath.description:
Type the full path of an inbox directory (for example, c:\data\inbox). Files are uploaded to this directory. When fully written, files are moved to the pickup directory for retrieval. Do not put the inbox under the pickup directory unless you use a period at the beginning of the inbox name. The trading engine and other applications ignore directories and files that begin with periods. For example, do not use the following directory structure:
 c:\data\pickup\inbox
But you can use the following because a period is the first character of the inbox directory name:
 c:\data\pickup\.inbox

keyUserName.description: This user name applies to both public/private key pair and host-based authentication.

maxBlockSize.description:
The maximum size of the packets that can be downloaded from an external SFTP server by the SFTP client within the trading engine.
The client downloads messages in a series of data packets. By default the maximum size is 32768  data packet units.
The default value is compatible with most SFTP servers. However, when handling messages of a certain size (2-3 megabytes or larger),
some servers cannot process many packets of the default size and downloading hangs. If this occurs, reduce the packet size maximum.

maxMessagesPerConnection.description:
This value specifies the maximum number of messages to be consumed over a single connection before the connection is closed and reopened on another processing node. As such, this setting effectively controls load balancing. The default setting of 1 achieves optimal load balancing at the cost of greater overhead per message. Depending on your message volume and the load on each node, this value could be increased to avoid the overhead associated with reconnecting to the transport server, at the cost of a less well-balanced cluster.

This setting only applies to transports where a list of file names is not available. These include POP, JMS and (for Interchange stand-alone) the Synchrony Integrator exchange point, which is based on JMS. Exchange points such as these are limited to one connection at a time to prevent concurrency problems.

This field is not applicable in a single node environment.

metadataHierarchy.description:
Set message attributes that correspond to the names of subdirectories.
Each item in the selected attributes list represents another subdirectory level.
For example, add "From routing ID" and "To routing ID" to the selected attributes
list in that order. A message with attributes "From routing ID" set to "ABC"
and "To routing ID" set to "DEF" would be delivered to the subdirectory ABC/DEF.

overrideCipherSuites.description: If true, a list of cipher suites should be provided.

passwordAuthentication.description: Whether or not server requires the SFTP client to authenticate using a password

pickupDirectory.description:
The path of the directory on your server where messages are picked up.
When the trading engine polls the server for files, it only looks in the pickup directory, not an inbox directory.

port.description:
The port on which the server listens for incoming connections.
The default port for the SFTP server is 22 (embedded SFTP default for trading is 4022; for application 5022).

privateKeyCredentials.description:
The user name, password and the private key used to connect to server.
This applies to both public/private key pair and host-based authentication

publicKeyAuthentication.description:
Whether or not server requires the SFTP client to use public key authentication.

If this exchange is for a community, add the private key to the community. If this exchange is for a partner, add the public key to any community that will be trading with the partner.

readTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits to read data from the delivery exchange before terminating the connection.
The default is 30 seconds.

sequenceTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds that the trading engine waits for missing messages of a sequence before taking the appropriate action.
This feature avoids the blocking of processing when a sequenced message is not available. Default value is of
60 seconds.

sequenced.description:
Specify whether all messages that are consumed by this pickup should be delivered in their original
consumption order.
<p/>
In B2Bi message-handling, sequential delivery is the ability to deliver messages in the order they
were originally consumed on a specific pickup. This is sometimes referred to as first-in-first-out
(FIFO) behavior.
<p/>
Sequential message delivery is implemented only for trading engine pickups, not for integration
engine pickups

tempFileExtension.description:
If you prefer to not use an inbox, select this option. When a file is being written to the
pickup directory, a temporary extension is added so that the system knows not
to retrieve it because the file is only partially written. Once fully written, the
temporary extension goes away and the file can be retrieved.

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: The user name and its password to connect to the server.

useRFC2204.description: For OFTP V1 only when protocol version is 1.3, this check box tells the trading engine the protocol release level (SSIDLEV) to use for the trading partner. If this option is true, the partner uses the RFC 2204 implementation. This means the SSIDLEV field in the start session (SSID) command has a value of 1. Set this option to false if the partner uses the RFC 5024 implementation. This means the SSIDLEV field in the SSID command has a value of 2. Note that in either case the exchange point is being defined for OFTP protocol revision level 1.3.

oldTransactionNumberValid.description:
Set to true to validate the latest document number (field 05 in the VDA header). Validation means that
B2Bi will validate the number which is referenced in the incoming transmission against what B2Bi has
stored internally as the last processed transmission for this partner (customer / supplier)
combination.

documentAgreements.description: List with all document agreements for current agreement

useSenderIdentification.description:
Specifies if "Partner Code" identification defined in the senders VDA Messaging ID will be used for
detection / matching. The field cannot be modified.

useReceiverIdentification.description:
Specifies if "Partner Code" identification defined in the receivers VDA Messaging ID will be used for
detection / matching. The field cannot be modified.

useSenderVdaRole.description: Specifies if the sender VDA role will be used for detection / matching. The field cannot be modified.

useReceiverVdaRole.description: Specifies if the receiver VDA role will be used for detection / matching. The field cannot be modified.

applicationReference.description:
Identifies whether the transmission contains data for an import application,
an export application, an accounting application. The application reference also
can be used to indicate the status of a transmission (live or test).

priorityCode.description:
The transmission priority code. Values are A, B and C.
This can be used for internal handling purposes, but otherwise is used rarely.

receiverTransmissionCode.description:
An EAN location number (GLN) identifying the transmission receiver (UNTO code).
The interchange parties can agree upon the code.
The value must be 14 or fewer alphanumeric characters.

receiverTransmissionName.description:
Identifies in plain language the transmission receiver (UNTO name).
The interchange parties can agree upon the name.
This value must be 35 or fewer alphanumeric characters.

senderTransmissionCode.description:
An EAN location number (GLN) identifying the transmission sender (FROM code).
The interchange parties can agree upon the code.
The value must be 14 or fewer alphanumeric characters.

senderTransmissionName.description:
Identifies in plain language the transmission sender (FROM name).
The interchange parties can agree upon the name.
This value must be 35 or fewer alphanumeric characters.

syntaxRuleId.description: The syntax rule identifier (STDS). Value can be ANA or ANAA (if reconciliation facility is used).

syntaxRuleVersion.description: The syntax rule version. Value is 1.

applicationReceiverId.description: A code identifying the receiver (GS03) of the message. The trading partners agree upon the codes to use. This is a functional group parameter.

applicationSenderId.description: A code identifying the sender (GS02) of the message. The trading partners agree upon the codes to use. This is a functional group parameter.

interchangeReceiverId.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The information code published by the receiver of the data (ISA08). This is an interchange envelope parameter. This is an interchange envelope parameter.

interchangeReceiverIdQualifier.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The qualifier for designating the system or method of information code structure to designate the receiver ID element being qualified (ISA07). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

interchangeSenderId.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The information code published by the sender for other parties to use as the receiver ID to route data to them (ISA06). When you are sending, the sender uses this as its sending ID. Other parties sending to you use this as a receiving ID route data to them. This is an interchange envelope parameter.

interchangeSenderIdQualifier.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The qualifier for designating the system or method of information code structure used to designate the sender ID element being qualified (ISA05). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

processingMode.description:
Processing mode to use for X12 message handling:

  • ISA_AND_GS (default)

    Select this option to enable the handling of complete X12 messages (including ISA headers).

  • GS_ONLY (X12 only)

    Select this option to enable the handling of X12 messages without ISA headers.

x12TestIndicator.description:
A code (T, I or P) indicating whether data in the interchange envelope is for testing or production
(ISA15). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

localPort.description: The local port used by the embedded PeSIT server to listen for incoming connections. The default value is 1761.

callerIdentification.description:
(For Trading Pickup only) Holds the default identity exposed by the server to the partners. You can override or restrict the the
caller's protocol identity (P14) and password requirements.

serverIdentification.description:
For Trading Pickups, holds the partner password requirements (P15) to connect to this embedded server.

For Application Pickups, holds the back-end client password requirements (P15) to connect to this embedded server.

enableAcks.description:
Send acknowledgments for messages received by this exchange - If you select this option, the server
sends an acknowledgment to the partner when it receives a file successfully. This occurs when the
corresponding message is correctly unpackaged. This is a protocol level acknowledgment, which
indicates only that the trading engine has correctly received the file.

senderServerAckPairs.description:
(For application pickup only)

For each application that expects an acknowledgment:

  • In the Inbound sender field, enter the caller identity (PI3) used by the application to connect. If you do not enter a caller identity, no acknowledgements are sent on this exchange.
  • In the Inbound sender field, to select the community that sends the acknowledgment, and then select the connection string that corresponds to the back-end server which should receive the acknowledgment. This is how you select the delivery exchange that is used to send the acknowledgement.
An acknowledgment is sent to the Sender/Server pair, when the reception is completed and the corresponding incoming message is successfully unpackaged. This means that it is a protocol acknowledgment (the trading engine received the file). A receipt message is generated and sent through the selected integration delivery exchange.

ssl.description: Specify whether Secure Sockets Layer protocol is in use during connections. If this option is set to true, the server presents a certificate for verification. To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

localPort.description:
The local port used by the embedded SFTP server to listen for incoming connections. The default values are 4022
for a trading server and 5022 for an application server.

subDirectories.description:
Subdirectories associated to the SFTP exchange point. A specific combination of user
and directory can be associated with only one exchange.

deleteAfterDownload.description: Specify whether the embedded server should delete files after they have been downloaded from it.

modifySftpServerDirectory.description: Specify whether subdirectory management is enabled on the client side. When this option is set to true, SFTP clients are allowed to add or remove subdirectories.

preserveFilename.description:
Specify whether the original file names should be preserved when the trading engine delivers messages.
Preserving original file names enables your back-end application to process binary messages based on their
file names.

overwriteIfDuplicate.description:
Specify whether when the trading engine detects a duplicate file name, it should overwrite the existing file,
replacing it with the duplicate file.

defaultUser.description: Default account for the SFTP server.

acceptGroups.description: Specify whether group segments are accepted.

groupTimeout.description: The time limit in hours and minutes before groups time out (when group segments are accepted). The 24-hour format is HH:MM.

groupTimeoutAction.description:
The action to perform if group messages are missing (when group segments are accepted). The available options are:
  • SEND_AND_WARN
  • SEND
  • STOP

maxNumbDocs.description: The largest number of entries the envelope can contain.

envelopeTimeout.description: The envelope timeout in hours and minutes. The 24-hour format is HH:MM.

localPort.description: The local port used by the embedded MLLP server to listen for incoming connections.

ssl.description: Specify whether Secure Sockets Layer protocol is in use during connections. If this option is set to true, the server presents a certificate for verification. To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

pollingIntervalSeconds.description: Returns the interval in seconds the trading engine waits before polling for messages to retrieve.

maxMessagesPerPollingInterval.description: Returns the highest number of messages the system can retrieve each time it polls.

keyId.description: The keyId is string identifier for the Public Key.

level.description:
A signer indicates a level of trust ranging from low to high.
For example, a self-signed certificate is by default signed
by the community that generated the certificate within B2Bi.
The community gives the certificate a positive level, which
is a high level of trust.

userName.description: The username refers to Community name and email

serverSettingsId.description: Embedded server settings id of the embedded exchange point.

shouldParseMetadataFromHeader.description:
Parse SOAP headers into message metadata - Select this option if you want to SOAP headers to be carried as
metadata attributes with the message.

xpaths.description: If shouldParseMetadataFromHeader is selected, enter the XPath expressions to resolve the header.

shouldIntegrateBody.description: Process SOAP Body - Select this option to process the contents of the SOAP body.

shouldIntegrateAttachments.description: Process Attachments - Select this option to process the attachments of the SOAP message.

groupAttachments.description:
Group Attachments - Select this option to enable the consumed message to be split into parent and dependent
child messages.

host.description: The name of the FTP server.

port.description: The port on which the server listens for incoming connections. The default is 21 (embedded FTP default is 4021).

pickupDirectory.description:
Path of the directory on your server where messages are
picked up. When the trading engine polls the server for files, it only looks in the pickup
directory, not in an inbox directory. If connecting to a partner's B2Bi embedded FTP server,
use a mailbox if picking up. Leave the field blank if delivering.

connectTimeoutSeconds.description: The maximum time in seconds the component waits for a reply from the server before disconnecting.

readTimeoutSeconds.description: Select this option to keep open the server connection for additional FTP requests.

passive.description: Set this option to true to transmit file using passive mode. Clear this option to use active mode.

transferType.description:
Format of the files that are transmitted over this delivery exchange:
  • Binary (default)
  • Ascii automatic line ending
  • Ascii user CR/LF
  • Ascii use LF only

commandSetConfigPath.description: The script that specifies commands sent to the host is the XML command set document, named ftpcommandset.xml. Default location is in [install directory]\conf. It contains a set of metacommands, each consisting of one or more FTP commands to be sent to an FTP server.

attemptRestarts.description:
Indicates whether the system resumes transferring large files at the interruption point,
when a connection is lost before a transfer is completed.
If selected, the system resumes the processing of files that are at least as large as
specified in the restartable minimum bytes field. This checkpoint-restart
feature is worthwhile only for large documents. If this option is not used,
the system starts a file transfer over when processing is interrupted.

restartableMinKiloBytes.description:
If attempt restarts is selected, the minimum size of a file that triggers the
system to continue the file transfer at the point interrupted before the
connection was lost. The minimum size is in megabytes. The system only resumes
transfers of files that meet this minimum. The system restarts the transfer
of smaller files whose processing is interrupted.

tempFileHoursToLive.description:
If attempt restarts is selected, how long the system retains a file whose transfer
has been interrupted while waiting for the connection to be restored.
This temporary file enables the system to resume the transfer at the point interrupted.

deliveryFilenameMode.description:
This property is used when the trading engine delivers messages.

Ftp Delivery Filename Options:
  • Preserve original

    Select this option if you want original file names to be preserved when the trading engine delivers messages.
  • Auto generate

    If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine appends a number to the new file. For FTP and SFTP the appended number is hexadecimal, with the format: filename_c4.
  • Custom generate

    When this option is used, the additional property userDefinedDeliveryFilename must be set.

duplicateFileNameMode.description:
We recommend using this option to prevent the trading engine from attempting to retrieve partially written files.There may be some specialized servers, typically running on mainframes, that support only part of the FTP protocol (RFC 959). In such cases you may have to take steps of your own to make sure collisions do not occur. Ftp Duplicate File Name Options:
  • Overwrite

    If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine overwrites the existing file.
  • Auto generate

    Automatically generate unique filenames.
  • Append

    If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine appends a number to the new file. For FTP and SFTP the appended number is hexadecimal, with the format: filename_c4.
  • Custom generate

    When this flag is used, the additional property userDefinedDuplicateFilename must be set.

userCommands.description:
Enter user commands such as SITE to be sent to the server after login. Commands must be entered in the exact case and format expected by the server. For example, most FTP clients allow mkdir test, but most servers only accept MKD test.

Consult RFC 959 for a list of standard FTP commands. You can use FTP commands that do not make use of the FTP data connection. Commands that make use of the FTP data connection are not supported. In addition, specific servers may support other commands. Refer to the server documentation for more information.

If any command fails, the remaining commands are not executed, and production to the FTP server fails. To avoid possible failures, preface any command with an (at) sign (@) to indicate that errors from that command should be ignored, for example, @MKD test. Preface any command with an asterisk to cause the entire line to be treated as a comment, for example, *Create test directory.

fixOutputFilenames.description:
Return true if output filenames are to be processed through the FilenameBeautifier to make sure they
don't contain any characters that would offend certain FTP servers.  This includes always prefixing
filenames that begin with a number with the letter "a".

fileCollisionMode.description:
It is recommended to use this option to prevent the trading engine from attempting to retrieve partially written files. There may be some specialized servers, typically running on mainframes, that support only part of the FTP protocol (RFC 959). In such cases you may have to clear this option and take steps of your own to make sure collisions do not occur. If connecting to a partner's Interchange embedded FTP server, use None. This property will be ignored if the filename handling is in append mode.

Options available:

  • NoneUse this option if the partner's server is an Interchange embedded server.
  • Use temp files with inbox

    Type the full path of an inbox directory (for example, c:\data\inbox). Files are uploaded to this directory. When fully written, files are moved to the pickup directory for retrieval. Do not put the inbox under the pickup directory unless you use a period at the beginning of the inbox name. The trading engine and other applications ignore directories and files that begin with periods. For example, do not use the following directory structure:
      c:\data\pickup\inbox
    But you can use the following because a period is the first character of the inbox directory name:
      c:\data\pickup\.inbox

    When this flag is used, the additional property inboxPath should be set.
  • Use temp file extension

    If you prefer not to use an inbox, select this option. While a file is being written to the pickup directory, a temporary extension is added so the system knows not to retrieve it because the file is only partially written. Once fully written, the temporary extension goes away and the file can be retrieved.

    When this flag is used, the additional property tempFileExtension should be set.

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: The user name and its password to connect to the server.

inboxPath.description:
Type the full path of an inbox directory (for example, c:\data\inbox). Files are uploaded to this directory. When fully written, files are moved to the pickup directory for retrieval. Do not put the inbox under the pickup directory unless you use a period at the beginning of the inbox name. The trading engine and other applications ignore directories and files that begin with periods. For example, do not use the following directory structure:
 c:\data\pickup\inbox
But you can use the following because a period is the first character of the inbox directory name:
 c:\data\pickup\.inbox

tempFileExtension.description:
If you prefer to not use an inbox, select this option. When a file is being written to the
pickup directory, a temporary extension is added so that the system knows not
to retrieve it because the file is only partially written. Once fully written, the
temporary extension goes away and the file can be retrieved.

metadataHierarchy.description:
Set message attributes that correspond to the names of subdirectories.
Each item in the selected attributes list represents another subdirectory level.
For example, if you add "From routing ID" and "To routing ID" to the selected
attributes list in that order, a message with attributes "From routing ID"
set to "ABC" and "To routing ID" set to "DEF" is delivered to the subdirectory ABC/DEF.

activePorts.description:
Used when the server is in active mode (passive property set to true).
, ; - is the list of separators for port numbers. Ex: 5555,5556-5565

userDefinedDuplicateFilename.description: Use items such as $filename$, $extension$, $timestamp$, $sequence$ and $filesequence$ one time.

cipherSuites.description: List with cipher suites.

ssl.description: Regular or secured FTP channel with authentication

implicitSsl.description: Implicit security is a mechanism by which security is automatically turned on as soon as the FTP client makes a connection to an FTP server. In this case, the FTP server defines a specific port for the client (990) to be used for secure connections. FTP over SSL Implicit has been deprecated and should no longer be used.

enableHostnameVerification.description:
SSL authentication.  If we're acting as the client, true means we should verify that the
hostname for the certificate given to us by the server matches the host we connected to.
If we're acting as the server, true means we require the client to present its
certificate ("client authentication").

overrideCipherSuites.description: If true, a list of cipher suites should be provided.

deleteAfterDownload.description:
Select this if you want the server to delete files after they have been downloaded from it. This option should be enabled in most cases. If an external server automatically deletes files that have been downloaded, deselect this option.
Note: This field is used only in integration.

enableFiltering.description:
Enabling file filtering allows the trading engine to discriminate which files to consume based on file names
Note: This field is used only in integration

filterPattern.description:
Insert the format of the file names you want the transport to consume or ignore. Use conventional wildcard characters for file names or extensions or both. The following describes the supported characters and symbols:

*      One or more characters.

?      Any single character.

[ ]      Matches any single character within the brackets. For example, r[aou]t matches rat, rot and rut.

,      Commas can be used as and/or operators within brackets (for example, r[a, o,u]t).

-      Use hyphens within brackets to specify ranges of letters or numbers. For example, [0-9] is for any number between 0 and 9, and [A-Za-z] is for any upper- or lower-case letter.

.      Use the character dot to separate the file name and extension. For example, *.txt.

|      Use the pipe character to separate multiple file name formats. For example, *.edi|*.txt|[a,b,c]?.xml.


Note: This field is used only in integration.

applyNegativeFiltering.description:
Specify whether the filter pattern is inclusive or exclusive.

If set to false it is inclusive, only files matching the pattern are consumed. If set to true it is exclusive, files matching the pattern are ignored, but all other files are consumed.
Note: This field is used only in integration.

senderTransmissionReferenceGenerator.description: Generator for reference number. Default value is $TransRef:9$.

recipientTransmissionReference.description: The reference for the transmission to the sender, if known.

sequenceNumberGenerator.description: Generator for previous document number. The default value is "$TransNumber:5$".

localPort.description:
The local port used by the embedded SMTP server to listen for incoming connections.
The default value is 4026.

sequenceTimeoutSeconds.description: Value of sequence timeout in seconds. <p/>

sequenced.description:
Set this option to true if you want all messages that are consumed by this pickup to be delivered in their
original consumption order. <p/>

attachmentsOnly.description:
Set this option to true to eliminate extraneous message fragments. This option is applicable when the
partners send messages using a mail client such as Microsoft Outlook. It is available under the generic email
message protocol, but not AS1.

When a partner uses a mail client application to send a trading document as an attachment to an email message,
the trading engine actually receives two or more documents. These can include the MIME header, the text of the
email message and the document attachment. The trading engine tracks and processes the incidental MIME body parts
just as it does any document. Although such processing does no harm, it can cause confusion.	Setting this option
to true causes the incidental MIME body parts to be ignored while preserving the important document attachments.

emailAddress.description: The email address that the remote partners use to send messages to the local community.

senderIdentificationType.description:
Specify how the sender will be identified; must be set to 'PD_EMAIL_ADDRESSES' or
'PARTNER_EMAIL_ACCOUNTS'.

definitionName.description:
Name to be displayed in the UI wizard for selecting a transport.
This name will be displayed along with built-in transport names such as "Ftp", "File system", etc.
For consistency with existing names, use an initial capital letter, and no period at the end.

settings.description: Defines setting string to be passed to the implementation class when a pluggable transport is created

json_NotImplementedException.title: NotImplementedException
json_NotImplementedException.description:
Base class for all API exceptions.  Any class that extends this will automatically get mapped to the correct
HTTP return code and the exception message will be populated in the response body.

activePorts.description:
Used when the server is in active mode (passive property set to true).
, ; - is the list of separators for port numbers. Ex: 5555,5556-5565

applyNegativeFiltering.description:
Specify whether the filter pattern is inclusive or exclusive.

If set to false it is inclusive, only files matching the pattern are consumed. If set to true it is exclusive, files matching the pattern are ignored, but all other files are consumed.
Note: This field is used only in integration.

attemptRestarts.description:
Indicates whether the system resumes transferring large files at the interruption point,
when a connection is lost before a transfer is completed.
If selected, the system resumes the processing of files that are at least as large as
specified in the restartable minimum bytes field. This checkpoint-restart
feature is worthwhile only for large documents. If this option is not used,
the system starts a file transfer over when processing is interrupted.

cipherSuites.description: List with cipher suites.

commandSetConfigPath.description: The script that specifies commands sent to the host is the XML command set document, named ftpcommandset.xml. Default location is in [install directory]\conf. It contains a set of metacommands, each consisting of one or more FTP commands to be sent to an FTP server.

connectTimeoutSeconds.description: The maximum time in seconds the component waits for a reply from the server before disconnecting.

deleteAfterDownload.description:
Select this if you want the server to delete files after they have been downloaded from it. This option should be enabled in most cases. If an external server automatically deletes files that have been downloaded, deselect this option.
Note: This field is used only in integration.

deliveryFilenameMode.description:
This property is used when the trading engine delivers messages.

Ftp Delivery Filename Options:
  • Preserve original

    Select this option if you want original file names to be preserved when the trading engine delivers messages.
  • Auto generate

    If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine appends a number to the new file. For FTP and SFTP the appended number is hexadecimal, with the format: filename_c4.
  • Custom generate

    When this option is used, the additional property userDefinedDeliveryFilename must be set.

duplicateFileNameMode.description:
We recommend using this option to prevent the trading engine from attempting to retrieve partially written files.There may be some specialized servers, typically running on mainframes, that support only part of the FTP protocol (RFC 959). In such cases you may have to take steps of your own to make sure collisions do not occur. Ftp Duplicate File Name Options:
  • Overwrite

    If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine overwrites the existing file.
  • Auto generate

    Automatically generate unique filenames.
  • Append

    If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine appends a number to the new file. For FTP and SFTP the appended number is hexadecimal, with the format: filename_c4.
  • Custom generate

    When this flag is used, the additional property userDefinedDuplicateFilename must be set.

enableFiltering.description:
Enabling file filtering allows the trading engine to discriminate which files to consume based on file names
Note: This field is used only in integration

enableHostnameVerification.description:
SSL authentication.  If we're acting as the client, true means we should verify that the
hostname for the certificate given to us by the server matches the host we connected to.
If we're acting as the server, true means we require the client to present its
certificate ("client authentication").

fileCollisionMode.description:
It is recommended to use this option to prevent the trading engine from attempting to retrieve partially written files. There may be some specialized servers, typically running on mainframes, that support only part of the FTP protocol (RFC 959). In such cases you may have to clear this option and take steps of your own to make sure collisions do not occur. If connecting to a partner's Interchange embedded FTP server, use None. This property will be ignored if the filename handling is in append mode.

Options available:

  • NoneUse this option if the partner's server is an Interchange embedded server.
  • Use temp files with inbox

    Type the full path of an inbox directory (for example, c:\data\inbox). Files are uploaded to this directory. When fully written, files are moved to the pickup directory for retrieval. Do not put the inbox under the pickup directory unless you use a period at the beginning of the inbox name. The trading engine and other applications ignore directories and files that begin with periods. For example, do not use the following directory structure:
      c:\data\pickup\inbox
    But you can use the following because a period is the first character of the inbox directory name:
      c:\data\pickup\.inbox

    When this flag is used, the additional property inboxPath should be set.
  • Use temp file extension

    If you prefer not to use an inbox, select this option. While a file is being written to the pickup directory, a temporary extension is added so the system knows not to retrieve it because the file is only partially written. Once fully written, the temporary extension goes away and the file can be retrieved.

    When this flag is used, the additional property tempFileExtension should be set.

filterPattern.description:
Insert the format of the file names you want the transport to consume or ignore. Use conventional wildcard characters for file names or extensions or both. The following describes the supported characters and symbols:

*      One or more characters.

?      Any single character.

[ ]      Matches any single character within the brackets. For example, r[aou]t matches rat, rot and rut.

,      Commas can be used as and/or operators within brackets (for example, r[a, o,u]t).

-      Use hyphens within brackets to specify ranges of letters or numbers. For example, [0-9] is for any number between 0 and 9, and [A-Za-z] is for any upper- or lower-case letter.

.      Use the character dot to separate the file name and extension. For example, *.txt.

|      Use the pipe character to separate multiple file name formats. For example, *.edi|*.txt|[a,b,c]?.xml.


Note: This field is used only in integration.

fixOutputFilenames.description:
Return true if output filenames are to be processed through the FilenameBeautifier to make sure they
don't contain any characters that would offend certain FTP servers.  This includes always prefixing
filenames that begin with a number with the letter "a".

host.description: The name of the FTP server.

implicitSsl.description: Implicit security is a mechanism by which security is automatically turned on as soon as the FTP client makes a connection to an FTP server. In this case, the FTP server defines a specific port for the client (990) to be used for secure connections. FTP over SSL Implicit has been deprecated and should no longer be used.

inboxPath.description:
Type the full path of an inbox directory (for example, c:\data\inbox). Files are uploaded to this directory. When fully written, files are moved to the pickup directory for retrieval. Do not put the inbox under the pickup directory unless you use a period at the beginning of the inbox name. The trading engine and other applications ignore directories and files that begin with periods. For example, do not use the following directory structure:
 c:\data\pickup\inbox
But you can use the following because a period is the first character of the inbox directory name:
 c:\data\pickup\.inbox

metadataHierarchy.description:
Set message attributes that correspond to the names of subdirectories.
Each item in the selected attributes list represents another subdirectory level.
For example, if you add "From routing ID" and "To routing ID" to the selected
attributes list in that order, a message with attributes "From routing ID"
set to "ABC" and "To routing ID" set to "DEF" is delivered to the subdirectory ABC/DEF.

overrideCipherSuites.description: If true, a list of cipher suites should be provided.

passive.description: Set this option to true to transmit file using passive mode. Clear this option to use active mode.

pickupDirectory.description:
Path of the directory on your server where messages are
picked up. When the trading engine polls the server for files, it only looks in the pickup
directory, not in an inbox directory. If connecting to a partner's B2Bi embedded FTP server,
use a mailbox if picking up. Leave the field blank if delivering.

port.description: The port on which the server listens for incoming connections. The default is 21 (embedded FTP default is 4021).

readTimeoutSeconds.description: Select this option to keep open the server connection for additional FTP requests.

restartableMinKiloBytes.description:
If attempt restarts is selected, the minimum size of a file that triggers the
system to continue the file transfer at the point interrupted before the
connection was lost. The minimum size is in megabytes. The system only resumes
transfers of files that meet this minimum. The system restarts the transfer
of smaller files whose processing is interrupted.

ssl.description: Regular or secured FTP channel with authentication

tempFileExtension.description:
If you prefer to not use an inbox, select this option. When a file is being written to the
pickup directory, a temporary extension is added so that the system knows not
to retrieve it because the file is only partially written. Once fully written, the
temporary extension goes away and the file can be retrieved.

tempFileHoursToLive.description:
If attempt restarts is selected, how long the system retains a file whose transfer
has been interrupted while waiting for the connection to be restored.
This temporary file enables the system to resume the transfer at the point interrupted.

transferType.description:
Format of the files that are transmitted over this delivery exchange:
  • Binary (default)
  • Ascii automatic line ending
  • Ascii user CR/LF
  • Ascii use LF only

userCommands.description:
Enter user commands such as SITE to be sent to the server after login. Commands must be entered in the exact case and format expected by the server. For example, most FTP clients allow mkdir test, but most servers only accept MKD test.

Consult RFC 959 for a list of standard FTP commands. You can use FTP commands that do not make use of the FTP data connection. Commands that make use of the FTP data connection are not supported. In addition, specific servers may support other commands. Refer to the server documentation for more information.

If any command fails, the remaining commands are not executed, and production to the FTP server fails. To avoid possible failures, preface any command with an (at) sign (@) to indicate that errors from that command should be ignored, for example, @MKD test. Preface any command with an asterisk to cause the entire line to be treated as a comment, for example, *Create test directory.

userDefinedDuplicateFilename.description: Use items such as $filename$, $extension$, $timestamp$, $sequence$ and $filesequence$ one time.

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: The user name and its password to connect to the server.

json_ForbiddenException.title: ForbiddenException
json_ForbiddenException.description: Exception that maps to HTTP 403 return code

parameters.description:
Define the parameter string to be passed for a specific type of B2Bi exchange point. For more information about
the specific parameters to be passed for each type of B2Bi exchange point, please see the admin guide.

type.description: The type of the B2Bi exchange point.

password.description: The password for the SFTP account to connect to the server.

userName.description:
The user name to connect to the server. The name is used not only for connection, but also represents
the home directory for the SFTP account.

enabled.description: Specify whether the SFTP account is enabled.

hasCredentials.description:
Specify where the account has associated credentials. The accounts might not have credentials if the server
uses public/private key pair authentication

passwordPolicyName.description:
The name of the password policy to assign to the user. A default password policy is in effect globally for all
transport users. You can override the default policy by adding one or more user-defined policies and assigning
policies to specific users.

sftpSubDirectories.description:
Subdirectories associated to the SFTP account. A specific combination of user
and directory can be associated with only one exchange.

sshPublicKeys.description:
Returns the RSA or DSK qualified SSH key for the user. Multiple keys may be combined in one string and will be separated by a carriage return or carriage return + line feed.

Note: if multiple keys are present it is best to parse the keys using a BufferedReader wrapped with a StringReader which takes this data a value.

backupMessages.description:
Indicates whether the system backs up copies of the messages it retrieves from integration or receives
from partners.

businessProtocol.description: The business protocol associated with this exchange point.

enabled.description: Returns if this exchange point is enabled.

friendlyName.description: The friendly name for this exchange point.

id.description: The unique id String for the exchange point.

maxConcurrentConnections.description:
(For partner trading delivery only.) The number of total open connections the trading engine server can make to a partner. If you are operating in a cluster environment, this is the total number across the entire cluster, no matter how many JVM nodes are running. For example, if the value is 100 connections and there are 150 messages to send, the trading engine opens only 100 connections to that partner. The remaining 50 messages are queued until connections become available.

The default value is suitable in almost all cases. However, if a partner says your trading engine is over running his receiving system, decrease the value. (This advice does not apply to OFTP X.25 or X.25 over ISDN, as the default maximum value is 1 for those transports.)If sending messages to Transfer CFT via PeSIT (PeSIT), the value in this field must be less than the CFTTCP setting in Transfer CFT.

partyId.description:
Return the party id that owns the exchange point. Can be null if this is an application pickup, or if this
exchange point has not yet been associated with a business protocol.

requiresBusinessProtocol.description:
Return if an exchange point must be associated with a business protocol.

Returns true for exchange point which are associated with a trading pickup/delivery and false for application pickups/delivery.

eventType.description: MSH-0009 (Message Header Segment) field that indicates the response event type. This field is not required on response or acknowledgement process.

messageStructure.description: MSH-0009 (Message Header Segment) field that indicates the message type (Example: ADT, ORU, ACK).

useEventType.description: Enables event type for detection / matching.

useMessageStructure.description: Enables message structure for detection / matching.

id.description: The ID of the argument that belongs to a specific parameter set.

name.description: The name of the argument. This is a read-only field.

type.description: The type of the argument. This is a read-only field.

sharedOftpExchangePointToPollId.description:
Select the partner delivery exchange to share, if any are available. The available choices are OFTP V1
or OFTP V2 delivery exchanges for other partners. The user interface only allows selecting delivery
exchanges of the same type being added. For example, if you are adding an OFTP V1 exchange, only OFTP
V1 selections are available.

coreId.description: The parent core id of the message

loggerId.description: The logger id of the message

message.description: The description of the log event

severity.description: The severity of the log event

timestamp.description: The timestamp of the log event

maxThreads.description: The most threads the trading engine can dedicate to the server.

minThreads.description: The least number of threads the trading engine must dedicate to the server.

networkSettings.description:
The network settings for this server. The following types are supported:
  1. TCP. Transmission Control Protocol is the basic communications protocol of the Internet.
  2. X.25. An ITU-T standard protocol suite for packet-switched wide area network communications.
  3. X.25 over ISDN (B-channel). Integrated Services Digital Network broadband channel supports data transfers over telephone networks

shouldSubmitCertificate.description: Used for hiding the SSL server certificate URI; true if the entity was newly persisted and false otherwise

callerIdentification.description:
(For Trading Pickup only) Holds the default identity exposed by the server to the partners. You can override or restrict the the
caller's protocol identity (P14) and password requirements.

enableAcks.description:
Send acknowledgments for messages received by this exchange - If you select this option, the server
sends an acknowledgment to the partner when it receives a file successfully. This occurs when the
corresponding message is correctly unpackaged. This is a protocol level acknowledgment, which
indicates only that the trading engine has correctly received the file.

localPort.description: The local port used by the embedded PeSIT server to listen for incoming connections. The default value is 1761.

senderServerAckPairs.description:
(For application pickup only)

For each application that expects an acknowledgment:

  • In the Inbound sender field, enter the caller identity (PI3) used by the application to connect. If you do not enter a caller identity, no acknowledgements are sent on this exchange.
  • In the Inbound sender field, to select the community that sends the acknowledgment, and then select the connection string that corresponds to the back-end server which should receive the acknowledgment. This is how you select the delivery exchange that is used to send the acknowledgement.
An acknowledgment is sent to the Sender/Server pair, when the reception is completed and the corresponding incoming message is successfully unpackaged. This means that it is a protocol acknowledgment (the trading engine received the file). A receipt message is generated and sent through the selected integration delivery exchange.

serverIdentification.description:
For Trading Pickups, holds the partner password requirements (P15) to connect to this embedded server.

For Application Pickups, holds the back-end client password requirements (P15) to connect to this embedded server.

ssl.description: Specify whether Secure Sockets Layer protocol is in use during connections. If this option is set to true, the server presents a certificate for verification. To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

recipientApplicationId.description: (UNG 007 0044) Identifies the party receiving the transmission. This code is agreed by the trading partners.

recipientCodeQualifier.description: (UNG 007 0007) Qualifier referring to the source of codes for the identifiers of interchanging partners.

senderApplicationId.description: (UNG 006 0040) Identifies the party sending the transmission. This code is agreed to by trading partners.

senderCodeQualifier.description: (UNG 006 0007) Qualifier referring to the source of codes for the identifiers of interchanging partners.

useApplicationPassword.description: Specify whether the applicationPassword field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useFunctionalGroupId.description: Specify whether the functionalGroupId field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useRecipientApplicationId.description: Specify whether the recipientApplicationId field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useRecipientCodeQualifier.description: Specify whether the recipientCodeQualifier field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useSenderApplicationId.description: Specify whether the senderApplicationId field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useSenderCodeQualifier.description: Specify whether the senderCodeQualifier field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

documentFormat.description: The documentStandard or format that applies to the document that is to be exchanged between partners.

documentType.description: The type of document that is to be exchanged between partners.

documentVersion.description: The documentVersion of the document that is to be exchanged between partners.

id.description: The id of this Document Agreement Output.

name.description: The name of the Document Agreement Output. This cannot be modified.

outboundAgreements.description: The outbound agreement configuration to use for output delivery.

outputType.description:
Select one of the following:

  • USE_INBOUND_RECEIVER - Use inbound agreement receiver as delivery partner

    This is the default behavior of the document agreement.

  • USE_ALTERNATE_DELIVERY_PARTNER

    Select this option if you want to specify a partner (other than the inbound agreement receiver) as the destination of outbound messages. The partner you select must have a valid Routing ID and a delivery exchange defined.

  • USE_OUTBOUND_AGREEMENT

    Select this option to link the document agreement to an outbound agreement.

  • USE_NONE

    This option is the default when the Service used by the owning Document Agreement delivers to an Application. It can be selected only when the Service delivers to Application or when the Service delivers to Partner but the Agreement has no explicit receiver.

useEnvelopingProfile.description:
Set to one of the following:

  • true - Deliver using defined outbound agreement(s)

    Select this option if you want to specify an outbound agreement to use for the output delivery.

  • false - Deliver using best matching outbound agreement

    Select this option if you want to let B2Bi select the outbound agreement to link to this agreement. The trading engine selects the best matching agreement from the available agreements. If no matching outbound agreement is found, a message is generated to Message Log.

testFlag.description: Set this field to true if the agreement is for testing and not for production.

useReceiverIdentification.description: Enable receiver identification for detection/matching. </br> This is a read-only field.

useSenderIdentification.description: Enable sender identification for detection/matching. </br> This is a read-only field.

useTestFlag.description: If true, testFlag will be used for detection / matching.

url.description:
Return the URL associated with this exchange point. For delivery exchanges either on the trading or
integration side, and for polling pickup exchanges like FTP client and file system client, this should
always have a value in the database (unless the exchange isn't complete). The same is true for embedded
HTTP exchanges. For other types of exchanges such as embedded FTP, the URL in the database may be null.
Such exchanges should override this method and dynamically return a URL built from values derived from
places like their settings object (and primary FtpUser in the case of FTP).
<p/>
Worst case, this method will return remoteUrl if url is null.

businessProtocol.description: The business protocol associated with this exchange point.

enabled.description: Returns if this exchange point is enabled.

friendlyName.description: The friendly name for this exchange point.

backupMessages.description:
Indicates whether the system backs up copies of the messages it retrieves from integration or receives
from partners.

maxConcurrentConnections.description:
(For partner trading delivery only.) The number of total open connections the trading engine server can make to a partner. If you are operating in a cluster environment, this is the total number across the entire cluster, no matter how many JVM nodes are running. For example, if the value is 100 connections and there are 150 messages to send, the trading engine opens only 100 connections to that partner. The remaining 50 messages are queued until connections become available.

The default value is suitable in almost all cases. However, if a partner says your trading engine is over running his receiving system, decrease the value. (This advice does not apply to OFTP X.25 or X.25 over ISDN, as the default maximum value is 1 for those transports.)If sending messages to Transfer CFT via PeSIT (PeSIT), the value in this field must be less than the CFTTCP setting in Transfer CFT.

inlineProcessors.description: Returns the list of inline processors that are associated with this exchange point.

inlinePostProcessors.description: Returns the list of inline post processors that are associated with this exchange point.

schedule.description: Returns the schedule that is associated with this exchange point.

callerIdentification.description: Holds the caller's protocol identity (P13) and password requirements. <p/>

name.description: Functional group name

functionalGroupId.description: (GS 479) Identifies a group of application related transaction sets.

senderMessagingId.description: (GS 142) Identifies the party sending the transmission. This code is agreed to by trading partners.

receiverMessagingId.description: (GS 124) Identifies the party receiving transmission. This code is agreed to by trading partners.

responsibleAgencyCode.description: (GS 455) Identifies the issuer of the standard. This code is used in conjunction with GS 480 below.

identifierCode.description:
(GS480) Code indicating the version, release, sub-release, and industry identifier of the EDI standard
being used, including the GS and GE segments. If code in DE455 in GS segment is X, then in DE 480
positions 1-3 are the version number; positions 4-6 are the release and subrelease, level of the
version; and positions 7-12 are the industry or trade association identifiers (optionally assigned by
user); if code in DE455 in GS segment is T, then other formats are allowed.

timeFormat.description:
Select one of the following time formats:
  • HHMM
  • HHMMSS
  • HHMMSSD
  • HHSSMMDD

controlNumberGenerator.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The data interchange information code control number. This is the starting value of unique identifiers for outbound messages. By default, the identifier increases by 1 for each additional message (ISA13). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

directory.description:
The full path for a unique directory where the trading engine picks up messages. If the directory does not exist,
the trading engine creates it for you.
<p/>
You must specify a unique directory name. You may want to give the directory a name that indicates that the transport
is being used for integration or receiving messages from partners.

filterOption.description:
Enabling file filtering allows the trading engine to discriminate which
files to consume based on file names  <p/>

negativeFilterOption.description:
Specify whether the filter pattern is inclusive or exclusive. <p/>
If set to false it is inclusive: only files matching the pattern are consumed. If set to true it is exclusive:
files matching the pattern are ignored, but all other files are consumed.

filterConditions.description:
Insert the formats of the files you want the transport
to consume or ignore. Use conventional wildcard characters for file names or
extensions or both. The following describes the supported characters and symbols:
<p/> <hr/>
*      One or more characters.<p/><hr/>
?      Any single character.<p/><hr/>
[ ]      Matches any single character within the brackets. For example, r[aou]t
matches rat, rot and rut.<p/><hr/>
,      Commas can be used as and/or operators within brackets (for example, r[a,
o,u]t). <p/><hr/>
-      Use hyphens within brackets to specify ranges of letters or numbers. For
example, [0-9] is for any number between 0 and 9, and [A-Za-z] is for any
upper- or lower-case letter. <p/><hr/>
.      Use the character dot to separate the file name and extension. For example,
*.txt.<p/><hr/>
|      Use the pipe character to separate multiple file name formats. For example,
*.edi|*.txt|[a,b,c]?.xml.<p/>

metadataHierarchy.description:
You can use metadata hierarchy to avoid file name collisions by selecting message attributes that
correspond to the names of subdirectories. <p/>
Each item added represents another subdirectory level. For example, add "From routing ID" and "To
routing ID" to the selected attributes list in that order. Then, place a message in a subdirectory
named "ABC/DEF". The message will be assigned a "From routing ID" attribute set to "ABC" and a
"To routing ID" set to "DEF".

className.description: The server class of the pluggable server.

maxMessagesPerPollingInterval.description: Returns the highest number of messages the system can retrieve each time it polls.

pollingIntervalSeconds.description: Returns the interval in seconds the trading engine waits before polling for messages to retrieve.

serverName.description: The name of the transport server, used to distinguish it from other embedded servers.

settings.description: Enter name/value pairs as custom parameters.

ftpUserName.description: Get the name of the FTP user.

subDirectory.description:
User's subdirectory where the messages will be written.
The user subdirectories for each exchange are different.

directory.description:
The full path for a unique directory where the trading engine routes messages. If the directory does not exist, the trading
engine creates it for you.
<p/>
You must specify a unique directory name. You may want to give the directory a name that indicates whether the transport is being used for integration, or sending messages to
partners.

metadataHierarchy.description:
You can use metadata hierarchy to avoid file name collisions by selecting message attributes that
correspond to the names of subdirectories. <p/>
Each item added represents another subdirectory level. For example, add "From routing ID" and "To
routing ID" to the selected attributes list in that order. Then, place a message in a subdirectory
named "ABC/DEF". The message will be assigned a "From routing ID" attribute set to "ABC" and a
"To routing ID" set to "DEF".

preserveFilename.description:
Set this to true if you want original file names to be preserved when the trading engine delivers messages.
<p/>
For binary messages, we recommend that you preserve original file names. Otherwise, the trading engine assigns a
unique file name that does not readily identify the contents of the file. Preserving original file names also allows
your back-end application to process binary messages based on their file names.

preserveFilenameMode.description:
File Name Preserve Mode Option:
  • Overwrite duplicate filenames

    An option when you choose to preserve original file names. If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine overwrites the existing file.

  • Sequentially number duplicate filenames

    An option when you choose to preserve original file names. If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine appends a number to the new file.

  • Generate unique filenames

    Select to have the system provide a unique file name instead of using the original name. This field applies to community integration delivery exchanges and partner delivery exchanges only. When selected, files are given arbitrary names. The names always have less than 30 characters and often have less than 20 characters.

    Appended to the file name is a hex representation of a monotonically increasing file name counter that is maintained in the database and guaranteed to be unique across all nodes in a cluster. In addition, if the original file name had an extension, the same extension is appended to the unique name the system generates.

    The following are examples of unique file names generated by the system, one with the original file extension and one without:

    • dabeed45_4cb.edi
