    • z47e4120_4ce

userDefinedDeliveryFilename.description:
The pattern for the name of the message file sent to a partner. You can enter any combination of the following elements in the userDefinedDeliveryFilename or userDefinedDuplicateFilename fields for Delivery exchange file naming action:
  • Literal strings

  • %metadata name%

    You can use any metadata attribute associated with the FTP or File System delivery. You cannot use Custom attributes.

  • $filename$

  • $extension$

  • $timestamp$

    Where timestamp is a shortcut for SimpleDateFormat string 'yyyyMMddHHmmssSSS'.

  • $sequence$

    This is a monotonically increasing counter. A different counter is maintained for each delivery exchange. A Message Handler rule uses a single global counter.

  • $any legal Java SimpleDateFormat string$

userDefinedDuplicateFilename.description:
You can set Duplicate file renaming by entering a renaming pattern in the Pattern field. The patterns that you can enter in this field are similar to the renaming patterns listed for userDefinedDeliveryFilename, with the following differences:
  • You must include $filename$.

  • You must enter at least one of the following elements, in order to ensure that a unique name is generated for the duplicate:
    • $sequence$

      This is the sequence number calculated from all delivery file names handled on all deliveries

    • $timestamp$

    • $filesequence$

      This variable is only allowed in the duplicate file naming case (not the file naming case above). It is calculated from only the file names handled on the specific delivery where you set the pattern. It is recommended that you use $sequence$ instead of $filesequence$ because $filesequence$ consumes greater processing resources.

    • $any legal Java SimpleDateFormat string$

requiresSecureAuthentication.description:
For OFTP V2 only, this is an extra layer of security to enable senders and receivers to validate each other as genuine. There are two requirements to enable secure OFTP authentication:

  • Both the sender and receiver must enable secure OFTP authentication. If one party turns it on and the other party does not, a protocol error is generated and the session between the parties is disconnected.
  • Both the sender and receiver must be using certificates. These are the normal certificates used by a community and its partners to securely exchange messages. These are not TLS certificates, which are additional certificates needed if TLS is configured for a delivery exchange.
This is how the authentication works: The initiator of the connection uses the partners public key to encrypt and send a short, random message to the partner. The partner decrypts the message with its private key and sends the message back. The initiator compares the response to the original message. If the messages match, the initiator has authenticated the partner. The partner repeats the process to validate the initiator.

secureAuthCertificateId.description:
The ID of the partner certificate used for secure authentication. This ID is shown only when another certificate
than the default one is used. <p/>

useDifferentAuthCertificate.description:
Set this to true in order to select a partner certificate to use for secure authentication other than the default
certificate. <p/>

xml_ns0_exchangePointScheduleBean.description:
Used to set times for making a pickup or delivery exchange inactive while keeping the transport in an enabled state.
For example, you could set a schedule to turn off the exchange for a few hours once a week to perform maintenance on a transport server.</br>
By default exchanges are active continuously. Schedules are added by day of the week and time of day.
For instance, if you select Monday 0:00 - 23:59, the exchange is on all day every Monday.
If you select Monday 8:30 - 11:30, the exchange is on from 8:30 to 11:30 a.m. and off all other times on Mondays.</br>
Times are expressed in 24-hour format: hh:mm or h:mm. Times are the time zone for your server.</br>
If you schedule down times for a pickup used by a community to receive messages from partners, you may want to inform partners when the transport is inactive.</br>
If you want an exchange to be active most of the time but turned off only some of the time, you may need many schedules specifying the daily times you want
the transport to be on or off. For example, to schedule a transport to turn off between 1 and 2 p.m. each Saturday, eight schedules are needed as follows:
six daily schedules calling for the transport to run continuously Sunday through Friday and two Saturday schedules, the first specifying the transport
is on from midnight to 1 p.m. and the second specifying the transport is on from 2 p.m. to midnight.</br>
Messages in queue when a transport turns off are suspended until the transport turns back on. For example, if a message is picked up from an application
while the transport for sending to a partner is turned off, Message Tracker reports the status for the message as "scheduled production."
When the transport turns on again, processing of the message continues. Similarly, retries and resends for messages are suspended while the transport is off,
but they resume at the point where they were suspended when the transport turns back on.</br>
To use schedules, make sure message backups are enabled for the affected transports.
Unless backups are enabled, messages in process when a transport turns off cannot be queued to resume processing when the transport turns on again.</br>
If you trade via the AS2 message protocol and request asynchronous receipts, your community cannot receive receipts from partners
when the sending transport is turned off. To avoid this, request synchronous receipts or schedule a transport to be off when no messages are in process.

deliveryFilenameMode.description:
This property is used when the trading engine delivers messages.

Ftp Delivery Filename Options:
  • Preserve original

    Select this option if you want original file names to be preserved when the trading engine delivers messages.
  • Auto generate

    If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine appends a number to the new file. For FTP and SFTP the appended number is hexadecimal, with the format: filename_c4.
  • Custom generate

    When this flag is used, the additional property userDefinedDeliveryFilename must be set.

duplicateFileNameMode.description:
We recommend using this option to prevent the trading engine from attempting to retrieve partially written files.There may be some specialized servers, typically running on mainframes, that support only part of the FTP protocol (RFC 959). In such cases you may have to take steps of your own to make sure collisions do not occur. Ftp Duplicate File Name Options:
  • Overwrite

    If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine overwrites the existing file.
  • Auto generate

    Automatically generate unique filenames
  • Append

    If duplicate file names are detected, the trading engine appends a number to the new file. For FTP and SFTP the appended number is hexadecimal, with the format: filename_c4.
  • Custom generate

    When this flag is used, the additional property userDefinedDuplicateFilename must be set.

this is the receivers ID.

To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

name.description: The name of the argument. This is a read-only field.

type.description: The type of the argument. This is a read-only field.

acceptGroups.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

Select this option if you want to accept group segments.

authCode.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

A value representing additional identification or authorization of the interchange sender or the data in the interchange (ISA02). This is an interchange envelope parameter. The type of information is set by the Authorization code qualifier (ISA01).

authCodeQualifier.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

A code identifying the type of information in the authorization information (ISA01). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

compositeElementSeperator.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

Enter the character to use as the composite element separator (ISA16). The field uses a colon as the default value. Alternately, you can use a hex code.

elementSeperator.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

Enter the character to use as the element separator. The field uses an asterisk as the default value. Alternately, you can use a hex code.

envelopeTimeout.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

The envelope timeout in hours and minutes. The 24-hour format is HH:MM, where HH is from 00 to 23 and MM is from 00 to 59.

groupAckWaitTime.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

The time in hours and minutes to wait for receiving acknowledgments. If not received within this time, the transmission is regarded as faulty. The 24-hour format is HH:MM, where HH is from 00 to 23 and MM is from 00 to 59.

groupTimeout.description: When acceptGroups is true, specify the time limit in hours and minutes before groups time out. The 24-hour format is HH:MM.

groupTimeoutAction.description:
When acceptGroups is true, specify the action to perform if group messages are missing. The accepted values are:
  • SEND_AND_WARN
  • SEND
  • STOP

interchangeControlNumberGenerator.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The data interchange information code control number. This is the starting value of unique identifiers for outbound messages. By default, the identifier increases by 1 for each additional message (ISA13). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

interchangeControlVersion.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The information code version number. This covers all current interchange control segments (ISA12). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

maxNumbDocs.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

The largest number of documents the envelope can contain.

repetitionSeperator.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

The repetition separator character for the repeating element (ISA11). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

request997Acks.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

Select this option if the an acknowledgement to the outbound message is required.

requestTa1Acks.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

Select this option to request an interchange acknowledgment (TA1) (ISA14). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

securityCode.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

Security information about the interchange sender or the data in the interchange (ISA04). This is an interchange envelope parameter. The type of information is set by the Security code qualifier (ISA03).

securityCodeQualifier.description:
Enabled for Interchange and group level processing mode only.

A code identifying the type of information in the security information (ISA03). This is an interchange envelope parameter.

segmentSeperator.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

Enter the character to use as the segment separator. The field uses the hex code \H0A as the default value.

transSetControlNumbGenerator.description:
Enabled for both X12 processing modes.

A control number assigned by the sender and stored in the transaction set header. The number must be unique in the functional group (ST02).

useEventType.description: Enables event type for detection / matching.

useMessageStructure.description: Enables message structure for detection / matching.

primary.description:
Specify whether this messaging id is used as default for identifying the associated partner at message level.
A default messaging id can be configured for each message standard that can be exchanged by a specific partner.

name.description: The name of the messaging id.

routingId.description: RoutingId derived from this MessagingId.  Used for display purposes and by Integrator/pmServer.

client.description: The IDOC client. The maximum length of this field is 3.

ediStandardFlag.description: The EDI standard flag. The maximum length of this field is 1.

ediVersion.description: The EDI version. The maximum length of this field is 6.

partnerNumberReceiver.description: The partner number of the receiver (RCVPRN). This is a read-only field.

partnerNumberSender.description: The partner number of the sender (SNDPRN). This is a read-only field.

partnerPortReceiver.description: The port of the receiver (RCVPOR). This is a read-only field.

partnerPortSender.description: The port of the sender (SNDPOR). This is a read-only field.

partnerTypeReceiver.description: The partner type of the receiver (RCVPRT). This is a read-only field.

partnerTypeSender.description: The partner type of the sender (SNDPRT). This is a read-only field.

testIndicator.description: Specify if the Agreement is for testing or for production.

mpc.description:
Message Partition Channels (MPCs) allow for partitioning the flow of messages from an MSH (Messaging Service
Handler) to another MSH into separate flows, so that each one of these flows can be controlled independently by
either MSH, in terms of transfer priorities.

batchRejectionRule.description: The action to take when the batch is rejected.

fileRejectionRule.description: The action to take when a file is rejected.

useFileIdModifier.description: use the file id modifier field

partnerId.description: The destination partner name. This is used when outputType is set to USE_ALTERNATE_DELIVERY_PARTNER.

routingId.description: A Routing ID belonging to the destination partner.

deliveryId.description: The ID of the partner delivery to use as the delivery to the destination partner.

bgmDocNameCode.description: The BGM name code for which this document agreement is used. If detectBGMContent is true, this identification field will be used for matching/selection.

detectBGMContent.description: Select this option if you want to use this document agreement only on a specific BGM content type.

allocationSizePercentage.description:
Destination file size delta for transformed files (+/- in %) - If you configure an "on the fly" transformation,
you can use this setting to adjust the file size info sent with the PeSIT CREATE order. That is because the
"on the fly" transformation changes the file size while sending. If no transformation is configured, this value
is ignored.  <p/>

bufferSize.description:
Max data unit size in bytes (PI25): The largest chunk of data, in bytes, to be transferred at one time. For
high-speed networks, use the default 32700 bytes. This value is related to the client setting for record length.
<p/>
The value of this field must be the same or larger than the value of the record length field.

callerIdentification.description: Holds the caller's protocol identity (P13) and password requirements. <p/>

compressionType.description:
Compression (PI21) - Controls the compression of the file during the transfer (compression on the fly). Select a compression method:

  • NONE

    No compression. (default)

  • HORIZONTAL

    Compresses the consecutive identical characters in the records.

  • Vertical

    Records are compared to one another and the consecutive identical columns are compressed.

  • BOTH

    Combination of the above two compression methods.

connectTimeoutSeconds.description: The maximum time in seconds to wait for a reply from the server before disconnecting.

connectionTimeoutSecs.description: PeSIT Tc timeout. The time the caller waits for a connection acknowledgment from the server. <p/>

customFilename.description: File label (PI37) - Logical name of the file. It is used when overwriteFileLabel is set to true. <p/>

dataEncoding.description:
Data encoding (PI16)

  • TEXT

    Used for ASCII files

  • BINARY

    Used for all other file types

enableAcks.description:
Expect acknowledgments - this should be true if you expect the remote application or partner to send a receipt to
acknowledge receiving each message sent.  <p/>

fileName.description:
File name (PI12) - Name of the file, forced to uppercase at runtime. Often, the real name of the file is delivered in
in File label (customFilename).

fileType.description: The file type (PI11) - Some monitors use this. The default value is 0.  <p/>

finalDestinationEnabled.description:
Use the final destination ID from the message - Set to true on an Application Delivery to have the trading engine
read pesit.finalDestinationId.out (which corresponds to PI62), and use it as PI4. When set to false on an Application
Delivery, the Remote Identification should have restrictedToId set to true and an identifier set. <p/>
This value should be false for Partner Delivery.

host.description:
The IP address or the network name of the trading partner PeSIT server to connect to. This must be the fully
qualified domain name or IP address of the PeSIT server your community connects to for sending messages.<p/>

kbPerSyncPoint.description:
Intervals between sync points (Kbytes): Each time an amount of data equal to this value has been sent, the
client is expected to ask the server to confirm whether data totaling this value has been received. This represents
a check point in the progress of a file transfer. If a connection is lost before a file transfer has been
completed, the transfer resumes (upon restart of the transport) at the point of the last successful check point. <p/>
The default value is 1024 kilobytes (1 megabyte).  <p/>
This setting corresponds to the pacing setting in Axway Transfer CFT. <p/>

maxOutstandingSyncPoints.description:
Sync acknowledgement window: The number of check-point cycles that the client waits for the server to respond
to a request to confirm file-transfer progress. For example, if the value of Kb per sync point (pacing) is 1024
(1 megabyte) and the value of this field is 1, the client stops sending data after 1024 kilobytes unless the
server responds, although the transfer remains active.  <p/>
If this value is 2, the client keeps sending until 2 megabytes (1024 x 2) of data  are sent, and so on. <p/>
If the client's value for this field is 0 (zero), the client does not ask the server to confirm at intervals the
amount of data received.  <p/>
If the server's value for this field is 0, the server does not send confirmations at intervals of data received.
The default value is 3. In most situation this is the correct value. <p/>
This setting corresponds to the chkw setting in Axway Transfer CFT.

networkTimeoutSecs.description:
PeSIT Tr timeout. The time the caller waits for an expected and effective network disconnection, before forcing
it. <p/>

overrideCommunitySettings.description:
Controls whether to override the community settings in a Partner Delivery. For Application Delivery this value
should be false. <p/>

port.description: The port on which the partner PeSIT server listens for connection requests.<p/>

priority.description:
Priority (PI17) - Select an option:

  • HIGH

    Highest priority

  • MEDIUM

    Default

  • LOW

    Lowest priority

protocolTimeoutSecs.description:
PeSIT Tp timeout. The time the caller waits for the response of the remote, in the middle of a protocol action
(such as a transfer). <p/>

readTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits to read data from the delivery exchange before terminating the
connection.<p/>

recordFormat.description:
Record format (PI31). Select one of the following:

  • FIXED

    For fixed length records

  • VARIABLE

    For variable length records

recordLength.description: Record length (PI32) - Record length for fixed records, or maximum record length for variable records.  <p/>

serverIdentification.description:
Holds the partner server's protocol identity (PI4) and password requirements.  <p/>
For Application Delivery you must then enter a specific identifier for PI4 if finalDestinationEnabled flag is set to false. This value must
correspond to the value used by the application to identify the server. <p/>

serviceParam.description: Free text (PI99) - Any text string. Often it is used to transfer metadata. <p/>

supportNegativeAcknowledgement.description: If expect acknowledgements is enabled, set this to true to support negative acknowledgements. <p/>

transferTimeoutSecs.description: PeSIT Td timeout. The time the caller keeps the connection open, waiting for another message to send.  <p/>

identification.description:
Unique identification string used for partner identification at message level and to help control
message processing. For an outbound message, this is the sender's ID and for an inbound message,
this is the receivers ID.

useEnvelopingProfile.description:
Set to one of the following:

  • true - Deliver using defined outbound agreement(s)

    Select this option if you want to specify an outbound agreement to use for the output delivery.

  • false - Deliver using best matching outbound agreement

    Select this option if you want to let B2Bi select the outbound agreement to link to this agreement. The trading engine selects the best matching agreement from the available agreements. If no matching outbound agreement is found, a message is generated to Message Log.

outboundAgreements.description: The outbound agreement configuration to use for output delivery.

outputType.description:
Select one of the following:

  • USE_INBOUND_RECEIVER - Use inbound agreement receiver as delivery partner

    This is the default behavior of the document agreement.

  • USE_ALTERNATE_DELIVERY_PARTNER

    Select this option if you want to specify a partner (other than the inbound agreement receiver) as the destination of outbound messages. The partner you select must have a valid Routing ID and a delivery exchange defined.

  • USE_OUTBOUND_AGREEMENT

    Select this option to link the document agreement to an outbound agreement.

  • USE_NONE

    This option is the default when the Service used by the owning Document Agreement delivers to an Application. It can be selected only when the Service delivers to Application or when the Service delivers to Partner but the Agreement has no explicit receiver.

name.description: The name of the Document Agreement Output. This cannot be modified.

emailAddress.description:
The email address of this SMTP user. Once created, it cannot be changed. The email address allows wildcards:
  • ? - matches any character
  • * - matches any characters occurring zero or more times
Examples: user@host.com; *@host.com; ??user@*.com.

Message Partition Channels (MPCs) allow for partitioning the flow of messages from an MSH (Messaging Service
Handler) to another MSH into separate flows, so that each one of these flows can be controlled independently by
either MSH, in terms of transfer priorities.

email.description: The email address of the contact

bufferSize.description:
Max data unit size in bytes (PI25) - The largest of chunk of data, in bytes, to be transferred at one
time. For high-speed networks, use the default 32700 bytes. This value is related to the client setting
for record length.
<p/>
The value of this field must be the same or larger than the value of the record length field.

cipherSuites.description:
The specific cipher suites supported by the server. If empty, all cipher suites are supported by
default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain cipher suites. The default order in
the list is the preferred order of use.
<p/>
A cipher suite is a collection of security algorithms used in making connections via Secure Sockets
Layer or Transport Layer Security. For example, an SSL or TLS protocol requires signing messages using
a message digest algorithm. But the choice of algorithm is determined by the particular cipher suite
being used for the connection. Typically, you can select an MD5 or SHA digest algorithm.

connectTimeoutSeconds.description:
Connection timeout (seconds) - Time in seconds the trading engine waits for a connection to the delivery
exchange before the attempt times out. Although the default value is 30 seconds, this may be longer
than the interval allowed by your operating system (OS). For example, Windows XP by default allows a
maximum timeout of 20 seconds. The actual connect timeout interval is the lesser of the OS timeout and
the value set in the trading engine.

enableClientAuthenticatedSsl.description:
Select this option if you require the client to authenticate itself with its own certificate when
connecting (mutual authentication). This means you must import the client's certificate to the
community's personal certificate list. If you want to use the pickup for multiple communities, you must
import the same certificate to each community

kbPerSyncPoint.description:
Interval between sync points (Kbytes) - Each time an amount of data equal to this value has been sent, the client is expected to ask the server to confirm whether data totaling this value has been received. The server responds optionally with a confirmation. This represents a check point in the progress of a file transfer. If a connection is lost before a file transfer has been completed, the transfer resumes, upon restart of the transport, at the point of the last successful check point.

The default value is 1024 kilobytes (1 megabyte). Do not change this value unless advised by the administrator of the component.

localPort.description: The port on which the embedded server listens for connection requests.

maxOutstandingSyncPoints.description:
Max outstanding sync points - This controls how many check point cycles the client waits for the server to respond to a request to confirm file-transfer progress. For example, if the value of Kb per sync point (pacing) is 1024 (1 megabyte) and the value of this field is 1, the client stops sending data after 1024 kilobytes unless the server responds, although the transfer remains active. If this value is 2, the client keeps sending until 2 megabytes (1024 x 2) of data are sent, and so on.

If the client's value for this field is 0 (zero), the client does not ask the server to confirm at intervals the amount of data received. If the server's value for this field is 0, the server does not send confirmations at intervals of data received.

The default value is 3. Do not change this value unless advised by the administrator of the component.

maxThreads.description: Maximum threads - The most threads can dedicate to the server.

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Specify whether the cipher suites supported by the server are stated, in order for you select the level of security that suits your needs and enables communicating with others who might have different security requirements.

For example, when an SSL connection is established, the client and server exchange information about the cipher suites they have in common. Then they communicate using the common cipher suite that offers the highest level of security. If they do not have a cipher suite in common, secure communication is not possible. If this option is set to false, all cipher suites are supported by default.

errors on the client side. Setting this too high may cause tread pool depletion on the trading engine

To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

requiresSecureAuthentication.description:
For OFTP V2 only, this is an extra layer of security to enable senders and receivers to validate each other as genuine. There are two requirements to enable secure OFTP authentication
  • Both the sender and receiver must enable secure OFTP authentication. If one party turns it on and the other party does not, a protocol error is generated and the session between the parties is disconnected.
  • Both the sender and receiver must be using certificates. These are the normal certificates used by a community and its partners to securely exchange messages. These are not TLS certificates, which are additional certificates needed if TLS is configured for a delivery exchange.

      • This is how the authentication works:

      1. The initiator of the connection uses the partner's public key to encrypt and send a short, random message to the partner.
      2. The partner decrypts the message with its private key and sends the message back.
      3. The initiator compares the response to the original message. If the messages match, the initiator has authenticated the partner.
      4. The partner repeats the process to validate the initiator.

  • 1 - ASCII 7 bit
  • 2 - ASCII 8 bit

  • 4 - Code page 850 (IBM PC Multinational)
  • 5 - UCS-2
  • 6 - UCS-4
  • 7 - UTF-8
  • 8 - UTF-16
  • ZZZ - Mutually agreed between trading partners

The results should respect the pagination values passed to it, but also should return the ENTIRE count of the results. For example, if a request is called to get all remote parties, the limit of the returned response might be 10 results in the collection but there may be 5000 total remote parties. The count value is necessary to clients such as a UI to build there page bar.

retries.description:
This is the number of times the trading engine will retry connecting to the partner's transport if the initial attempt to connect and send the message failed. The following are common reasons for triggering retries. The connection attempt failed immediately for a reason such as host not found.
  • The connection attempt failed immediately for a reason such as host not found.
  • The host was found, but the connection process took longer than the connect timeout interval specified.
  • The connection was successful, but the partner's HTTP server took longer than the response timeout interval to return a 200 OK response indicating the message was successfully received.

postProcessingScript.description:
The full path to an executable file that contains post-processing commands. This field is available for
community integration delivery exchanges and partner trading delivery exchanges.

holdMessagesForPickup.description: Get if all outbound messages sent over this exchange are held for remote pickup. Applies for the moment only for PeSIT exchange point. The default value is set to false.

useCustomRetryIntervals.description: Specifies if a customized retry schedule should be used.

customRetryIntervals.description: Interval delays on each subsequent retry expressed in minutes. Example: 5,10,15,30,60.

customComponentId.description: The id of the processing step to handle the processing for this custom delivery.

readTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits to read data from the delivery exchange before terminating
the connection.

enableRestarts.description:
Specify whether checkpoint-restart is enabled. A checkpoint is information saved to disk that is a
recovery point in the event of a transport failure.
<p/>
The restart program uses the last saved checkpoint and
starts again, ensuring no loss of data. To reduce unnecessary overhead when processing small files,
checkpoint files are only created for messages that are at least 100 KB in size.

enableChunking.description:
Specify whether chunking messages is enabled. A chunked message is a large message broken into smaller
pieces for sending to a partner over the Internet or to back-end integration.
<p/>
Although primarily used for handling large messages, chunking can also be enabled for small messages.
You should perform tests to determine whether a partner's server can handle chunked messages.

connectTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits for a connection to the delivery exchange before the attempt times out.
<p/>
Although the default value is 30 seconds, this may be longer than the interval allowed by your operating
system. For example, Windows XP by default allows a maximum timeout of 20 seconds. The actual connect timeout
interval is the lesser of the operating system timeout and the value set in the trading engine.

responseTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits for the delivery exchange to respond to a request
before terminating the connection.

enable102Processing.description:
Specify whether 102-processing is enabled. If this option is set to true, it is ensured that the connection between the client and server does not become idle and fail while message processing is in progress.

For example, this makes sure the connection remains active when the client is sending a multi-gigabyte message. Most often this setting is useful when the client requests a synchronous receipt, but is also recommended in some cases for an asynchronous receipt. Before selecting this option, make sure the server supports 102 responses.

cipherSuites.description:
The specific cipher suites supported by the server. If empty, all cipher suites are supported by
default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain cipher suites.
The default order in the list is the preferred order of use.
<p/>
A cipher suite is a collection of security algorithms used in making connections via Secure Sockets Layer or
Transport Layer Security. For example, an SSL or TLS protocol requires the signing of messages using a message digest
algorithm. The choice of algorithm is determined by the particular cipher suite being used for the
connection. Typically, you can select an MD5 or SHA digest algorithm.

ssl.description: Specify whether Secure Sockets Layer protocol is in use during connections. If this option is set to true, the server presents a certificate for verification. To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Specify whether the cipher suites supported by the server are stated, to enable communication with partners who might have different security requirements.

For example, when an SSL connection is established, the client and server exchange information about the cipher suites they have in common. Then they communicate using the common cipher suite that offers the highest level of security. If they do not have a cipher suite in common, secure communication is not possible. If this option is set to false, all cipher suites are supported by default.

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: User name and password to connect to the server.

proxy.description:

the proxy is located between the trading engine and the partner's HTTP server.

defaultMetadataTemplate.description:
A reference to a metadata template in the system, that is applied when a message is received. If the
metadata template isn't anymore in the system, we just log a warn a message.

enabledByProtocol.description: Indicates if the exchange point supports metadata template passed through the protocol.

metadataTemplatePolicy.description:
This option is available only for OFTP and PeSIT exchanges. You can specify the template name in the file name of the message submitted by the sender or by the setting defaultMetadataTemplate property
Indicates the way to deal with metadata template, it allows 3 values :
  • always : Apply MMT provided by protocol. If unknown, the transfer is refused.
  • ifKnown : Apply MMT provided by protocol if it is known, else apply the default MMT (if set).
  • never : Ignore the MMT provided by the protocol. Always apply the default MMT (if set).

priorityOverFixedAttributes.description:
Indicates if the metadata template has priority than the fixed message attributes. In case the metadata
template has priority then we first apply the metadata defined in the message attributes then we apply the
metadata template ones (if there's a conflict between the same metadata, the metadata template one
wins) and vice versa.
