including standard EDI or custom formats that include special characters or spaces.

cipherSuites.description: List with cipher suites.

connectTimeoutSeconds.description: Time in seconds the trading engine waits for a connection to the delivery exchange before the attempt times out. The default value is 30 seconds. Required.

emailAddress.description: The email address for sending messages to a partner.

enableHostnameVerification.description:
SSL authentication.  If we're acting as the client, true means we should verify that the
hostname for the certificate given to us by the server matches the host we connected to.
If we're acting as the server, true means we require the client to present its
certificate ("client authentication").

host.description:
The SMTP server for sending messages to the specified partner. You must provide a fully qualified domain name or IP
address for the server. If you leave this field blank, the system inserts its external SMTP server.

overrideCipherSuites.description: If true, a list of cipher suites should be provided.

port.description: The port used for sending messages to the specified partner. The default values is 25.

readTimeoutSeconds.description: Time in seconds the trading engine waits to read data from the delivery exchange before terminating the connection. Required.

ssl.description: client use ssl to connect to this server ?

useGlobalSmtp.description:
Specify whether the system's external SMTP server is used to send messages to the partner.
Otherwise, you can specify a different external SMTP server to send messages to the partner.

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: User name and password to connect to the server. Usually, SMTP servers do not require user names and passwords for sending messages.

enveloperId.description: The ID of the service to be used for enveloping outbound In-House documents.

testFlag.description: Set this field to true if the agreement is for testing and not for production.

id.description: Functional group identifier

name.description: Functional group name

xml_ns0_x25NetworkSettingsBean.title: x25NetworkSettingsBean

packetSize.description: The size of the X.25 packet. If the value is blank the networks default value is used.

windowSize.description:
The number of X.25 packets that can be sent without acknowledgment.
If the value is blank the networks default value is used.

xml_ns0_x25NetworkSettingsBean.description: An ITU-T standard protocol suite for packet-switched wide area network communications

localPort.description:
The local port used by the embedded FTP server to listen for incoming connections.
The default value is 4021 for the trading server and 5021 for the application server.

modifyFtpServerDirectory.description: Enable subdirectory management on the client side.

sequenced.description:
Specify whether all messages that are consumed by this pickup should be delivered in their original
consumption order.
<p/>
In B2Bi message-handling, sequential delivery is the ability to deliver messages in the order they
were originally consumed on a specific pickup. This is sometimes referred to as first-in-first-out
(FIFO) behavior.
<p/>
Sequential message delivery is implemented only for trading engine pickups, not for integration
engine pickups

sequenceTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds that B2Bi waits for missing messages of a sequence before taking the appropriate action.
This feature avoids the blocking of processing when a sequenced message is not available. Default value is of
60 seconds.

defaultUser.description: The default ftp account used by the FTP embedded server.

useRFC2204.description: For OFTP V1 only when protocol version is 1.3, this check box tells the trading engine the protocol release level (SSIDLEV) to use for the trading partner. If this option is true, the partner uses the RFC 2204 implementation. This means the SSIDLEV field in the start session (SSID) command has a value of 1. Set this option to false if the partner uses the RFC 5024 implementation. This means the SSIDLEV field in the SSID command has a value of 2. Note that in either case the exchange point is being defined for OFTP protocol revision level 1.3.

cipherSuites.description:
The specific cipher suites supported by the server. If empty, all cipher suites are supported by
default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain cipher suites.
The default order in the list is the preferred order of use.
<p/>
A cipher suite is a collection of security algorithms used in making connections via Secure Sockets Layer or
Transport Layer Security. For example, an SSL or TLS protocol requires the signing of messages using a message digest
algorithm. The choice of algorithm is determined by the particular cipher suite being used for the
connection. Typically, you can select an MD5 or SHA digest algorithm.

connectTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits for a connection to the delivery exchange before the attempt times out.
Although the default value is 30 seconds, this may be longer than the interval allowed by your operating system.
For example, Windows XP by default allows a maximum timeout of 20 seconds. The actual connect timeout interval
is the lesser of the operating system timeout and the value set in the trading engine.

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Specify whether the cipher suites supported by the server are stated, in order for you select the level of security that suits your needs and enables communicating with others who might have different security requirements.

For example, when an SSL connection is established, the client and server exchange information about the cipher suites they have in common. Then they communicate using the common cipher suite that offers the highest level of security. If they do not have a cipher suite in common, secure communication is not possible. If this option is set to false, all cipher suites are supported by default.

readTimeoutSeconds.description: Time in seconds the trading engine waits to read data from the delivery exchange before terminating the connection.

responseTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits for the delivery exchange to respond to a request before terminating the
connection.

ssl.description: Specify whether Secure Sockets Layer protocol is in use during connections. If this option is set to true, the server presents a certificate for verification. To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

localPort.description: The port on which the embedded server listens for connection requests.

bufferSize.description:
Max data unit size in bytes (PI25) - The largest of chunk of data, in bytes, to be transferred at one
time. For high-speed networks, use the default 32700 bytes. This value is related to the client setting
for record length.
<p/>
The value of this field must be the same or larger than the value of the record length field.

cipherSuites.description:
The specific cipher suites supported by the server. If empty, all cipher suites are supported by
default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain cipher suites. The default order in
the list is the preferred order of use.
<p/>
A cipher suite is a collection of security algorithms used in making connections via Secure Sockets
Layer or Transport Layer Security. For example, an SSL or TLS protocol requires signing messages using
a message digest algorithm. But the choice of algorithm is determined by the particular cipher suite
being used for the connection. Typically, you can select an MD5 or SHA digest algorithm.

connectTimeoutSeconds.description:
Connection timeout (seconds) - Time in seconds the trading engine waits for a connection to the delivery
exchange before the attempt times out. Although the default value is 30 seconds, this may be longer
than the interval allowed by your operating system (OS). For example, Windows XP by default allows a
maximum timeout of 20 seconds. The actual connect timeout interval is the lesser of the OS timeout and
the value set in the trading engine.

ssl.description: Specify whether Secure Sockets Layer protocol is in use during connections. If this option is set to true, the server presents a certificate for verification. To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

kbPerSyncPoint.description:
Interval between sync points (Kbytes) - Each time an amount of data equal to this value has been sent, the client is expected to ask the server to confirm whether data totaling this value has been received. The server responds optionally with a confirmation. This represents a check point in the progress of a file transfer. If a connection is lost before a file transfer has been completed, the transfer resumes, upon restart of the transport, at the point of the last successful check point.

The default value is 1024 kilobytes (1 megabyte). Do not change this value unless advised by the administrator of the component.

maxOutstandingSyncPoints.description:
Max outstanding sync points - This controls how many check point cycles the client waits for the server to respond to a request to confirm file-transfer progress. For example, if the value of Kb per sync point (pacing) is 1024 (1 megabyte) and the value of this field is 1, the client stops sending data after 1024 kilobytes unless the server responds, although the transfer remains active. If this value is 2, the client keeps sending until 2 megabytes (1024 x 2) of data are sent, and so on.

If the client's value for this field is 0 (zero), the client does not ask the server to confirm at intervals the amount of data received. If the server's value for this field is 0, the server does not send confirmations at intervals of data received.

The default value is 3. Do not change this value unless advised by the administrator of the component.

maxThreads.description: Maximum threads - The most threads can dedicate to the server.

minThreads.description: Minimum threads - The least number of threads must dedicate to the server.

networkTimeoutSeconds.description: Network timeout (seconds) - Time in seconds the network times out

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Specify whether the cipher suites supported by the server are stated, in order for you select the level of security that suits your needs and enables communicating with others who might have different security requirements.

For example, when an SSL connection is established, the client and server exchange information about the cipher suites they have in common. Then they communicate using the common cipher suite that offers the highest level of security. If they do not have a cipher suite in common, secure communication is not possible. If this option is set to false, all cipher suites are supported by default.

protocolTimeoutSeconds.description: Protocol timeout (seconds) - Time in seconds the protocol times out.

serverTimeoutSeconds.description:
Server timeout (seconds) - Controls how long the server waits after receiving a file to see if the
client is going to be sending another file on the same session. Setting this too low may cause abort
errors on the client side. Setting this too high may cause tread pool depletion on the trading engine
side.

transferTimeoutSeconds.description: Transfer timeout - server mode (seconds) - Time in seconds a transfer times out.

enableClientAuthenticatedSsl.description:
Select this option if you require the client to authenticate itself with its own certificate when
connecting (mutual authentication). This means you must import the client's certificate to the
community's personal certificate list. If you want to use the pickup for multiple communities, you must
import the same certificate to each community

certificate.description: Path to get the certificate for this server. <p/>

localPort.description: The local port used by the embedded HTTP server to listen for incoming connections. The default value is 4080.

ssl.description: Specify whether Secure Sockets Layer protocol is in use during connections. If this option is set to true, the server presents a certificate for verification. To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

sequenced.description:
Specify whether all messages that are consumed by this pickup should be delivered in their original
consumption order.
<p/>
In B2Bi message-handling, sequential delivery is the ability to deliver messages in the order they
were originally consumed on a specific pickup. This is sometimes referred to as first-in-first-out
(FIFO) behavior.
<p/>
Sequential message delivery is implemented only for trading engine pickups, not for integration
engine pickups

sequenceTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds that B2Bi waits for missing messages of a sequence before taking the appropriate action.
This feature avoids the blocking of processing when a sequenced message is not available. Default value is
60 seconds.

path.description:
The last component of the path that partners will use to send messages to this server.
A good choice for this value would be one of the community's routing IDs.
The path to the HTTP server must be unique.

syncResponseGenInBackend.description:
Synchronous response generated in back end - Select this option to have the back-end application generate
synchronous responses. If this option is not selected, the synchronous response is generated within the trading
engine. By default, this option is not selected.

friendlyName.description:
A user-defined name for a certificate.  <p/>
Naming the certificate can help identify the community or partner it belongs to.

fingerprint.description:
Fingerprints are a way to verify the source of a certificate. After you import or export a certificate, you can
contact your partner and ensure the fingerprints at both ends are identical. Do this before attempting to
exchange documents. If the fingerprints do not match, one of the certificates might be corrupted or out of date. <p/>

keyId.description: The keyId is string identifier for the PGP Certificate.

keyAlgorithm.description: An algorithm identifier that specifies the public key crypto system this key belongs to and any associated key parameters, such as key length <p/>

keyLength.description: Key length indicates encryption strength, the larger the number the stronger the key. <p/>

validFrom.description: The date the certificate became valid. <p/>

validTo.description: The date the certificate expires, provided it is not compromised or revoked before that date. <p/>

publicKeys.description:
The Public Key is what its name suggests - Public. It is made available
to everyone via a publicly accessible repository or directory. On the other hand,
the Private Key must remain confidential to its respective owner.

signatures.description: A digital signature certifies and timestamps a document

ackDeliveryExchangeId.description:
The ID of the delivery exchange used for handling the delivery of the acknowledgements. This information is
needed when an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements is selected.

ackTransportReceiverId.description: The ID of the partner selected as the receiving party of the acknowledgement. This information is needed when an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements is selected and the overrideAckTransportReceiver field is set to true.

ackTransportReceiverRoutingId.description: The ID of the Routing Id of the partner selected as the receiving party of the acknowledgement. This information is needed when an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements is selected and the overrideAckTransportReceiver field is set to true.

bypassEdiProcessing.description: Specify whether all other inbound processing options are unavailable. If this option is set to true, the performance of B2Bi is improved when handling large interchanges. The trading engine handles incoming interchanges without unpacking the envelopes. The trading engine reads only the interchange header and transaction set header segment (ST). The entire interchange is sent to the map as a single message. Regular EDI logic is not applied. For this reason, no acknowledgements can be automatically generated and sent. It is not required to have a map in the service attached to this agreement. This enables the trading engine to pass an entire interchange to the next application without modification. If the service that is attached to the agreement contains a map, the documents contained in the interchange must all be of the same type and same version.

documentServiceId.description:
The ID of the Service used for generating acknowledgements. This information is needed when an
acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements is selected.

dupAction.description:
The action to take for duplicate numbers, when the dupCheckControlNumbs field is set to true. The following options are available:
  • WARN_AND_PROCESS - allows an inbound interchange to be processed successfully, with a logged warning
  • FAIL_AND_PARK - processing is halted and an error is logged

dupCheckControlNumbs.description: Specify whether the interchange control numbers are checked for duplicates by comparing to interchanges already received. If a duplicate is detected for an inbound interchange, the dupAction is respected.

dupCheckGroupControlNumbs.description: Specify whether the interchange group control numbers are checked for duplicates by comparing to interchanges already received. If a duplicate is detected for an inbound interchange group , the dupAction is respected.

generateAckRule.description:
The condition for sending acknowledgments. The available options are:
  • NEVER (default) - no acknowledgement is generated
  • ON_REQUEST - acknowledgments must be requested when an integration is set up.
  • ALWAYS - acknowledgments are always sent.
  • IF_ERRORS - acknowledgements are sent only when errors are detected

generateAckType.description:
The type of the EDIFACT acknowledgement. This information is needed when an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements is selected. The following options are available:
  • CONTROL_EANCOM_D93A
  • CONTROL_EANCOM_D96A
  • CONTROL_UN_EDIEL_2
  • CONTROL_UN_2
  • CONTROL_UN_2_1
  • CONTROL_UN_2_2
  • CONTROL_UN_3
  • CONTROL_UN_4
  • CONTROL_EDIG_S_3_2
  • CONTROL_EDIG_S_4

outOfSeqAction.description:
The action to take for non-sequential numbers, when the seqCheckControlNumbs field is set to true. The following options are available:
  • WARN_AND_PROCESS - allows an inbound interchange to be processed successfully, with a logged warning
  • FAIL_AND_PARK - processing is halted and an error is logged

outboundAgreementForAckEnvelopeId.description:
The ID of the outbound agreement used for enveloping the acknowledgement. This information is needed when an
acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements is selected.

overrideAckTransportReceiver.description: Specify whether you want to identify a specific party as the receiving party of the acknowledgement. If this option is set to false, the receiver that is specified in the selected outbound agreement is used as the receiving delivery partner of the acknowledgement. This information is needed when an acknowledgement rule that generates acknowledgements is selected.

rejectionRule.description:
The condition for rejecting interchanges. Interchanges are rejected depending on where errors are found. For example, if there is an error in one transaction set, the whole interchange is rejected. The available options are:
  • NONE
  • ENTIRE_INTERCHANGE
  • SAME_TYPE
  • CUSTOM_TYPE

seqCheckControlNumbs.description: Specify whether the interchange control number for inbound messages is verified to be in sequence. For example, if the user sets the next expected interchange control number to 123456, the system validates the next inbound document has an interchange control number of 123456. If the validation succeeds, the field is updated to 123457. If the validation fails, the outOfSequence action is respected.

seqCheckGroupControlNumbs.description: Specify whether the interchange group control number for inbound messages is verified to be in sequence. For example, if the user sets the next expected interchange group control number to 123456, the system validates the next inbound document has an interchange control number of 123456. If the validation succeeds, the field is updated to 123457. If the validation fails, the outOfSeqAction is respected.

useApplicationReference.description: Specify whether the applicationReference field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useCommunicationAgreementId.description: Specify whether the communicationAgreementId field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useIdCodeQualifierReceiver.description: Specify whether the idCodeQualifierReceiver field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useIdCodeQualifierSender.description: Specify whether the idCodeQualifierSender field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

usePartnerIdInternalIdReceiver.description: Specify whether the partnerIdInternalIdReceiver field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

usePartnerIdInternalIdSender.description: Specify whether the partnerIdInternalIdSender field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

usePartnerIdInternalSubIdReceiver.description: Specify whether the partnerIdInternalSubIdReceiver field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

usePartnerIdInternalSubIdSender.description: Specify whether the partnerIdInternalSubIdSender field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

usePartnerIdReceiver.description: Specify whether the partnerIdReceiver field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

usePartnerIdSender.description: Specify whether the partnerIdSender field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useSyntaxIdentifier.description: Specify whether the syntaxIdentifier field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useSyntaxVersion.description: Specify whether the syntaxVersion field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

useTestIndicator.description: Specify whether the testIndicator field is used for matching/selection at runtime.

receiverIdentification.description: The receiver partner's messaging ID. </br> This is a read-only field.

senderIdentification.description: The sender partner's messaging ID. </br> This is a read-only field.

host.description:
The IP address or the network name of the back-end PeSIT server to poll. This must be the fully
qualified domain name or IP address of the PeSIT server

port.description: The Port on which the back-end PeSIT server listens.

remotePesitExchangePointId.description:
Select the partner delivery exchange / application delivery, if any are available. When used, caller and server identifications are automatically filled on the trading side.
Note: Only Pesit exchanges from partners on same community with this exchange are allowed
Note: On integration, an application delivery on same community can be selected, or for special use (for example, 3rd party monitoring), another one can be used too.

ssl.description:
Select this option If the backend server is configured to transfer over SSL/TLS.
You must import the root certificate of the remote server to the community trusted SSL root certificates.

enableHostnameVerification.description: If you select this option, the trading engine verifies that the name of the server is the same as the name in the server's certificate. This requires that you import the server certificate chain in the community's personal certificates and then select the option Trust this for SSL server and/or client authentication. The trading engine automatically adds the root certificate to the linked community's trusted SSLroot certificates.

enableCftComptatibility.description:
When you select this option, B2Bi aligns the PeSIT record size on TLS packets.
This is the only method handled by Axway Transfer CFT before version 3.0,
and is the default method for the Axway products Gateway and Interpel.

overrideCipherSuites.description: Optionally, set to true in order to override the default cipher suites.  <p/>

cipherSuites.description: List of cipher suites to be used. <p/>

acknowledgementExpected.description: Select this option if the polled back-end server expects an acknowledgment for each file fetched.

callerIdentification.description: Holds the caller's protocol identity (P13) and password requirements. Note: This field is automatically filled on trading part

serverIdentification.description:
Holds the partner server's protocol identity (PI4) and password requirements.
Note: This field is automatically filled on trading part

fileName.description:
File name (PI12) - Name of the file, forced to uppercase at runtime. Often, the real name of the file is shipped
in File label (customFileName).

fileType.description: The file type (PI11), which is used by some monitors. The default value is 0.

compressionType.description:
Compression (PI21) - Controls the compression of the file during the transfer (compression on the fly). Select a compression method:
  • NONE No compression. (default)
  • HORIZONTAL Compresses the consecutive identical characters in the records.
  • Vertical Records are compared to one another and the consecutive identical columns are compressed.
  • BOTH Combination of the above two compression methods.

priority.description:
Priority (PI17) - Select an option:
  • HIGH Highest priority
  • MEDIUM Default
  • LOW Lowest priority

serviceParam.description: Free text (PI99), often used to transfer metadata.

bufferSize.description:
Max data unit size in bytes (PI25): The largest chunk of data, in bytes, to be transferred at one time. For
high-speed networks, use the default 32700 bytes. This value is related to the client setting for record length.

The value of this field must be the same or larger than the value of the record length field.

kbPerSyncPoint.description:
Intervals between sync points (Kbytes): Each time an amount of data equal to this value has been sent, the
client is expected to ask the server to confirm whether data totaling this value has been received. This represents
a check point in the progress of a file transfer. If a connection is lost before a file transfer has been
completed, the transfer resumes, upon restart of the transport, at the point of the last successful check point.
The default value is 1024 kilobytes (1 megabyte).
This setting corresponds to the pacing setting in Axway Transfer CFT.

maxOutstandingSyncPoints.description:
Sync acknowledgement window: The number of check-point cycles that the client waits for the server to respond
to a request to confirm file-transfer progress. For example, if the value of Kb per sync point (pacing) is 1024
(1 megabyte) and the value of this field is 1, the client stops sending data after 1024 kilobytes unless the
server responds, although the transfer remains active.
If this value is 2, the client keeps sending until 2 megabytes (1024 x 2) of data  are sent, and so on.
If the client's value for this field is 0 (zero), the client does not ask the server to confirm at intervals the
amount of data received.
If the server's value for this field is 0, the server does not send confirmations at intervals of data received.
The default value is 3. In most situation this is the correct value.
This setting corresponds to chkw setting in Axway Transfer CFT.

readTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds the trading engine waits to read data from the delivery exchange before terminating the
connection.

connectionTimeoutSeconds.description: PeSIT Tc timeout. The time the caller waits for a connection acknowledgment from the server.

transferTimeoutSeconds.description: PeSIT Td timeout. The time the caller keeps the connection open, waiting for another message to send.

networkTimeoutSeconds.description:
PeSIT Tr timeout. The time the caller waits for an expected and effective network disconnection, before forcing
it.

protocolTimeoutSeconds.description:
PeSIT Tp timeout. The time the caller waits for the response of the remote, in the middle of a protocol action
(such as a transfer).

disableNagleAlgorithm.description:
Select this option to disable Nagle's algorithm on the underlying TCP connection used by the PeSIT protocol.
Disable Nagle's algorithm to enhance transfer speed or enable it to reduce overhead of the transferred packet data.

clientModeEnabled.description:
The MQSeries connection type. Two options are available:
  • true - select this option to use a channel connection on the local machine or via the network, to connect to a queue manager.
  • false select this option to use an API connection, via shared memory, to a local queue manager.

convertUsingCCSID.description: Enable this option if you want to convert the characters set of messages received from the queue to the set specified in the 'mqCharset' field. Set to false if you want to turn off data conversion.

maxMessagesPerConnection.description:
This value specifies the maximum number of messages to be consumed over a single connection before the connection
is closed and reopened on another processing node. As such, this setting effectively controls load balancing. The
default setting of 1 achieves optimal load balancing at the cost of greater overhead per message. Depending on your
message volume and the load on each node, this value could be increased to avoid the overhead associated with
reconnecting to the transport server, at the cost  of a less well-balanced cluster.

mqCharset.description: The character set for converting data.

mqPort.description: The MQSeries port number. The default port is 1414.

mqQueueName.description: The name of the MQSeries queue that receives incoming documents.

multiInstanceEnabled.description: Select this option if you are using an MQSeries multi-instance queue manager.

segmentationSize.description: The message segmentation size in bytes.

sequenceTimeoutSeconds.description: Value of sequence timeout in seconds.

sequenced.description:
Set this option to true if you want all messages that are consumed by this pickup to be delivered in their
original consumption order.

sslCipherSuite.description: The SSL cipher suite to use for SSL encryption.

useSsl.description: Use SSL to connect to the MQSeries server.

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: User name and password to connect to the server.

friendlyName.description: The friendly name for the global external server. Read-only.

host.description: Fully qualified domain name or IP address for the global external server, which is used by default for sending e-mail messages. Required.

id.description: The unique ID of the global external server.

port.description: The port used by the global external server. The default values is 25. Required.

ssl.description: Regular or secured channel with authentication.

usernamePasswordCredentials.description: User name and password to connect to the server. Usually, SMTP servers do not require user names and passwords for sending messages.

xml_ns0_inlineProcessorBean.title: inlineProcessorBean

description.description: Documentation for this user defined functionality

parameters.description: Parameters for user defined java class

xml_ns0_inlineProcessorBean.description:
The extensible architecture of the trading engine enables system integrators to apply custom logic to in-process messages
as an integral part of the processing pipeline. You can selectively apply the custom processing logic to inbound or outbound
messages at runtime, implemented as a user-defined Java class .

json_ApiException.title: ApiException
json_ApiException.description:
Base class for all API exceptions.  Any class that extends this will automatically get mapped to the correct
HTTP return code and the exception message will be populated in the response body.

defaultUser.description: Default account for the SFTP server.

deleteAfterDownload.description: Specify whether the embedded server should delete files after they have been downloaded from it.

localPort.description:
The local port used by the embedded SFTP server to listen for incoming connections. The default values are 4022
for a trading server and 5022 for an application server.

modifySftpServerDirectory.description: Specify whether subdirectory management is enabled on the client side. When this option is set to true, SFTP clients are allowed to add or remove subdirectories.

overwriteIfDuplicate.description:
Specify whether when the trading engine detects a duplicate file name, it should overwrite the existing file,
replacing it with the duplicate file.

preserveFilename.description:
Specify whether the original file names should be preserved when the trading engine delivers messages.
Preserving original file names enables your back-end application to process binary messages based on their
file names.

enveloperId.description: ID of the service to be used for enveloping outbound XML documents.

testFlag.description: Set this field to true if the agreement is for testing and not for production.

transmissionCode.description:
An EAN location number (GLN) identifying the transmission sender
(FROM code) or the transmission receiver (UNTO code). The interchange parties can agree
upon the code. The value must be 14 or fewer alphanumeric characters.

transmissionName.description:
Identifies in plain language the transmission sender (FROM name) or the transmission receiver (UNTO name).
The interchange parties can agree upon the name. This value must be 35 or fewer alphanumeric characters.

parameters.description:
Define the parameter string to be passed for a specific type of B2Bi exchange point. For more information about
the specific parameters to be passed for each type of B2Bi exchange point, please see the admin guide.

type.description: The type of the B2Bi exchange point.

definitionName.description:
Name to be displayed in the UI wizard for selecting a transport.
This name will be displayed along with built-in transport names such as "Ftp", "File system", etc.
For consistency with existing names, use an initial capital letter, and no period at the end.

settings.description: Defines setting string to be passed to the implementation class when a pluggable transport is created

type.description:
The type of the current processing step. This field can have one of the following four values:
  • Document
  • Post enveloping
  • Post transfer success
  • Post transfer failed

stepId.description: The current processing step to be configured.

defaultEncryptionCertificateId.description: ID of the specified partner's default certificate for encrypting the documents you send to ensure secure trading.

name.description: Agreement name

enabled.description: Returns if this agreement is enabled.

receiverMessagingId.description:
Receiving partner's message routing ID </br> When null messagingId, routingId will be [ALL] for
inbound, [DEFAULT] for outbound

communityId.description: Community this agreement is linked to

communityRoutingId.description: If the community has multiple routing IDs, you must supply a routing ID

agreementAttributes.description: List with all attributes for current agreement

agreementAttributesTemplate.description: List with all template attributes for agreements

documentAgreementAttributesTemplate.description: List with all template attributes for document agreements

senderIdentification.description: The sender partner's messaging ID. </br> This is a read-only field.

receiverIdentification.description: The receiver partner's messaging ID. </br> This is a read-only field.

applicationReference.description: The application on the receiver's network to which the interchange is directed (0026). For example, a value of %IN% indicates the CONTRL message should use the value of the application reference of the incoming interchange.

communicationsAgreementId.description: Any communications agreements that control the exchange of data (0032).

idCodeQualifierReceiver.description: The interchange recipient's partner identification code qualifier (S003 0007). This is a read-only field.

idCodeQualifierSender.description: The interchange sender's partner identification code qualifier (S002 0007). This is a read-only field.

partnerIdIntSubReceiver.description: The interchange recipient's interchange recipient internal sub-identification (S003 0046). This is a read-only field.

partnerIdIntSubSender.description: The interchange sender's interchange sender internal sub-identification (S002 0042). This is a read-only field.

partnerIdInternalIdReceiver.description: The interchange recipient's routing address (S003 0014). This is a read-only field.

partnerIdInternalIdSender.description: The interchange sender's address for reverse routing (S002 0008). This is a read-only field.

partnerIdReceiver.description: The interchange recipient's identification (S003 0010). This is a read-only field.

partnerIdSender.description: The interchange sender's identification (S002 0004). This is a read-only field.

syntaxGroup.description: The appropriate syntax to use for messages.

syntaxIdentifier.description: The agency controlling the syntax and the character repertoire used in an interchange (S001 0001). Each identity consists of the letters UN followed by two letters identifying the character repertoire.

testIndicator.description: Indicates that the structural level containing the test indicator is a test (0035).

useFunctionalGroups.description:
When one or more transaction sets are received from a trading partner in an interchange, the transaction sets may
be grouped in functional groups within the envelope. Transactions sets that are grouped together are identified
by the same functional group ID. Within the inbound agreement, you can add functional group agreements to specify
the valid functional group IDs to be verified for exchanges that may be performed between the selected trading
partners.

customRetryIntervals.description: Interval delays on each subsequent retry expressed in minutes. Example: 5,10,15,30,60.

holdMessagesForPickup.description: Get if all outbound messages sent over this exchange are held for remote pickup. Applies for the moment only for PeSIT exchange point. The default value is set to false.

postProcessingScript.description:
The full path to an executable file that contains post-processing commands. This field is available for
community integration delivery exchanges and partner trading delivery exchanges.

retries.description:
This is the number of times the trading engine will retry connecting to the partner's transport if the initial attempt to connect and send the message failed. The following are common reasons for triggering retries. The connection attempt failed immediately for a reason such as host not found.
  • The connection attempt failed immediately for a reason such as host not found.
  • The host was found, but the connection process took longer than the connect timeout interval specified.
  • The connection was successful, but the partner's HTTP server took longer than the response timeout interval to return a 200 OK response indicating the message was successfully received.

useCustomRetryIntervals.description: Specifies if a customized retry schedule should be used.

xml_ns0_isdnNetworkSettingsBean.title: isdnNetworkSettingsBean

bandwidthLimitedTo56k.description:
Select this when a provider uses 56 kbps-bit transparent operation
with byte-framing from the network as its physical layer protocol
instead of the default 64-kbps with HDLC framing. For such cases,
this check box must be selected for the ISDN connection to be properly established.

highestIncomingChannel.description: The highest value for the incoming channels identifiers counter. If blank, use the networks default value.

highestOutgoingChannel.description: The highest value for the outgoing channels identifiers counter. If blank, use the networks default value.

highestTwoWayChannel.description: The highest value for the two-way channels identifiers counter. If blank, use the networks default value.

layer2WindowSize.description:
Specifies how many layer 2 (ISO 7776) packets can be sent
before an acknowledgment is required from the partner. If blank, use the networks default value.

layer3PacketSize.description: Specifies the size of the layer 3 packets. If blank, use the networks default value.

layer3WindowSize.description:
Specifies how many layer 3 (ISO 8208) packets can be sent
before an acknowledgment is required from the partner. If blank, use the networks default value.

lowestIncomingChannel.description: The starting value for the incoming channels identifiers counter. If blank, use the networks default value.

lowestOutgoingChannel.description: The starting value for the outgoing channels identifiers counter. If blank, use the networks default value.

lowestTwoWayChannel.description: The starting value for the two-way channels identifiers counter. If blank, use the networks default value.

xml_ns0_isdnNetworkSettingsBean.description: Integrated Services Digital Network broadband channel supports data transfers over telephone networks

customComponentId.description: The id of the processing step to handle the processing for this custom delivery.

customDeliveryComponent.description: Reference to an custom delivery registry object.

acceptGroups.description: Specify whether group segments are accepted.

ackTimeout.description: The time limit in hours and minutes to wait for receipt of acknowledgments. The 24-hour format is HH:MM.

charEncodingCoded.description:
The coded identification of the character encoding used in the interchange (S001 0133). The available options are:
  • 1 - ASCII 7 bit
  • 2 - ASCII 8 bit
  • 3 - Code page 500 (EBCDIC Multinational No. 5)
  • 4 - Code page 850 (IBM PC Multinational)
  • 5 - UCS-2
  • 6 - UCS-4
  • 7 - UTF-8
  • 8 - UTF-16
  • ZZZ - Mutually agreed between trading partners

componentElementSeparator.description: The component element separator value matching the EDIFACT document. It can be either a character or a hex value with the \H prefix.

controlReferenceGenerator.description: This value describes how a unique ID is generated, in order to identify each transmission.

decimalMark.description: The decimal mark value matching the EDIFACT document. It can be either a character or a hex value with the \H prefix.

documentControlNumberGenerator.description: This value describes how to generate the message reference number (0062 generator).

elementSeparator.description: The element separator value matching the EDIFACT document. It can be either a character or a hex value with the \H prefix.

envelopeTimeout.description: The envelope timeout in hours and minutes. The 24-hour format is HH:MM.

forceGenerateUNA.description: Specify whether the UNA segment is added to the envelope.

groupTimeout.description: The time limit in hours and minutes before groups time out (when group segments are accepted). The 24-hour format is HH:MM.

groupTimeoutAction.description:
The action to perform if group messages are missing (when group segments are accepted). The available options are:
  • SEND_AND_WARN
  • SEND
  • STOP

maxNumbDocs.description: The largest number of documents the envelope can contain.

processingPriorityCode.description:
A code used to request a processing priority for the interchange (0029). The code is specified in the
parties' interchange agreement.

recipientRefPasswordQualifier.description:
The qualifier for the receiver's password or reference (S005 0025). The use of the qualifier is
specified in the partners' interchange agreement.

releaseChar.description: The release character value matching the EDIFACT document. It can be either a character or a hex value with the \H prefix.

repeatingElementSeparator.description: The repeating element separator matching the EDIFACT document. It can be either a character or a hex value with the \H prefix.

requestAcks.description: Specify whether acknowledgments for messages are requested.

segmentSeparator.description: The segment separator value matching the EDIFACT document. It can be either a character or a hex value with the \H prefix.

serviceCodeDirNumber.description: The version of the service code list directory to use to define encoded EDIFACT values (S001 0080).

useDefaultSyntax.description:
Specify whether the default values of the version displayed in the syntax version field are used. Alternatively, custom values in decimal or hex code format can be provided for the following fields:
  • componentElementSeparator
  • elementSeparator
  • decimalMark
  • releaseChar
  • segmentSeparator

cipherSuites.description:
The specific cipher suites supported by the server. If empty, all cipher suites are supported by
default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain cipher suites.
The default order in the list is the preferred order of use.
<p/>
A cipher suite is a collection of security algorithms used in making connections via Secure Sockets Layer or
Transport Layer Security. For example, an SSL or TLS protocol requires signing messages using a message digest
algorithm. But the choice of algorithm is determined by the particular cipher suite being used for the
connection. Typically, you can select an MD5 or SHA digest algorithm.

enableClientAuthenticatedSsl.description: Specify whether the partners certificate should be used for authentication when the partner connects to the server, when using SSL option is enabled. If this option is set to true, partners are required to present a certificate for identity verification trusted by the server before the delivery exchanges using this server allow the connection and you must add an authentication certificate for the partner. If this option is set to false, non-authenticated HTTPS is used.

localPort.description: The port on which the embedded server listens for connection requests.

maxLingerTimeSeconds.description:
The amount of time in seconds the connection is kept open after it is closed.
A negative number (-1) indicates that the connection should not be kept open after it is closed

maxThreads.description: The maximum number of threads the trading engine can dedicate to the server.

minThreads.description: The least number of threads the trading engine must dedicate to the server.

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Specify whether the cipher suites supported by the server are stated, in order for you select the level of security that suits your needs and enables communicating with others who might have different security requirements.

For example, when an SSL connection is established, the client and server exchange information about the cipher suites they have in common. Then they communicate using the common cipher suite that offers the highest level of security. If they do not have a cipher suite in common, secure communication is not possible. If this option is set to false, all cipher suites are supported by default.

restartableMinKiloBytes.description:
The minimum size of a file that triggers the system to continue the file transfer at the point where it was
interrupted before the connection was lost. The minimum size is in kilobytes. The system only resumes
transfers of files that meet this minimum. The system starts over the transfer of smaller files whose
processing is interrupted.

shouldSubmitCertificate.description: Used for hiding the SSL server certificate URI; true if the entity was newly persisted and false otherwise

ssl.description: Specify whether Secure Sockets Layer protocol is in use during connections. If this option is set to true, the server presents a certificate for verification. To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

tempFileHoursToLive.description:
The number of hours the system retains a file whose transfer has been interrupted while waiting for the
connection to be restored, if restart attempts are made.
This temporary file enables the system to resume the transfer at the point where it was interrupted.

compareOperator.description:
Operator which specifies the relationship between the attribute name (metadataName) and the provided value (metadataValue). You can define attributes to be active only when certain conditions occur. This lets you customize attributes to a high degree of specificity. You can choose one of the following operators:
  • EQUALS - the operator tests whether an attribute exists and has a specific value
  • NOT_EQUALS - the operator tests whether an attribute exists, but does not match a specific value
Conditions cause payloads to be delivered to the appropriate application delivery. If a payload does not satisfy the delivery criteria for any application delivery, then the first available application delivery is used. An application delivery with no criteria is used only if it is the first one available.

metadataName.description:
The name of the message attribute used for attaching metadata to the messages the trading engine picks up
from applications or receives from partners.
<p/>
Attributes are name-value pairs whose values are extracted from messages through parsing or have
fixed values. The trading engine can parse only XML messages, but attributes with fixed values can
apply to EDI, XML or binary documents.
For example, you can have the system parse certain XML messages for values of an attribute named
POAmount. Or, you can instruct the system to apply an attribute named SupplyChain with a fixed
value of Retail to certain messages.

metadataValue.description:
The value of the message attribute used for attaching metadata to the messages the trading engine picks up
from applications or receives from partners.

groupAttachments.description:
Group Attachments - Select this option to enable the consumed message to be split into parent and dependent
child messages.

shouldIntegrateAttachments.description: Process Attachments - Select this option to process the attachments of the SOAP message.

shouldIntegrateBody.description: Process SOAP Body - Select this option to process the contents of the SOAP body.

shouldParseMetadataFromHeader.description:
Parse SOAP headers into message metadata - Select this option if you want to SOAP headers to be carried as
metadata attributes with the message.

xpaths.description: If shouldParseMetadataFromHeader is selected, enter the XPath expressions to resolve the header.

parameters.description:
Define the parameter string to be passed for a specific type of B2Bi exchange point. For more information about the
specific parameters to be passed for each type of B2Bi exchange point, please see the admin guide.

type.description: The type of the B2Bi exchange point.

useSyntaxRuleId.description: Enable syntax rule identification for detection / matching.

useSyntaxRuleVersion.description: Enable syntax rule version for detection / matching.

useApplicationReference.description: Enable application reference for detection / matching.

usePriorityCode.description: Enable transmission priority code for detection / matching.

recipientTransmisionReference.description: Receiver Reference (Out_ReceiverReference). Transmission reference ID of the receiver.

useSenderTransmissionCode.description: Enable sender identification code for detection / matching.

useReceiverTransmissionCode.description: Enable receiver identification code for detection / matching.

useSenderTransmissionName.description: Enable sender identification name for detection / matching.

useReceiverTransmissionName.description: Enable receiver identification name for detection / matching.

documentAgreements.description: List with all document agreements for current agreement.

certificateState.description:
Indicates whether the certificate can be used. Valid states are:

  • PENDING
  • OPERATIONAL
  • EXPIRED
  • FAILED
  • REVOKED
  • UNKNOWN

certificateUsage.description:
Describes the functions that the certificate can perform. The intended usage does not mean the certificate is being used for that purpose, only that it can be used for it.

  • ENCRYPTION
  • VERIFICATION
  • ANY
  • OTHER
  • NON_REPUDIATION
  • DIGITAL_SIGNATURE

friendlyName.description:
A user-defined name for a certificate.  <p/>
Naming the certificate can help identify the community or partner it belongs to.

id.description: ID of this certificate.

issuer.description: The name of the person or entity that issued the certificate.<p/>

issuerId.description:
The issuer is the X.500 distinguished name of the CA or entity that signed the certificate. <p/>
In cases of a self-signed certificate, the issuer and subject are the same.
Using the certificate implies trusting the signer.

issuerUniqueId.description: Gets the issuerUniqueID value from the certificate. The issuer unique identifier is present in the certificate to handle the possibility of reuse of issuer names over time.

keyUsage.description: Identifies the purpose of the key in the certificate, such as encipherment, digital signature or certificate signing. <p/>

md5Fingerprint.description:
Fingerprints are a way to verify the source of a certificate. After you import or export a certificate, you can
contact your partner and ensure the MD5 fingerprints at both ends are identical. Do this before attempting to
exchange documents. If the fingerprints do not match, one of the certificates might be corrupted or out of date. <p/>

publicKey.description: Public key which is used to encrypt messages before sending. <p/>

publicKeyAlgorithm.description: An algorithm identifier that specifies the public key crypto system this key belongs to and any associated key parameters, such as key length <p/>

publicKeyExtensions.description: Extensions used to store additional information regarding the certificate holder and to define certificate usage. <p/>

publicKeyLength.description: Key length indicates encryption strength, the larger the number the stronger the key. <p/>

selfSigned.description:
Self-signed certificates are easily created. The primary disadvantage is lack of
verification by a trusted third party.

serialNumber.description:
The serial number uniquely identifies the certificate.  <p/>
The CA or entity that issued the certificate assigned this number. <p/>
If the issuer revokes a certificate, it can place the serial number on a certificate revocation (CRL) list.

sha1Fingerprint.description:
Fingerprints are a way to verify the source of a certificate. After you import or export a certificate, you can
contact your partner and ensure the SHA1 fingerprints at both ends are identical. Do this before attempting to
exchange documents. If the fingerprints do not match, one of the certificates might be corrupted or out of date. <p/>

signatureAlgorithm.description: The algorithm the CA used to sign the certificate. <p/>

subject.description: The name of person or entity who was issued the certificate. <p/>

subjectUniqueId.description:
The subject key identifier extension provides a means of identifying
certificates that contain a particular public key.

validFrom.description: The date the certificate became valid. <p/>

validTo.description: The date the certificate expires, provided it is not compromised or revoked before that date. <p/>

x509Version.description: The version of the X.509 standard that applies to the certificate <p/>

SSID.description:
SSID identification code - The start session identification (SSID) of the local or remote party. Trading partners
exchange SSIDs to identify each other in the protocol handshake and session setup.   <p/>

connectTimeoutSeconds.description:
Connect timeout (seconds) - Time in seconds the trading engine waits for a connection to the delivery exchange
before the attempt times out. Although the default value is 30 seconds, this may be longer than the interval
allowed by your operating system (OS). For example, Windows XP by default allows a maximum timeout of 20 seconds.
The actual connect timeout interval is the lesser of the OS timeout and the value set in the trading engine. <p/>

creditCounter.description:
Credit counter - The number of consecutive data exchange buffers sent by the speaker before it must wait for a
credit (CDT) command from the listener. The credit value is only applied to data flow in the data transfer phase.
The speaker's available credit is initialized to SSIDCRED when it receives a start file positive answer (SFPA)
command from the listener. It is zeroed by the end file (EFID) command. After negotiation, the smallest size must
be selected in the answer of the responder or a protocol error aborts the session.  <p/>

dataExchangeBuffer.description:
Data exchange buffer - The length in octets of the largest acceptable data exchange buffer. The length includes
the command octet, but not the stream transmission header. After negotiation, the smallest size is selected.
The value in this field maps to the SSIDSDEB field in the SSID OFTP protocol command. <p/>

enableHostNameVerification.description:
Enable host name verification - If selected, the trading engine compares the name of the TLS server to the name
in the server's certificate to ensure they are the same.<p/>

localSSIDOverride.description:
If overrideSsidAndPassword is set to true, this SSID must be set. This SSID will be used instead of the one from
the community's OFTP delivery exchange. <p/>

localSSIDPasswordOverride.description:
Entering an override password is optional. This password overrides the password in the field named "This server
requires a session password", which is an optional field for a community OFTP delivery exchange. <p/>

networkSettings.description:
The Network Settings for this Exchange Point. The network settings on an OFTP Exchange Point must be one of the
following type: TCP, X25, ISDN.<p/>

overrideSsidAndPassword.description:
Set this to true in order to have this partner exchange use an SSID code and password different than the values
set on a community's OFTP delivery exchange. <p/>

readTimeoutSeconds.description: Read timeout (seconds) - The maximum number of seconds the server waits when reading data from a partner. <p/>

sessionPassword.description: The OFTP session password -  The password can be no longer than eight alphanumeric characters and is case sensitive. <p/>

useSessionPassword.description:
Set OFTP session password - If set to true, the partner must present this password to your community. The password
is compared to the one your community has stored for the partner. <p/>

version.description:
OFTP Protocol version.

    For Odette FTP V1

  • VERSION_1_3
  • VERSION_1_4
    • For Odette FTP V2:
  • VERSION_2_0

attachmentsOnly.description:
Set this option to true to eliminate extraneous message fragments. This option is applicable when the
partners send messages using a mail client such as Microsoft Outlook. It is available under the generic email
message protocol, but not AS1.

When a partner uses a mail client application to send a trading document as an attachment to an email message,
the trading engine actually receives two or more documents. These can include the MIME header, the text of the
email message and the document attachment. The trading engine tracks and processes the incidental MIME body parts
just as it does any document. Although such processing does no harm, it can cause confusion.	Setting this option
to true causes the incidental MIME body parts to be ignored while preserving the important document attachments.

emailAddress.description: The email address that the remote partners use to send messages to the local community.

localPort.description:
The local port used by the embedded SMTP server to listen for incoming connections.
The default value is 4026.

senderIdentificationType.description:
Specify how the sender will be identified; must be set to 'PD_EMAIL_ADDRESSES' or
'PARTNER_EMAIL_ACCOUNTS'.

sequenceTimeoutSeconds.description: Value of sequence timeout in seconds. <p/>

sequenced.description:
Set this option to true if you want all messages that are consumed by this pickup to be delivered in their
original consumption order. <p/>

enabled.description: Specify whether the party is enabled.

partyName.description: The friendly name for the specified party.

defaultRoutingId.description:
The default Routing Id for the specified party. A Routing Id is a unique identifier that the trading engine uses as the "to" and "from" address for e-commerce messages exchanged over the Internet. Routing Ids are used for party identification at transport level. A Routing Id can be in any format or length (up to 255 characters), including standard EDI or custom formats that include special characters or spaces.

Although a community or partner can have many Routing Ids, the user interface designates one per community or partner as the default. Default Routing Ids are used by default for message protocol headers when packaging messages. For example, when packaging an AS2 message the default Routing Ids are used for as2-to and as2-from attributes in headers, regardless of the Routing Ids parsed from the payload.

countryCode.description: The country code for the specified party which indicates its location. The format is [ISO code]-[Country name]. For a list of codes see the Website for ISO (International Organization for Standardization): http://www.iso.org/iso/home.html.

routingIds.description: The Routing Ids used by the party.

primaryContact.description:
The principal contact person for the party and the corresponding email address. You can provide
additional information, including a phone number, email and notes about the contact.

contacts.description: The list of contacts with the primary contact first.

WSUsers.description: The list of Web Services users defined on this party.

fingerprint.description:
Fingerprints are a way to verify the source of a certificate. After you import or export a certificate, you can
contact your partner and ensure the fingerprints at both ends are identical. Do this before attempting to
exchange documents. If the fingerprints do not match, one of the certificates might be corrupted or out of date. <p/>

friendlyName.description:
A user-defined name for a certificate.  <p/>
Naming the certificate can help identify the community or partner it belongs to.

id.description: ID of this certificate.

keyAlgorithm.description: An algorithm identifier that specifies the public key crypto system this key belongs to and any associated key parameters, such as key length <p/>

keyId.description: The keyId is string identifier for the PGP Certificate.

keyLength.description: Key length indicates encryption strength, the larger the number the stronger the key. <p/>

publicKeys.description:
The Public Key is what its name suggests - Public. It is made available
to everyone via a publicly accessible repository or directory. On the other hand,
the Private Key must remain confidential to its respective owner.

signatures.description: A digital signature certifies and timestamps a document

validFrom.description: The date the certificate became valid. <p/>

validTo.description: The date the certificate expires, provided it is not compromised or revoked before that date. <p/>

applicationNamespaceId.description:
This field uniquely identifies the namespace ID (IS) of the sending application (MSH-00003) among all other applications within the network enterprise.
This field uniquely identifies the namespace ID (IS) of the receiving application (MSH-0005) among all other applications within the network enterprise.
The network enterprise consists of all those applications that participate in the exchange of HL7 messages within the enterprise. Entirely site-defined.

applicationUniversalId.description:
This field uniquely identifies the universal ID (ST) of the sending application (MSH-00003) among all other applications within the network enterprise.
This field uniquely identifies the universal ID (ST) of the receiving application (MSH-0005) among all other applications within the network enterprise.
The network enterprise consists of all those applications that participate in the exchange of HL7 messages within the enterprise. Entirely site-defined.

applicationUniversalIdType.description:
This field uniquely identifies the universal ID type (ID) of the sending application (MSH-00003) among all other applications within the network enterprise.
This field uniquely identifies the universal ID type (ID) of the receiving application (MSH-0005) among all other applications within the network enterprise.
The network enterprise consists of all those applications that participate in the exchange of HL7 messages within the enterprise. Entirely site-defined.

facilityNamespaceId.description:
This field uniquely identifies the namespace ID (IS) of the sending facility (MSH-00004). This field contains the address of one of several occurrences of
the same application within the sending system. Absent other considerations, the Medicare Provider ID might be used with an appropriate sub-identifier in the second component. Entirely user-defined.
<p/>
This field uniquely identifies the namespace ID (IS) of the receiving facility (MSH-00006). This field identifies the receiving application among multiple
identical instances of the application running on behalf of different organizations. Entirely site-defined

facilityUniversalId.description:
This field uniquely identifies the universal ID (ST) of the sending facility (MSH-00004). This field contains the address of one of several occurrences of
the same application within the sending system. Absent other considerations, the Medicare Provider ID might be used with an appropriate sub-identifier in the second component. Entirely user-defined.
<p/>
This field uniquely identifies the universal ID (ST) of the receiving facility (MSH-00006). This field identifies the receiving application among multiple
identical instances of the application running on behalf of different organizations. Entirely site-defined

facilityUniversalIdType.description:
This field uniquely identifies the universal ID type (ID) of the sending facility (MSH-00004). This field contains the address of one of several occurrences of
the same application within the sending system. Absent other considerations, the Medicare Provider ID might be used with an appropriate sub-identifier in the second component. Entirely user-defined.
<p/>
This field uniquely identifies the universal ID type (ID) of the receiving facility (MSH-00006). This field identifies the receiving application among multiple
identical instances of the application running on behalf of different organizations. Entirely site-defined

localPort.description: The local port used by the embedded HTTP server to listen for incoming connections. The default value is 4080.

path.description:
The last component of the path that partners will use to send messages to this server.
A good choice for this value would be one of the community's routing IDs.
The path to the HTTP server must be unique.

sequenceTimeoutSeconds.description:
Time in seconds that B2Bi waits for missing messages of a sequence before taking the appropriate action.
This feature avoids the blocking of processing when a sequenced message is not available. Default value is
60 seconds.

sequenced.description:
Specify whether all messages that are consumed by this pickup should be delivered in their original
consumption order.
<p/>
In B2Bi message-handling, sequential delivery is the ability to deliver messages in the order they
were originally consumed on a specific pickup. This is sometimes referred to as first-in-first-out
(FIFO) behavior.
<p/>
Sequential message delivery is implemented only for trading engine pickups, not for integration
engine pickups

ssl.description: Specify whether Secure Sockets Layer protocol is in use during connections. If this option is set to true, the server presents a certificate for verification. To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

syncResponseGenInBackend.description:
Synchronous response generated in back end - Select this option to have the back-end application generate
synchronous responses. If this option is not selected, the synchronous response is generated within the trading
engine. By default, this option is not selected.

localPort.description: The TCP port on which the embedded server listens for connection requests.

minThreads.description: The least number of threads the trading engine must dedicate to the server.

maxThreads.description: The most threads the trading engine can dedicate to the server.

startBlockCharacter.description:
The decimal byte value used to identify the start block character.
Start and stop block characters enclose the message data that is sent or received in through MLLP messages.
At runtime, B2Bi converts this decimal value to hexadecimal. The default value is 11 (hexadecimal B).
The default value is the customary MLLP value.
You must use the same values for the client and server sides of the MLLP exchange.

endBlockCharacter.description:
The decimal byte value used to identify the end block character.
Start and stop block characters enclose the message data that is sent or received in through MLLP messages.
At runtime, B2Bi converts this decimal value to hexadecimal.
The default value is 28 (hexadecimal 1C).
The default value is the customary MLLP value.
You must use the same values for the client and server sides of the MLLP exchange.

acknowledgementMode.description:
The option for sending acknowledgements. The following options are available for the acknowledgement mode:
  • NONE - Select this option to implement MLLP connections without acknowledgements.
  • MLLP - Select this option to enable transport-level acknowledgements for connections to this MLLP server.
  • SYNC_FROM_BACKEND Select this option if you want connections to this MLLP server kept open until an application acknowledgement is generated in the back end.

ssl.description: Specify whether Secure Sockets Layer protocol is in use during connections. If this option is set to true, the server presents a certificate for verification. To do this, the server must support SSL and a certificate in a profile must be designated as the SSL certificate. If this option is set to false, connections are not encrypted.

overrideCipherSuites.description:
Select the level of security that suits your need and enables communicating with others who might have different security requirements. For example, when an SSL connection is established, the client and server exchange information about cipher suites they have in common. Then they communicate using the common cipher suite that offers the highest level of security. If they do not have a chipper suite in common, secure communication is not possible.

If this option is set to false, all cipher suites are supported by default.

cipherSuites.description:
The specific cipher suites supported by the server. If empty, all cipher suites are supported by
default. The default is less secure than specifying only certain cipher suites.
The default order in the list is the preferred order of use.
<p/>
A cipher suite is a collection of security algorithms used in making connections via Secure Sockets Layer or
Transport Layer Security. For example, an SSL or TLS protocol requires signing messages using a message digest
algorithm. But the choice of algorithm is determined by the particular cipher suite being used for the
connection. Typically, you can select an MD5 or SHA digest algorithm.

enableClientAuthenticatedSsl.description: Specify whether the partners certificate should be used for authentication when the partner connects to the server using SSL. If this option is set to true, partners are required to present a certificate for identity verification trusted by the server before the delivery exchanges using this server allow the connection. You must add an authentication certificate for the partner. If this option is set to false, non-authenticated HTTPS is used.

certificate.description: The path to get the certificate for this server. <p/>

the called party is charged for the call instead of the caller (OFTP V1 X.25 only)

Custom data to send to the partner along with the call establishment request.
The data is only meaningful for the remote party. It is usually used to distinguish
between calls that are addressed to the same NUA.

port.description: The TCP port on which the server listens for connection requests. This field does not apply to OFTP V1 X.25.

characterSet.description:
Field used to filter messages to be handled by this agreement.
Character set options:
  • blank (any)
  • ASCII
  • ISO 8859-1 ISO/IEC Part 1 - Latin - 1 Western European
  • ISO 8859-2 ISO/IEC Part 2 - Latin - 2 Central European
  • ISO 8859-3 ISO/IEC Part 3 - Latin - 3 South European
  • ISO 8859-4 ISO/IEC Part 4 - Latin - 4 North European
  • ISO 8859-5 ISO/IEC Part 5 - Latin/Cyrillic
  • ISO 8859-6 ISO/IEC Part 6 - Latin/Arabic
  • ISO 8859-7 ISO/IEC Part 7 - Latin/Greek
  • ISO 8859-8 ISO/IEC Part 8 - Latin/Hebrew
  • ISO 8859-9 ISO/IEC Part 9 - Latin - 5 Turkish
  • ISO 8859-15 ISO/IEC Part 15 - Latin - 9 Western European
  • ISO IR14 Code for Information exchange
  • ISO IR87 Japanese Graphic Character set
  • ISO IR159 Supplementary Graphic Character set

processingId.description:

  • P Production
  • D Debugging
  • T Training

processingMode.description:
Field used to filter messages to be handled by this agreement.
Processing mode options:
